<BYLINE>Eds: ADDS Huebl and Branch; A separate moved as a0781 on Huebl.
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Frank Mingo</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank L. Mingo, chief executive of one of
the nation's largest black-owned advertising agencies, died Monday
after suffering a stroke. He was 49.
   Mingo spent more than 20 years in the advertising business,
working at McCann-Erickson, Inc. and J. Walter Thompson before
founding The Mingo Group in 1977.
   In 12 years, he built the firm from a small shop with four
employees and $600,000 in annual billings to an agency with a staff
of 50 and billings of $60 million. The agency's clients include
Miller Brewing Company, General Motors, the U.S. Army and Greyhound
Corp.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Milan Huebl</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milan Huebl, 62, who headed
Czechoslovakia's Communist Party Academy during the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms and later joined the independent human rights
group Charter 77, was found dead Saturday.
   The exact cause of his death was unknown.
   Huebl, a key ideologist of the communist-led reforms of
Alexander Dubcek that were crushed by a Soviet-led invasion, served
as director of the Communist Party Academy during that brief period.
   However, he was convicted in 1972 on charges of ``anti-state''
activities and sentenced to 6{ years in prison. He was released
early, in December 1976, with three other prominent activists.
   Huebl was one of the first people to sign the Charter 77
manifesto on human rights and more recently joined Obroda, a group
of former communists advocating reform.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Judson Branch</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judson R. Branch, former chairman of the Allstate
Insurance Co., died Monday after a long illness at age 82.
   Branch spent 38 years with Allstate. As one of the company's
first agents, he helped establish the revolutionary merchandising
idea of selling insurance over the counter at Sears Roebuck and Co.
stores. He was elected president and chief executive officer of the
company in 1957, and became chairman of the board in 1966.
</TEXT>
