<FIRST>u a AM-OwenCharged 1stLd-Writethru a0401 10-31 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Owen Charged, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0401,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former State Official, Two Other Charged With Making Illegal Donations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf to CORRECT charges against Kaplan.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEW FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former lieutenant governor was charged
Tuesday with violating the state's Campaign Finance Act by making
excessive contributions to Gov. Mike Hayden.
   Former Lt. Gov. David C. Owen, a former state senator and
longtime political aide of Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., was charged with
11 counts of exceeding campaign contribution limits by $26,500 and
making donations of $34,000 in the names of others.
   He also was charged by special prosecutors with four counts of
theft and one count each of criminal solicitation, conspiracy and
making a false writing.
   Owen said he found it ``appropriate that this witch hunt
culminated on Halloween,'' and charged the investigation was
politically motivated.
   He said he did not intentionally violate the law and pledged a
``vigorous defense'' to exonerate himself and ``establish the
motives of everyone involved in this investigation.''
   The charges stem from allegations by the Kansas Public
Disclosure Commission that Owen funneled money into Hayden's 1986
election campaign in excess of donation limits in effect at the
time.
   Also charged were John E. Palmer, an Overland Park businessman,
and Elliot M. Kaplan, a Kansas City, Mo., attorney. Palmer was
named in one count of conspiracy, while Kaplan was charged with one
count of theft and one count of conspiracy to commit theft.
   Three persons were named as unindicted co-conspirators and
granted immunity in exchange for their testimony, including Owen's
wife, Beverly.
   Owen ran unsuccessfully for governor of Kansas in 1982. He was a
national fund-raiser for Dole in his bid for the 1988 Republican
presidential nomination but media disclosures about Owen's
involvement in the Hayden contribution case and Owen's business
dealings prompted him to resign from the Dole campaign in January
1988.
   In their report, special prosecutors Michael Barbara and Thomas
Haney said they had not attempted to determine what knowledge
Hayden had of the allegedly illegal donations.
   Hayden issued a statement saying the report exonerated him and
his staff.
   All 18 felony and misdemeanor counts were filed against him in
Johnson County District Court in Olathe.
</TEXT>
