   Wearing cowboy hats and talking about peace
between the United States and their country, 10 Soviet legislators
ended a two-day visit to Kansas.
   The delegation led by Yevgeniy Primakov, whose rank is similar
to the speaker of the U.S. House, visited Dodge City, attended a
town meeting, toured a grain elevator, had home-cooked roast beef
at a farm and looked at planes at McConnell Air Force Base.
   At Monday's farewell ceremonies at the base, Primakov said
improving relations with the United States ``is ... a very big
encouragement.''
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., who arranged the visit,
echoed Primakov's call for peace.
   ``It's a very difficult path and a very difficult course
sometimes,'' he said.
   The Soviets had a good look at a Kansas Air National Guard F-16
fighter. Primakov described the plane in one word: ``Ferocious.''
   Another member of the delegation, Veniamin Yarin, called the
B-1B ``a piece of art.''
