<FIRST>u w AM-Summit 1stLd-Writethru   10-31 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0404,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post Reports Superpower Summit Possible In December</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2nd graf with official's ``right track'' comment, DELETES
outdated 9th graf pvs: ``Some normally,''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration and the Soviet Union
are discussing a possible summit meeting as early as December,
perhaps on a ship in the Mediterranean to discuss U.S. help in
transforming the Soviet economy, the Washington Post said in
Tuesday editions.
   A well-placed U.S. official, while declining to confirm the Post
account, said it was ``on the right track.'' Other officials said
they were under instructions not to discuss the situation.
   The meeting between Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and
President Bush would not replace another between the two leaders
expected next summer, as was agreed between Secretary of State
James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
in Wyoming last month, according to an unidentified administration
official, cited by the Post.
   The meeting discussed in Wyoming would be in the United States
while the December conference might be in neutral territory, the
official told the newspaper.
   Among sites he mentioned as a possiblity was a ship in the
Mediterranean.
   The purpose of the meeting that Baker and Shevardnadze agreed to
work toward was described at the time as arms control.
   But a December meeting might concentrate on ways the United
States could help the Soviet Union move closer to a market economy,
according to the official.
   A White House spokesman, Roman Popadiuk, declined to comment on
the newspaper report.
   Bush has been criticized by congressional Democrats for alleged
timidity in responding to the fast-moving changes sweeping the
Soviet Union and some of its satellite states in eastern Europe
that are resulting in freer societies.
   In a recent speech, Baker said the Bush administration was
prepared to give technical economic help to the Soviets and in fact
U.S. economic officials already have been consulted about technical
matters. On Monday, Bush said he would send a Cabinet-level
delegation to Poland late next month to help the Warsaw government
plan ways to repair its ravaged economy.
   Gorbachev's economic reforms so far have not improved the
availability of consumer goods in the Soviet Union or the
performance of the Soviet economy.
</TEXT>
