<FIRST>r a AM-ShipSinks     10-31 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Sinks,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restaurant Ship Sinks in San Pedro</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto TOR1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The restaurant ship Princess Louise, a
331-foot-long former Canadian cruise ship, sank at its mooring in
Long Beach Harbor on Monday. No one was on board and no one was
injured, officials said.
   The vessel capsized at Harbor Marine on Terminal Island at 12:19
p.m., and sank 23 feet to the harbor floor, leaving the ship
half-submerged, Fire Department spokesman Jim Wells said.
   The cause of the sinking was not known. ``Some refurbishing was
done ... but it was not being worked on when it sank,'' said Los
Angeles Harbor Department spokeswoman Julia Nagano.
   Built in 1921, the Princess Louise carried passengers between
Vancouver, British Columbia, and Alaskan ports. The ship served as
a ferry for the Canadian Pacific Railroad before it was converted
to a restaurant ship in 1966 and taken to Terminal Island.
   The ship's seven banquet rooms and three dining rooms could
accommodate 1,200 diners at a time.
   The restaurant closed Jan. 15.
</TEXT>
