<FIRST>r p AM-Maddox     10-31 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maddox,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maddox Says He'll Enter Governor's Race in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Lester Maddox said Monday he will
enter the 1990 Democratic race for governor in January, making good
on his vow that he would run if no true conservative candidate
emerged.
   Maddox released a statement saying his candidacy ``now appears
to be a certainty.'' In a telephone interview, he said that means
he plans to run but will make no official announcement until
January.
   Asked if anything could change his mind, the 74-year-old former
governor said, ``I don't anticipate anything.''
   Maddox announced last year that he would enter the 1990 race if
no conservative Democratic candidate came forward to challenge the
party's national establishment.
   Since then, Lt. Gov. Zell Miller, state Rep. Lauren ``Bubba''
McDonald and state Sen. Roy Barnes have formally entered the
Democratic race for governor, and Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young has
indicated he will run. On the Republican side, state Rep. Johnny
Isakson and former Superior Court Judge Greeley Ellis are in the
running.
   ``It is true that a number of candidates have announced, or
promised to announce. ... Most are men I personally know as good
men,'' Maddox said in his statement. ``... However, they are all
followers and captives of the political establishment without
conservative records, and in my judgment could not be elected as a
Democratic candidate for governor of Georgia in 1990.''
   He also said the other candidates ``would be unable to provide
the strong and free conservative leadership so badly needed for the
years ahead in our state.''
   Maddox said he plans to raise his campaign funds from ``the
outsiders, the average Georgians'' who are ``fed up with their
government.''
   He said he believes he could win the primary, a primary runoff
and the general election with a total warchest of $1 million to
$1.25 million.
   ``I don't have to have the $15 million they're going to raise _
$3 million or $4 million each,'' he said.
   Although he has been treated for cancer, Maddox said his health
is now ``fantastic'' and he doesn't consider himself too old for
the office. ``I've determined that somewhere between 85 and 90,
people get old,'' he said.
   Maddox served as governor of Georgia from 1967 to 1971 and later
was lieutenant governor under former Gov. Jimmy Carter.
</TEXT>
