<HEAD>Diminishing Winds Allow Control of 4,000-Acre Wildfire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with fire controlled; picks up
4th graf, `Two hundred ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fierce winds that pushed flames over 4,000
acres of brushy hillsides diminished Monday, allowing firefighters
to surround the wildfire and declare it controlled.
   Firefighters snuffed out the blaze Monday evening, and planned
to remain at the scene until Tuesday afternoon to prevent
flare-ups, said Ventura County fire department spokeswoman Liz
Pickles.
   ``There's no more smoke, no more flames, and they'll decide
tomorrow whether to pull out,'' Ms. Pickles said.
   Two hundred firefighters, most of them using picks and shovels
to quell hot spots, took part in the mop-up.
   The fire began around 5 a.m. Sunday, when 50-mph winds downed a
power line, igniting the brushy Santa Monica Mountains area
northwest of Malibu.
   The fast-moving blaze destroyed two mountaintop homes and three
other buildings, sending residents, including entertainer Dick
Clark, rushing toward the ocean for safety. More than 2,200 people
were routed from campsites, authorities said.
   Thick, dark smoke from the fire forced closure of the busy
Pacific Coast Highway. The fire could be seen up to 30 miles away.
   Up to 570 firefighters from Los Angeles and Ventura counties
battled the blaze as four air tankers and six helicopters bombed a
two-mile front of flames with retardant and water.
   Residents hosed down the roofs of their homes just north of the
county line, and charred trees and smoldering brush lined the
coastal highway.
</TEXT>
