<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-Mayors-Issues Bjt   10-31 1114</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayors-Issues, Bjt,1148</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0444, changing category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mayoral Candidates Across the Country Accentuate the Negative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A paternity suit in Detroit, a wife-beating allegation in
Cleveland, a stock sale in New York _ all are high-profile issues
in mayoral elections at a time when voters say they are worried
about drugs, crime, homelessness and the quality of schools.
   ``This city faces very large problems,'' said Rudolph Giuliani,
Republican candidate for mayor of New York City. But discussion of
those problems keeps getting shoved aside by juicier stuff in the
harsh campaign between Giuliani and Democrat David Dinkins.
   From the nation's largest city to many of its smallest, voters
will elect hundreds of mayors on Nov. 7, with most incumbents
facing only token opposition.
   There are issue-oriented contests in Dayton, Ohio, and Seattle,
but in other cities with tough races, the campaigns accentuate the
negative and raise unpleasant memories of the worst aspects of the
1988 presidential race.
   The tactics are ``an extension of 1988'' and an example of the
importance voters give to character as a political issue, said
Democratic pollster Peter Hart.
   ``People vote for people, they don't vote for issues,'' said
Republican consultant Eddie Mahe, arguing that an emphasis on
character rather than position papers makes sense. ``These
proponents of one-sided positive campaigns, that's goo-goo land.
That's a dream world...''
   Drugs are named by many as the biggest problem facing the
nation, but politicians are all proclaiming their opposition to
drugs and drug dealers, a fact that Mahe said diminishes it as a
campaign issue.
   ``It appears negative stuff moves (polling) numbers and positive
doesn't,'' said James Ruvolo, Ohio Democratic Party chairman. ``I
think there's a mean spirit out there and I think people want to
believe the worst about politicians.''
   In Ruvolo's own back yard is one of the year's nastiest mayoral
races _ the contest in Cleveland between City Council President
George Forbes and state Sen. Michael R. White.
   Both finalists in the race to succeed Republican Mayor George
Voinovich are Democrats, but their common party affiliation has
done nothing to diminish the bitterness of the race.
   ``The master of sleaze,'' was White's description of Forbes.
   ``Slum lord'' was how Forbes characterized White.
   White accused Forbes operatives of leaking reports that the
state senator had beaten his first wife and said he was the object
of ``a campaign of political terror.'' A short time later, White's
second wife told reporters she had been shoved and beaten.
   Mary Forbes was described as a ``front person'' for her
husband's investments in two radio stations, a drive-in theater,
and a nursing home.
   ``I respect his wife,'' said Forbes. ``I demand he respect my
wife.''
   About the time 71-year-old Coleman Young was gearing up to run
for a fifth term as mayor of Detroit he was hit with a paternity
suit filed by a former city employee. But what looked like a golden
opportunity for Young's opponents faded as an issue when the mayor
agreed to set up a trust fund for 7-year-old Joel Loving and
provide for the boy through his 25th birthday.
   Opponent Tom Barrow emerged from the September nonpartisan
primary as Young's challenger and proclaimed, ``You can run,
Coleman, but you can't hide.''
   So far, Young has run quite well and holds a 10-point lead in
polls over the man he beat four years ago. Barrow has attacked
Young's leadership during 16 years as mayor, hoping voters will
decide it's time for a change.
   The city's two major newspapers think it is. Both the Detroit
News and the Detroit Free Press endorsed Barrow.
   Drugs and crime are issues in Dayton where Mayor Richard Clay
Dixon, a Democrat, is challenged by Abner Orick, a Republican city
commissioner.
   ``He's been in office for three years and each year he'd been
in, crime has increased substantially,'' said Orick.
   ``My records show I have been fighting the war on drugs since I
became mayor,'' retorted Dixon. ``Where was Abner when we declared
war? He did not mention drugs until he became a candidate.''
   Norm Rice, a Seattle city councilman, is favored to become the
city's first black mayor in a campaign in which an initiative aimed
at ending mandatory school busing is a major issue. Doug Jewett,
Rice's Republican opponent, helped draft the measure.
   Rice has criticized the initiative for lacking controls to
prevent the resegregation of schools, but also has said, ``Let's
face it, Doug Jewett is not a racist.''
   Even more low-key is the debate in Miami where Mayor Xavier
Suarez is challenged by Armando E. Lacasa who conceded, ``I do not
believe I was the best candidate to face Suarez. He's going to be
very difficult to beat. But we want to send a message to the mayor
that we are not happy.''
   No such politeness or modesty was detectable in New York City.
   Voters are told that Dinkins is careless about his finances and
that Giuliani is a cold prosecutor, that Jesse Jackson is an ally
of Dinkins and that comedian Jackie Mason's support of Giuliani
proved not very funny.
   ``I refuse to cede the moral high ground. Negative campaigning
doesn't work,'' said Dinkins as his campaign started running a
commercial in which Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., attacked
Giuliani for flip-flopping on abortion and supporting ``judges and
policies to roll back basic civil rights and civil liberties.''
   Jewish voters are a critical group in New York elections and
Giuliani welcomed the support of Mason, an ordained rabbi who
became a standup comic and now stars in the television series,
``Chicken Soup.''
   But Mason's help turned sour when he was overheard saying,
``There is a sick Jewish problem of voting for a black man no
matter how unfit he is for the job.''
   The resulting controversy had Giuliani reeling, but then Dinkins
was put on the defensive by a report he understated the value of a
stock he sold to his son and by an anti-semitic remark attributed
to a black activist who worked for the Dinkins campaign.
   The activist, Robert C. ``Sonny'' Carson, said it was incorrect
to call him anti-semitic. ``I'm anti-white,'' he said.
   Dinkins swiftly denounced Carson, but the incident reminded some
Jewish voters of their antipathy to Jackson who campaigned for
Dinkins during the primary in which he defeated Mayor Ed Koch.
   Even in the calmer atmosphere of Des Moines, Iowa, it's hard to
get people's attention with an issue-oriented campaign.
   Paul Sanfield is running city-wide against City Councilman
George Flagg for an at-large seat.
   ``My issue is affordable housing and neighborhood
redevelopment,'' said Sanfield, who lamented his problem getting
his message out. ``I guess issues aren't that important.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia     10-31 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terrorist, Police Officer Killed When Grenade Explodes Too Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terrorist attacking a police patrol
was killed when a grenade blew up in his hands before he could
throw it, but an officer was also killed and two other people
wounded, authorities said.
   Three more in a series of dynamite bombings blamed on drug
traffickers also shook the capital Monday, police said.
   A police statement said the grenade attack occurred Monday in a
middle-class neighborhood of Bogota.
   After the grenade exploded, fragments injured two police
officers, one of whom died moments later, the statement said.
   Police captured another man slightly injured in the blast and
accused him of aiding in the attack, it said without giving details.
   There was no immediate word on a possible motive for the attack,
which may have been related to the government's war on the the
illicit drug trade.
   The government and drug gangs have been engaged in a bloody
struggle since mid-August, when traffickers killed a leading
presidential candidate.
   Authorities blame drug traffickers for most of the 237 bombings
that have rocked Colombia since the government of President
Virgilio Barco declared the crackdown. The blasts have killed 33
people and injured 222.
   In several of the latest attacks, terrorists have targeted
police. On Thursday, five police officers were killed when a bomb
exploded beside a bus carrying officers to night duty in Medellin.
   The next day, another policeman died in the bombing of the
national police air base outside Bogota.
   Monday's attack occurred about the same time the wave of
dynamite bombings hit the capital. Three bombs exploded in
different parts of the city, causing extensive damage but no
injuries.
   The bombs targeted a bank, a social security office, and a
grocery store.
   It is believed the drug traffickers are retaliating for the
government's extradition of Colombian drug suspects captured in the
anti-drug campaign. Authorities have sent five suspects to face
trial in the United States.
   The government has repeatedly rebuffed offers from the Medellin
cartel to negotiate an end to the violence. Barco has said he will
not deal with traffickers accused of killing a justice minister, a
newspaper publisher and scores of other leading Colombians in the
last five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Writers'Beginnings     10-31 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Writers' Beginnings,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authors Got Their Start With Tales of Typhoons and Scrambled Eggs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author William Styron got his start as a
12-year-old writing a short story for his school newspaper about a
ship in a typhoon, with a captain who ``mused darkly'' and a mate
who gave a ``despondent shriek.''
   Doris Grumbach's first literary effort was titled ``A Man and
His Dog.'' It was good enough to win a high school contest and help
her finagle admission to college despite failing grades. She didn't
write her first novel until 37 years later.
   ``Eggs'' was the first piece written by novelist William
Kennedy, then a college freshman. His short story about a man who
ordered scrambled eggs in a diner was praised by Kennedy's mother
and his banjo teacher but panned by his father, who read it over
breakfast and snapped, ``What the hell is this?''
   Kennedy still has the rejection slip from Collier's magazine.
``It taught me that you don't trust your parents with literature,''
he said.
   They were among 21 prominent American novelists, poets and
essayists who took turns Monday night on the Elizabethan stage of
the Shakespeare Theater at the Folger describing how they got
started in the writing business.
   Their readings, which focused on the theme of Eudora Welty's
book ``One Writer's Beginnings,'' were the highlight of a 10th
anniversary celebration of the PEN@Faulkner Award for Fiction, an
annual prize honoring the best published works of fiction by
contemporary American writers.
   The award is named for the late novelist William Faulkner, who
used his Nobel Prize funds to support talented young writers, and
is financed by gifts, grants and an annual series of readings at
the Folger Shakespeare Library.
   Many of the writers thanked their parents for introducing them
at an early age to what Richard Bausch called ``the power of
words,'' with family traditions of storytelling and book reading.
   Gloria Naylor, winner of the American Book Award for first
fiction for ``The Women of Brewster Place,'' said she inherited her
``passionate love of books'' from her mother, a poor Mississippi
black who joined mail-order book clubs because she was barred from
the local library.
   Joyce Carol Oates, an award-winning novelist, playwright and
essayist, said she grew up poor in Lockport, N.Y., and lived in a
``world of imagination,'' fired by her visits to the town library
and hours of listening to stories read by her parents and
grandparents.
   ``Writers begin as privileged listeners,'' she said.
   After his clumsy boyhood attempt at writing an adventure story
in the style of Joseph Conrad, Styron said he abandoned his
literary interests in favor of moviegoing until he turned 18 and
discovered Thomas Wolfe's novels.
   For five years, Styron indulged the ``intoxicating and
dizzying'' pleasure of reading hundreds of books, and then began
his first novel, ``Lie Down in Darkness.'' He later won a Pulitzer
Prize for ``The Confessions of Nat Turner'' and the American Book
Award for ``Sophie's Choice.''
   Susan Sontag described herself as ``a voluntary misfit'' as a
child. ``At home in bed with a book was not only the safest place
to be but the freest,'' she said.
   Both Larry McMurtry and Miss Welty said they developed their
love of words and keen imaginations during long periods of illness
as children.
   As a sickly youngster in West Texas, McMurtry said he ``lived in
radioland'' listening to popular radio serials of the 1940s. When
wartime bulletins pre-empted his favorite radio shows too often, he
finally dipped into a box of books left by a cousin who had joined
the Army, and ``the literary life began for me.''
   Miss Welty said she was taken out of school at age 6 or 7 and
put to bed with a heart condition for several months. She remembers
that ``an opulence of story books covered my bed _ they were my
counterpane.''
   She fell in love first with the alphabet, then ``the wizardry of
the initials and letters and words'' of her fairy tales, then heard
``the voice of the story'' as she learned to read and later to
write.
   ``I was a writer who came from a sheltered life, but a sheltered
life can be a daring life, and the daring begins within,'' she said.
   Other writers who joined more than 200 guests at the
celebration, which included a candlelight dinner in the library's
Great Hall, were Amiri Baraka, Gwendolyn Brooks, Hortense Calisher,
Pat Conroy, Annie Dillard, Brendan Gill, Stephen Goodwin, Reynolds
Price, Maurice Sendak, Mary Lee Settle, Susan Richards Shreve and
Robert Stone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Nixon     10-31 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Nixon,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nixon, Deng Call for Restoring U.S.-China Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Nixon today brought his private
mission of U.S. reconciliation with China to senior leader Deng
Xiaoping, who agreed the two powers should put common interests
above ideological differences.
   ``I'm very much in favor of your view regarding state-to-state
relations,'' the 85-year-old Deng said at the beginning of their
meeting at the Great Hall of the People.
   ``You should focus on the strategic interests of a country, and
you should not talk about historical roots or differences in
ideology or the strength of a country.''
   Nixon, on the fourth day of a private visit, has called on the
two countries to bury their differences over the June killings of
pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing and mend their frayed
relations.
   He is the most prominent American to visit China since the
crackdown and is expected to brief President Bush upon returning to
the United States.
   Soldiers killed hundreds, perhaps thousands, of unarmed
civilians in Beijing June 4 as the government moved to crush the
student-led movement for a freer China.
   Chinese leaders have agreed it is time to renew ties but say the
United States is to blame for the poor relations and must take the
initiative.
   At today's meeting, Deng praised Nixon for his 1972 trip to
China, which ended 23 years of unveiled hostility and paved the way
for restoring relations. ``What you've done deserves our admiration
and interest,'' Deng said. ``It was you who as president of the
United States changed this status.''
   Nixon, 76, told Deng he had watched Chinese-American relations
for 17 years and that China should understand the depth of American
concern over the government's suppression of the pro-democracy
movement.
   A member of the Nixon party who attended the meeting described
it as a ``tough, no-holds-barred exchange'' that covered the
crackdown, China's ties to the United States and the Soviet Union,
reform in eastern Europe and other subjects.
   Deng appeared tired at today's meeting. Usually, he walks out to
greet visitors. This time, Nixon was escorted into a room to meet
Deng, who was already seated.
   Deng disappeared from public for three months after the June
military crackdown and was rumored to be seriously ill.
   However, talking to reporters after the meeting, Nixon said he
``was impressed by his vigor.''
   ``We found that we did not agree about many elements, but we
found that we agreed on some,'' Nixon added.
   Nixon said the current rift between the two countries is
``without question the most serious'' since 1972.
   But he said he was confident the relationship ``will be
sustained and those that are signaling its death are much
premature.''
   At a state banquet Monday hosted by Premier Li Peng, the former
president urged a restoration of good relations but also called for
a ``humanely governed China'' that won't ``turn away from greatness
and consign itself to the backwater of oppression and stagnation.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, commenting on Nixon's
appeal for rapprochement, said the United States wants to normalize
relations but the conditions are not yet right.
   Washington has suspended high-level official contacts and cut
off arms sales since the crackdown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
