<DOCNO> AP891031-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake Bjt   10-31 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake, Bjt,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Ponders How to Fund Billions of Dollars in Earthquake Repairs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos OAS1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bay cities capped World Series mania
with muted celebration and returned to the business of recovery
from billions of dollars in earthquake damage as lawmakers prepared
to debate how to pay the bill.
   The scale of the disaster continued to become more apparent as
the number of applicants for emergency housing, grants and loans
reached 30,000, but a poll indicated most Californians would
support a sales tax hike to help out.
   Businesses, meanwhile, began ad campaigns to bring back tourists
and conventions to prevent economic disaster on top of the natural
calamity.
   About 4,000 fans cheered the Oakland Athletics in Oakland's Jack
London Square on Monday, but there was no parade and the Oct. 17
quake that delayed the A's victory over the San Francisco Giants
for 10 days was in mind.
   ``Nobody likes the reason we had to wait so long to be the world
champions, but I know it means a great deal to all of us,'' A's
manager Tony La Russa told the crowd, which was asked to contribute
to quake relief.
   The team's arrival by ferry was an implicit endorsement of
officials' pleas for commuters to use public transportation to ease
congestion caused by closure of the damaged Bay Bridge, collapse of
double-decked Interstate 880 in Oakland and damage to other
Northern California roads and bridges.
   About the same time, workers demolishing the I-880 structure
removed the flattened car in which longshoreman Buck Helm amazingly
survived four days before his rescue. Helm remained in serious
condition at Highland Hospital.
   In Sacramento, Gov. George Deukmejian and state lawmakers
announced that a special session of the Legislature will convene
Thursday to consider legislation to help fund quake relief. Damage
has been estimated at more than $7 billion.
   The governor proposed a temporary quarter-cent increase in the
state's 6 percent sales tax. Beginning Dec. 1 and lasting 13
months, it would raise $800 million to pay the state's estimated
share of repairing public buildings and highways and providing
grants to families and assistance to local governments.
   According to a Los Angeles Times poll published Monday, 52
percent of 1,377 Californians surveyed would support a sales tax
increase to pay for earthquake repairs and to aid victims.
   The governor also said the state might have to dip into its $1.1
billion emergency reserve if costs prove to be higher, Deukmejian
said.
   Congress last week approved $3.5 billion for California
earthquake relief.
   The state transportation department director, Robert Best, said
$1.8 billion is the projected cost of repairing state and local
roads, including retrofitting all highway bridges in the state to
make them earthquake safe.
   The federal funds include $1 billion for highways. Best said he
hopes more federal money will be allocated once damage estimates
are firmed up.
   Elsewhere, state schools superintendent Bill Honig said public
schools suffered comparatively little damage because of strict
school construction standards, but repairs still will cost more
than $50 million.
   Seven of the 1,482 schools in the eight hardest-hit counties had
severe damage to buildings with classrooms. Five buildings without
classrooms also were damaged. Honig said 95 percent of students
returned to school in two days.
   Around the San Francisco Bay area, the San Francisco Convention
and Visitors Bureau, the Hyatt hotel corporation and Oakland
businesses began preparing advertising campaigns to keep the
tourists and their dollars coming to the region.
   ``We're doing a lot because the world thinks we've tumbled into
the bay,'' said Charles McElroy, general manager of the
Hyatt-Regency in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
