<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CarrierAccident     10-31 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carrier Accident,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captain Lauds Crew's Performance in Carrier Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XPA1</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bombs-Cruiser, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of the aircraft carrier USS
Lexington praised his crew's performance after the crash-landing of
a training jet that killed five people dead and sent flames rolling
across the flight deck.
   The crash killed the pilot, three sailors and a civilian
technician, and injured 19 aboard the Lexington, a training ship
fondly called ``Lady Lex'' because it is the Navy's only carrier
that allows female sailors. One of the 180 women in the crew of
1,440 was among those killed.
   ``Members of the crew responded superbly. They demonstrated they
were very well-trained and they moved. Their shipmates were injured
and they did all that they could to take care of them,'' said Capt.
C. Flack Logan after the ship arrived at its home port here Monday.
   One crew member who said she never thought of running for safety
was Airman Dee Votolato, a camera operator who kept her videotape
running until the instant the T-2 Buckeye jet crashed at her feet
Sunday and cartwheeled in flames.
   Ms. Votolato, 21, of Houma, La., was knocked to the deck when
the jet flipped upside down and crashed into the carrier's tower.
But she got back up and kept taping as shipmates put out a fire.
   ``The women were in fighting the fire, taking the medical
precautions, taking every step the men were taking,'' Ms. Votolato
said. ``A ship is not a beautiful place, it's not, but when you are
here to do your job and when get the job done you are not a woman,
you are a sailor.''
   Within 12 seconds of the crash, the first fire hoses turned on
the flames and the main blaze was extinguished in about two
minutes, Logan said.
   Two separate investigations will be conducted, as is routine in
such accidents, Logan said. Safety investigators will watch the
videotape and try to determine what caused the accident while the
Judge Advocate General's staff will look for possible wrongdoing.
   Aboard another Navy vessel Monday, a U.S. warplane accidentally
dropped a 500-pound bomb on the guided-missile crusier USS Reeves
during maneuvers in the Indian Ocean. The bomb left a 5-foot hole
in the main deck and five sailors were slightly injured, the Navy
said.
   The Lexington crash took place in near-perfect flying weather
when the ship was in the Gulf of Mexico, about 30 miles south of
Pensacola, Logan said, adding that the pilot didn't report
mechanical problems. Ms. Votolato said the plane was coming in too
low, appeared to overcorrect and climbed at a steep angle before
flipping upside down and hitting the ship.
   ``As I see it,'' Logan said, ``he ended up in a position, which
in naval aviation is known as being low and slow, which is a very
terrible place to be when you are coming aboard a ship.''
   Landing signal officers radioed the pilot to add power and waved
him off, but for some reason the airplane was unable to comply,
Logan said.
   The pilot, Ensign Steven E. Pontell, 23, of Columbia, Md., was
making his first attempt to land on a carrier, Logan said. He was
the only one aboard the two-seat trainer, as is normal when
aviators make their first carrier landings.
   Pontell was a member of Training Squadron 19 at Meridian (Miss.)
Naval Air Station and was a 1988 graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy.
   Also killed were Petty Officer 3rd Class Burnett Kilgore Jr.,
19, of Holly Springs, Miss.; Petty Officer 3rd Class Timmy L.
Garroutte, 30, of Memphis, Tenn., and Airman Lisa L. Mayo, 25, of
Oklahoma City, all Lexington crew members; and Byron Gervis
Courvelle, 32, of Meridian, Miss., a civilian employee of DynCorp,
which has a contract to maintain Navy aircraft. All four were
killed on the flight deck.
   Ms. Mayo had joined the Navy only four months ago, said her
mother, Doris Fant of Oklahoma City. The mother said she didn't
blame the death on her daughter's choice of career.
   ``I feel that she made a decision, that that's what she wanted
to do,'' Mrs. Fant said. ``You can't fail unless you try.''
   Two of the 19 others injured remained hospitalized, the most
serious in critical by stable condition.
</TEXT>
