<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-31 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips In Tokyo, Stocks Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell marginally against the Japanese yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index bounced back with
a moderate gain.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average recouped 132.00 points, or
0.37 percent, ending at 35,549.44. It had shed 109.85 points Monday.
   Dealers said the index recovered after losses in the last two
trading days although afternoon trading lacked direction as
participants' interests became widespread.
   Masahiro Umemori, a Nomura Securities analyst, said the index's
uptrend slowed toward the end of the afternoon session, but it
remained higher as some participants picked up electricals.
   Among winners were trading houses and real estate issues,
following news reports that Japan's Mitsubishi Estate Co. acquired
a majority of Rockefeller Group, Inc., dealers said.
   The dollar finished at 142.15 yen, down 0.02 yen from Monday's
142.17-yen close. It opened higher at 142.32 yen, and ranged
between 142.12 yen and 142.50 yen.
   ``The currrency trading was boring today,'' said Toru Kanai, a
foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities, Co. in Tokyo.
   He said some investors bought the dollar in early morning
trading prior to their end-of-the-month account settlement.
   But other market players pushed the U.S. currency down when it
hit the 142.50-yen line for profit-taking, Kanai said.
   Other traders said trading was slow ahead of a series of U.S.
economic data to be released later this week. The U.S. jobless
rate, which is watched most closely, is due out Friday.
</TEXT>
