<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-MIAs     10-31 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-MIAs,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Agrees To New Work To Resolve Cases of Missing U.S. Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has agreed to work to resolve
the cases of about 80 more U.S. soldiers missing from the Vietnam
War and other Americans reported lost in Laos, a U.S. envoy said
today after talks in Hanoi.
   John W. Vessey Jr. said he presented the Vietnamese with two new
lists totalling about 70 ``discrepancy cases'' involving the loss
of about 80 Americans in the war.
   ``Discrepancy cases'' are those to which the United States has
assigned highest priority. They are cases that the Vietnamese
should have information, according to U.S. officials.
   They include servicemen who were believed to have been taken
prisoner but were not freed when the U.S. involvement in the war
ended in 1973.
   Vessey told a news conference he also asked the Vietnamese to do
research on ``similar types of cases'' over the border in Laos. The
war spilled over into Laos, which North Vietnam used as a sanctuary
to fight U.S.-backed South Vietnam.
   ``The Vietnamese accepted both the suggestions that we made,''
Vessey said. He held two days of talks ending Sunday with Foreign
Minister Nguyen Co Thach.
   It was Vessey's second mission to Vietnam as presidential envoy.
During his August 1987 trip, he presented the Vietnamese with 70
cases. Specialists from both sides are now involved in their eighth
joint field investigation to resolve those cases.
   Vessey said 19 of the 70 cases have already been resolved
through the discovery of remains.
   In other cases, he said, ``we've gained new information but
they're still inconclusive and others, we don't know any more than
we did when we started out.''
   He said his team urged the Vietnamese to go back over the
unresolved cases and find soldiers or other witnesses who know
something about them.
   ``If the man is alive, we want him back. If he is not alive,
we'd like to be able to tell his family what happened to him,''
Vessey said.
   Vietnam says it is not holding any live Americans.
   Vessey said he also exchanged views with Thach on the conflict
in Cambodia, where a Vietnamese-installed government is fighting
guerrillas backed by the United States and other countries. The
United States has said it will not establish diplomatic ties with
Hanoi until it helps resolve the conflict.
   Vessey declined to give details but said Thach ``clarified'' his
government's position on Cambodia.
   Vessey's delegation to Hanoi included senior officials of the
Defense and State Departments and Ann Mills Griffiths, the head of
the private National League of Families of American Prisoners and
Missing in Southeast Asia.
   A U.S. Embassy official said Mrs. Griffiths and David F.
Lambertson, the deputy assistant secretary of state for Asian
affairs, would visit Laos for talks Nov. 2 to 3 on accounting for
missing soldiers there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
