<DOCNO> AP891031-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-OspreyFight     10-31 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Osprey Fight,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter-Plane Stuck at the Congressional Gate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saving the V-22 Osprey aircraft from Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney's budget ax is not an easy task for the
Marine Corps, lawmakers concerned about jobs back home and military
contractors.
   Ever since Cheney told Congress in May that budget constraints
had forced him to propose canceling the $27 billion project to
build the tilt-rotor aircraft, the campaign to spare the Osprey has
been intense.
   The contractors _ Boeing Helicopter of Lester, Pa., and Bell
Helicopter Textron of Fort Worth, Texas _ have filled the airwaves
with television ads showing the helicopter that can fly like an
airplane. Newspapers and magazines carry advertisements
proclaiming, ``V-22 Osprey, Affordability.''
   And key congressional backers of the aircraft, particularly
lawmakers from Pennsylvania and Texas, have fired off ``dear
colleague'' letters that include editorials and articles of praise
for the program.
   Marine Corps officials have even discussed the concept of an
assault support aircraft for the Osprey.
   The effort, however, has not met with much success.
   House and Senate negotiators hammering out a final defense
budget for the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 are considering a
proposal of about $255 million for research and development of the
Osprey but no procurement money. The Osprey's fate likely will be
decided this week as House and Senate negotiators wrap up work on
the defense bill.
   The future of the program would be tied to commercial use of the
V-22, said lawmakers and congressional sources, who requested
anonymity.
   ``The proposal is unacceptable,'' said Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa.,
a member of the House Armed Services Committee who has sent a
number of letters to colleagues urging them to support the Osprey.
   ``With just research and development, in effect there will never
be a V-22. ... Continue the funding and a make a decision next
year. But without procurement money, the program is, in fact,
dead,'' Weldon said.
   In proposing to cancel the Osprey, Cheney argued a mix of
conventional helicopters would serve as an alternative to the V-22,
which at $23 million a copy was too expensive.
   Weldon contends Cheney based his decision on inaccurate
information.
   ``Several military witnesses have appeared before the Armed
Services Committee, and all except Secretary Cheney's pencil
pushers are on the record acknowledging that the V-22 costs less
and delivers more capability than DOD's proposed alternatives,''
Weldon said in one letter.
   Rep. David O'B. Martin, R-N.Y., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee and former Navy pilot, said the Bush
administration's alternatives ``aren't any cheaper or as effective
as the Osprey.''
   While lawmakers argued their case, representatives from Bell
Helicopter Textron promoted the V-22 during a recent trade show in
Washington, saying it could have been used during the Panamanian
rebels failed coup attempt against Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and
to help earthquake victims in northern California.
   ``Delaying (the program) would cause us some grief,'' said Dick
Spivey, the director of V-22 business development.
   Supporters of Cheney's decision say the secretary had to make
the ``hard choices'' and they scoff at the argument the V-22 could
be used in Panama.
   ``That's a little like saying the B-2 can be used to blow up
(Libyan leader Moammar) Gadhafi's tent,'' said Rep. Andy Ireland,
R-Fla., a member of the Armed Services panel. ``It isn't a good,
hard argument.''
   Meanwhile, Gen. Michael P. Sullivan, director of the Marine
Corps Combat Development Command at Quantico, Va., has talked about
``the concept of an assault support aircraft that would provide
support for the V-22.''
   Congressional sources, who requested anonymity, said the
discussion by the Marine Corps of the support aircraft possibly was
an attempt to bolster the campaign for the V-22.
   But Lt. Col. Robert McLean, spokesman for the center at
Quantico, said the discussion of support aircraft is ``conceptual
only, not something that's in a sort of formal, proposal stage ...
This is not something that has special sponsorship'' of the Marine
Corps.
</TEXT>
