<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GasolineTax     10-31 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gasoline Tax,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Say Dole Gas Tax Idea Needs Bush Backing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House rejection of Senate Minority
Leader Bob Dole's suggestion for higher federal gasoline taxes
means the idea will go nowhere in Congress, say Democratic House
and Senate leaders.
   Consistent with President Bush's campaign promise to not raise
taxes, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater deflected the
proposal Monday.
   ``We do not feel that an increase in federal gas taxes is
necessary at this time,'' Fitzwater told reporters.
   On NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press'' program Sunday, Dole, R-Kan.,
said he would support an increase in the 9.1-cent-per-gallon
gasoline tax ``for rebuilding the infrastructure, not for debt
reduction.''
   But top Democrats said Monday that Dole's endorsement for the
idea meant little without Bush's backing.
   ``Before it goes through Congress, we would have to be ensured
of the president's support,'' said House Speaker Thomas S. Foley,
D-Wash. Foley said he favors raising the fuel levy to rebuild
crumbling roads.
   ``He (Bush) has veto power, and there's no way to override a
veto on a tax increase, that's for sure,'' said Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine. ``So there's no point going
through the exercise.''
   Democrats _ who have learned painfully in recent elections that
voters oppose higher taxes _ have been loath to push any major
revenue legislation without lining up presidential approval in
advance.
   Dole, who unsuccessfully challenged Bush for his party's
presidential nomination last year, has supported tax increases for
specified purposes before.
   He originally supported the income surcharge on the elderly to
pay for Medicare coverage of extended illnesses, a program Congress
enacted last year and now is in the process of rolling back. He has
also favored an oil import fee.
   Dole did not suggest an amount for a gasoline tax increase.
Officials estimate that for each penny increase, the levy would
raise an additional $1 billion.
   Other lawmakers from both parties _ Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., chairman of the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee,
and members of the Senate and House panels that oversee public
works _ have previously suggested boosting the gasoline tax.
   Some have suggested using the money for road programs, while
others have said it would be a good way to reduce the federal
deficit, which reached $152 billion last year.
   A penny-a-gallon gasoline tax first took effect in 1932. The
most recent increase occurred Jan. 1, 1987, when it was raised by
one-tenth of one cent to pay for cleaning up leaky underground fuel
tanks.
   Of the rest, all but one cent goes to road and bridge work. The
remaining penny is for mass transit assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
