<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Pierce     10-31 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Pierce,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce's Lawyer Complains Government Won't Pay Legal Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Housing Secretary Samuel Pierce Jr.'s
attorney says the Justice Department is stretching regulations to
avoid paying Pierce's legal bills from a congressional
investigation.
   A Justice Department spokesman said the agency's ruling was
based on a legal interpretation.
   But attorney Robert Plotkin said the Justice Department offered
an ``off-the-wall'' reason why regulations did not qualify Pierce
for reimbursement of private legal fees arising from a House
subcommittee's probe of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development.
   The former secretary twice refused to answer questions when he
appeared before the House Government Operations employment and
housing subcommittee, which has conducted hearings on mismanagement
and political favoritism in the award of HUD grants during Pierce's
tenure.
   Pierce asked HUD to pay his legal expenses because they arose
from questions about his performance of official duties in the
Reagan administration.
   But the Justice Department, asked by HUD to rule on the request,
said two weeks ago that the department has no responsibility to
represent Pierce and therefore wouldn't rule on whether he
qualified for reimbursement of private legal fees.
   Department spokesman David Runkel said ``our decision was based
on the civil division's interpretation of the law. The lawyers took
a look at it and that's their decision.''
   ``It's a hot potato,'' said Plotkin. ``HUD hands off to Justice,
Justice hands off back to HUD.''
   The Justice Department, Plotkin said, stretched the clear
meaning of the regulations to say it wasn't responsible for
representing Pierce.
   ``I couldn't believe that of several potential grounds that
perhaps they might have used to justify not paying it, the one they
used seemed so off-the-wall,'' Plotkin said.
   The regulation says current and former federal officials ``may
be provided representation in civil and congressional proceedings
and in state criminal proceedings ... when the actions for which
representation is requested reasonably appear to have been
performed within the scope of the employee's employment and
providing representation would otherwise be in the interest of the
United States.''
   ``One would think that clearly on it's face we are eligible,''
Plotkin said. ``And then they have to exercise their discretion as
to whether or not they want to pay it.''
   But in an Oct. 25 letter to HUD, Deputy Assistant Attorney
General Stephen C. Bransdorfer said legal representation by the
Justice Department ``is available only in situations where the
employee is subject to civil or state criminal proceedings as a
result of actions taken within the normal scope of that employee's
authority.
   ``If there are no such underlying proceedings then
representation is not available,'' Bransdorfer said.
   There are no civil or state criminal proceedings against Pierce.
   HUD said that based on Bransdorfer's determination, Pierce's
request was denied.
   Plotkin declined to describe the size of his law firm's legal
bill, saying only that he had been prepared to negotiate with the
Justice Department over what expenses the government would pay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
