<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Baker-MiddleEast     10-31 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Middle East,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Showdown Looming Over Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contrary to reports of deadlines and imminent
showdowns, Secretary of State James A. Baker III says he does not
expect a ``make-or-break'' decision on Mideast negotiations while
he is on an eight-day visit to Australia.
   Baker is leaving late tonight for talks with Prime Minister Bob
Hawke and also to attend a meeting in Canberra of 12 nations
considering the formation of a new economic compact to foster free
trade and an open-market system.
   Known as the Pacific Basin initiative, it has Baker's support as
timely because the United States is boosting trade with Asia to new
heights. Trade has more than tripled in 10 years to $280 billion in
1988, a senior U.S. official said Monday.
   Ten Asian nations, but not China, Taiwan or Hong Kong, are
attending, along with the United States and Canada. Some,
especially Japan, have been accused at times of protectionist
policies.
   But the Canberra meeting is designed ``to put pressure to open
markets around the world,'' said the U.S. official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``Open market systems tend to be associated
with greater freedom.''
   As he prepared to depart, Baker said he was reviewing his
five-point proposal for Mideast talks at Israel's request. But, he
told The Associated Press in an interview Monday: ``I don't
anticipate we will have definitive answers _ either yes or no _
before I get back from Australia.''
   He said Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens may be traveling in
Asia during the period, and ``we may continue to talk.'' But, Baker
added: ``I would guide you off of looking for either a make or
break on this thing before the trip is over.''
   Arens last week notified Baker the Israeli government accepted
the U.S. proposal _ but with two provisos. They were that the
Palestine Liberation Organization be excluded from any Israeli
meeting with Palestinians and that the agenda be limited to
preparations for an election on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir proposed the election, with U.S.
endorsement, as a way of having Palestinians choose their
representative to negotiate five years of limited self-rule in the
territories. The PLO, which Israel shuns, contends it is the sole
representative of the Palestinians.
   Baker's proposal gave Israel assurances it would talk only to a
Palestinian delegation it found satisfactory. He also said he was
not pressuring Israel to deal with the PLO.
   Recent reports from Israel suggest Baker is close to a decision
on whether to keep trying. Shamir was quoted last Tuesday as saying
there was ``no large gap'' between the two approaches and ``in a
few days we will know if there is an agreement or not.''
   But Baker disputed his month-long effort was at a critical point.
   ``I have not put any deadlines down and we will continue to try
and work the problem,'' he said. ``But I really don't anticipate
it's going to make or break before we get back from Australia.''
</TEXT>
