<FIRST>r a PM-HawaiiCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0471 10-31 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hawaii Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0471,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islanders Mourn Students Lost in Plane Crash that Killed 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Investigators from ...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with NTSB statement.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAUNAKAKAI, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends grieved for eight high-school
athletes and two educators who were among 20 killed in a plane
crash that shocked this community so deeply one person lamented,
``Our lifeblood is gone.''
   Across the close-knit rural island, people flew streamers of
green and white _ the Molokai High School colors _ from their car
antennas in memory of those lost when a commuter plane crashed
Saturday, killing everyone aboard.
   ``It's small enough here so that everybody knows each other,''
said the Rev. Robb Kojima of Kalaiakamanu Hou Congregational
Church. ``It's almost like the feeling when the (space shuttle)
Challenger blew up. In the same sense, we all feel the grief.''
   Investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board
arrived Monday to study the wreckage of the Aloha IslandAir de
Havilland Twin Otter, which slammed into a ridge near Halawa Valley
on the eastern end of the island during a flight from neighboring
Maui. Rescuers recovered the bodies Sunday from the charred
wreckage.
   There was no indication the pilot knew he was in trouble, said
NTSB acting Chairman James Kolstad, who heads the agency's
investigation team here.
   Thirteen victims were Molokai residents. Eight were members of
the school's volleyball teams returning from a tournament, the
coach of the girls' team and the school's athletic director. Also
killed were a honeymooning couple from Philadelphia, a couple from
Houston, a Maui island resident and the plane's pilot and co-pilot,
who live in Honolulu.
   A special assembly was held at the 655-student school Monday,
but the grief spread across the island of 6,000.
   ``This island, we're like a big family. When one hurts, everyone
hurts,'' said Wilma Grambusch, a Molokai High teacher. ``This is a
true tragedy. They're our young people. Our lifeblood is gone.''
   The Rev. Rick Lazor of Kaunakakai Baptist Church urged students
to help each other, particularly a group of athletes who caught an
earlier flight home and were suffering from what he called
``survival guilt.''
   ``You need to be there for each other today,'' Lazor told the
assembly.
   The twin-engine plane was 16 years old and had made 28,000
flights, said Peter Dudgeon, Aloha IslandAir's vice president and
general manager.
   The Federal Aviation Administration said there were no recent
reports of service difficulties or accidents.
   The airline has been negotiating to acquire more hangar space at
Honolulu International Airport because mechanics now service planes
in the open, Dudgeon said recently.
   However, Aloha IslandAir spokeswoman Stephanie Ackerman said
Monday the situation didn't affect the quality of maintenance.
   ``The maintenance is still thorough and complete where we are
now,'' Ms. Ackerman said. ``If it wasn't the FAA would know about
it.''
   Pete Beckner, an FAA manager of the Honolulu flight standards
office, said Aloha IslandAir wasn't required to have an enclosed
maintenance area. There weren't any pending maintenance complaints
against the airline, he said.
   The plane left Kahului Airport on Maui Saturday evening for a
scheduled 35-minute flight. The wreckage was sighted early Sunday,
spread over 300 feet.
   There was no distress call from the crew, authorities said.
   The plane had neither a flight-data recorder nor cockpit voice
recorder because that equipment isn't required of small commuter
aircraft, the NTSB said.
   The 30-year-old pilot, Capt. Bruce Pollard, had flown for the
airline for two years, Dudgeon said. The first officer was Phil
Helfrich, 27.
   The passenger list included Peter and Elizabeth Wiley,
honeymooners from Philadelphia; John Craig and Christina Batura of
Houston; and Hank Gabriel of Maui.
   The Molokai passengers were girl's volleyball coach Odetta
Rapanot; athletic director John Ino; students Leilani Ahina, Jared
Elia, Lea Dunnam, Natalie Helm, Nancine Mahiai, Aloma Spencer,
Jovencio Ruiz, and Testa Ku; and residents Collette Kekalia, Nancy
Pierce and Rodrigo Senica.
</TEXT>
