<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0435EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     10-31 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Members: Re-Opening of American Embassy in Beirut Discussed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The re-opening of the American Embassy in
Beirut is being discussed between U.S. officials and Lebanese
Christians, according to two House members who want a resumption of
diplomatic business in the war-torn country.
   Reps. Nick Joe Rahall, D-W.Va., and Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio,
returned from a 24-hour trip to Beirut over the weekend convinced
the State Department should send some American employees back to
Lebanon. Both lawmakers are of Lebanese descent.
   More than two dozen Americans were evacuated from the embassy
Sept. 6 after Ambassador John McCarthy said the security situation
had deteriorated to the point where safety could not be guaranteed.
   The impetus for the pullout was Gen. Michel Aoun's threat to
subject the Americans to a ``dose of Christian terrorism.'' Aoun,
head of the Christian militias fighting 40,000 Syrian troops based
in Lebanon, also supported sit-ins that had forced the embassy to
be supplied by helicopters.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Military Recruits Show Improved Test Scores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's military recruits have shown
improvements in standard military test scores and educational
background since 1980, according to a congressional study of the
nation's all-volunteer service.
   The study, conducted by the Congressional Budget Office, also
showed that the percentage of blacks among the nation's recruits
has dropped since 1980 but that minorities continue to be
disproportionately represented in the armed forces.
   The report, released Monday, said the results ``represent a
considerable change from the beginning of the decade, when testing
problems and recruiting difficulties resulted in large numbers of
low scorers and non-graduates being accepted for military service.''
   In 1980, less than 70 percent of active-duty recruits for the
armed services had high school diplomas, but seven years later, 94
percent of active-duty recruits had diplomas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Study Shows `Modest Success' in School Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although states made a greater effort to
improve public education in the 1980s than ever before, ``doubts
still linger'' about quality and classroom reforms met with only
``modest success,'' according to a report.
   The Center for Policy Research in Education said Monday that
states have introduced an ``unsurpassed number of education-related
bills, increased state aid, and examined the findings of hundreds
of state-level task forces and commission.''
   The report cited gains in high school curricula, teachers'
salaries and educational funding, but it said ``reforms met with
only modest success in achieving their goals.
   ``Doubts still linger about the rigor and challenge of some of
the new courses in academic subjects, the impact of reform on
at-risk students, the quality of teachers and teaching and the
equitable funding of schools.''
   The federally funded Center for Policy Research in Education is
a consortium of Rutgers, Michigan State and Stanford universities
and the University of Wisconsin at Madison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
