<HEAD>Judge Approves Agreement Evicting Court Offices from Town Hall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KILLINGLY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge ordered himself and the
rest of the Superior Court evicted from the Town Hall because of
complaints that people on court business littered, damaged the
building and took up parking space.
   Judge Michael Conway on Monday entered a judgment that will
require the state to find a new home for the Superior Court.
   The court, which handles misdemeanor cases and motor vehicle and
housing complaints, has occupied the second floor of Killingly Town
Hall for about 20 years, paying $25,000 a year rent for the last
seven years.
   ``We just want 'em out of there,'' said Donald F. Costello,
chairman of the Town Council, which voted last year to ask the
state to move the court. ``The business of the town is the business
of town hall.''
   Conway, whose ruling came on a suit filed by the town in June,
is expected to set a deadline for the move at a Dec. 4 hearing.
