<FIRST>r p PM-LesterMaddox     10-31 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lester Maddox,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says He Will Enter Georgia Governor's Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Lester Maddox, once a flamboyant
symbol of segregation, says his plan to enter the 1990 Democratic
race for governor appears to be a certainty.
   But the 74-year-old Maddox said he will make no official
announcement until January.
   Maddox, who announced last year he would enter the race if no
conservative Democratic candidate came forward to challenge the
party's national establishment, released a statement Monday of his
intentions.
   Lt. Gov. Zell Miller, state Rep. Lauren ``Bubba'' McDonald and
state Sen. Roy Barnes have formally entered the Democratic race,
and Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young has indicated he will run.
   On the Republican side, state Rep. Johnny Isakson and former
Superior Court Judge Greeley Ellis are running.
   ``It is true that a number of candidates have announced or
promised to announce,'' Maddox said. ``Most are men I personally
know as good men.''
   Maddox contended, though, that ``they are all followers and
captives of the political establishment without conservative
records, and in my judgment could not be elected as a Democratic
candidate for governor of Georgia in 1990.''
   Maddox called the other Democratic contenders ``a bunch of
look-alikes'' who need campaign consultants to create an image.
   Although he has been treated for cancer, Maddox said his health
is ``fantastic'' and he doesn't consider himself too old for the
office.
   Maddox, who was Georgia governor from 1967 to 1971, later was
lieutenant governor under then-Gov. Jimmy Carter.
   Maddox gained national attention before he became governor by
selling his restaurant rather than serving blacks.
   Yet, despite fears of a segregationist administration, Maddox
named more blacks to high state office when he was governor than
any of his predecessors and adopted a moderate approach to racial
issues.
</TEXT>
