<FIRST>r a PM-MissingBoysRdp     10-31 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Boys Rdp,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search For Two Missing Boys Intensifies; Body of Third Boy Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOSEPH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for an 11-year-old boy who
was abducted at gunpoint last week intensified after a motorist
reported seeing a young man and a boy in a car stopped along a
road, the FBI said.
   About 35 sheriff's deputies, city police and state patrolmen
searched four south-central Minnesota counties Monday for a sign of
Jacob Wetterling. Authorities arrested a man who was driving a
white Chevrolet, which matched the motorist's description of the
vehicle.
   But the motorist later failed to identify the man in a photo
lineup, authorities said.
   Elsewhere, searchers hunted in an Oregon gold mine for a missing
boy, while authorities in West Sacramento, Calif., recovered the
remains of an 8-year-old boy who was missing for two months.
   In Minnesota, FBI spokesman Byron Gigler said a 19-year-old
motorist on Monday saw a boy and a man in his 20s get into a car on
a road near Hector, 75 miles west of Minneapolis and 60 miles south
from where Jacob was abducted.
   The motorist said he went over to see if the had car trouble,
but the man and boy drove off. He said the man showed something
that looked like a gun.
   The boy was described as being 5 feet to 5 feet 4 inches _ about
the size as Jacob _ and was wearing a red jacket similar to the one
Jacob wore when he was abducted a week ago from his home in St.
Joseph, police said.
   Less than an hour after the motorist's sighting, a Carver County
deputy sheriff spotted an eastbound car near Victoria _ 45 miles
east of Hector _ matching the general description of the other car,
said Eden Prairie Police Capt. Jim Clark.
   The driver, a Minneapolis man, was arrested for carrying two
handguns without a permit, Clark said. The man, whose name was not
released, was alone in the car. He was being held on the gun
charges.
   Gigler said authorities will look today for other white
Chevrolets.
   Jacob, a top student and hockey player, was abducted at gunpoint
by a masked man on a dark stretch of road less than a mile from his
home on Oct. 22. The abduction occurred as Jacob, his 10-year-old
brother, Trevor, and an 11-year-old friend were returning home.
   The abductor grabbed Jacob and threatened to shoot the other two
unless they ran into the woods.
   Gigler said authorities on Monday called off a ground search in
the township where the abduction occurred. About 225 National
Guardsmen and about 80 state workers had combed the 36-square mile
area over the weekend without finding clues to the abduction.
   In south-central Oregon, authorities searched for 9-year-old
Nathan Madsen in an abandoned gold mine after someone told them
about the little-known mine. The boy, on horseback, disappeared
Oct. 22 while on a family cattle roundup. Today, divers are
expected to search bogs and sinkholes in the area.
   In California, skeletal remains of 8-year-old Ysidro Valles was
found Sunday by a passer-by in an isolated area near the Sacramento
River, police said. The boy vanished two months ago from his
Sacramento home. An autopsy Monday found that the death was a
homicide, but police released no further details.
</TEXT>
