<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     10-31 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly higher but trading in a
narrow range in Europe late this morning. Gold prices fell slightly.
   The British pound gained ground, and was quoted at $1.5790,
compared with $1.5785 late Monday.
   Currency dealers said they don't expect major movements in the
dollar in the near-term.
   ``Not much has changed since the day before,'' said one trader
in Milan, Italy. ``The dollar is fairly stable ... and I don't
expect any disturbances to change the situation.''
   ``There's nothing special going on today,'' agreed Jens-Uwe
Fischer, senior trader at Manufacturers Hanover in Frankfurt.
   ``It seems to me we're still closely tied to the Dow Jones
(Industrial Average). The last two days we've followed it almost
exactly.''
   Traders said the market was calm ahead of the release later
today of the U.S. September index of leading indicators and
Friday's release of U.S. unemployment data for October. The index
is expected to show a month-to-month rise of 0.4 percent.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.02 yen to a closing 142.52 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 142.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates in London at midmorning compared with late
Monday:
   _1.8405 West German marks, up from 1.8360
   _1.6125 Swiss francs, up from 1.6065
   _6.2425 French francs, up from 6.2325
   _2.0780 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0727
   _1,348.50 Italian lire, up from 1,348.00
   _1.1732 Canadian dollars, down from 1.17475
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $376.00 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $376.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $376.05.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $376.10 compared with $376.75 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.75 to close at a bid $376.00.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.24 a troy
ounce, up from Monday's $5.22.
