<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Uganda-Prisoners     10-31 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Uganda-Prisoners,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uganda Releases 625 Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has freed 625 prisoners
who were among thousands jailed without trial in 1986 on suspicion
of supporting rebel groups, officials said today.
   The prisoners, released Saturday, brought to 4,332 the number of
political detainees freed in the past 16 months, officials said.
   Joseph Etima, the acting prisons commissioner, said fewer than
2,000 of the prisoners remained in jail but ``will be released in
due course, after their papers have been processed.''
   The prisoners were taken into custody during fighting between
government troops and the rebel Uganda People's Democratic Army in
1986. Museveni seized power in January 1986 after a five-year
guerrilla war.
   Four groups of prisoners have been released since the rebels
signed a peace accord with the government in June 1988.
   The releases also followed criticism from human rights groups,
which complained that the government of President Yoweri Museveni
was allowing the prisoners to languish in jail without charge or
trial.
</TEXT>
