<FIRST>r a PM-SovietConference 1stLd-Writethru a0493 10-31 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editor a No-Show Over Gorbachev Poll</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to say poll found Gorbachev less popular than dissident
sted poll criticized Gorbachev. Pick up 2nd graf pvs: Vladislav Starkov...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20 Soviet journalists are attending a
conference on issues including outer space and pollution. Absent
was an editor who's doing penance for publishing a recent poll that
found Mikhail Gorbachev less popular than a leading dissident.
   Vladislav Starkov was to appear at the fifth General Chautauqua
Conference on U.S.-Soviet Relations.
   But Leonid Drobrokhotov, a senior member of the Soviet Central
Committee of the Communist Party, said the liberal editor of the
26-million circulation weekly, Arguments and Facts, was strongly
urged to remain at home to resolve problems arising from the poll.
   ``We have a very difficult situation now in the country,''
Drobrokhotov said at news conference Monday. ``He has a great
responsibility for correct information and for this reason, the
best way is for him to be in Moscow.
   ``He is a communist and we have the right to advise members of
the Communist Party what to do and what not to do.''
   Gorbachev reportedly called for Starkov's resignation after the
weekly, the country's most popular newspaper, published a reader
survey indicating human rights activist Andrei Sakharov was more
popular than the Soviet president.
   Soviet lawmakers, the newspaper's workers and other editors
rallied in Starkov's defense, and he was not fired.
   Dobrokhotov said Gorbachev told Starkov, ``I'm waiting for the
correct results.''
   The following edition that appeared Oct. 20 was a chastened
version of Arguments and Facts. The lead story confessed that the
first poll was an unscientific sampling of readers' letters and
included what it described as a scientific poll in which
Gorbachev's performance got a favorable assessment from the
majority of respondents.
   Yuri Ustimenko, chief editor of the American desk of the
official Soviet news agency Tass, said the Starkov case does not
represent a tightening of restrictions on Soviet journalists.
   ``It's an exceptional case. I don't see any trend or any
pressures,'' he said. ``It's very unlike Gorbachev to demand the
resignation of a particular editor.''
   Although Dobrokhotov acknowledged that polls in the Soviet Union
are not always correct, he said they nevertheless must be conducted
scientifically.
   ``The criticism toward Starkov was not because he had his own
point of view,'' Dobrokhotov said. ``But he did not objectively
reflect the real opinion of the public. He agreed this public
opinion poll was not correct. The results of the second poll
reflect more objectively the real situation in the country.''
   Dobrokhotov said the decision to delay Starkov's visit abroad
was not punishment but rather ``an objective solution.''
   The conference in Pittsburgh is sponsored by the University of
Pittsburgh and Chautauqua Institution in western New York.
   About 200 Soviet delegates, ranging from laborers to
psychiatrists, are staying with Pittsburgh area residents.
   ``This is citizens' diplomacy versus official diplomacy,'' said
Vladimir V. Petrovsky, Soviet deputy minister of foreign affairs.
``It's a place for a new kind of exchange.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
