<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HalloweenLiability     10-31 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Halloween Liability,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scaring Up Insurance For Haunted Houses Can Be Tough</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children delight in the axe-wielding
psychopaths, monsters, ghosts and other horrors of haunted houses
each Halloween. It's the insurance companies that are spooked.
   Civic groups that set up haunted houses to entertain children
and raise money are finding that scaring up insurance can be
expensive and tough, especially if insurers think the house's
attractions are dangerous.
   ``Some of (the haunted houses) are innocuous. But some get
pretty involved, with people jumping out and grabbing you, hanging
nooses and open flame,'' said Fran Brown, underwriter at Crump E &amp;
S of Florida Inc., an insurance broker.
   Moving staircases are frowned on too, because they could cause
people to lose their balance and fall, Brown said.
   Because of the possibility of injury and damage, most insurers
do not offer coverage. And those that do may charge thousands of
dollars for the few days the house operates.
   The Brookfield High School Band Parents are paying $1,439 for
property and liability insurance for a haunted house they hope will
raise $10,000 for a band trip.
   ``I think it's a very excessive amount,'' said Noel Costa, vice
president of fund-raising for the parents.
   But insurers say prices are based on what they perceive to be
the risk.
   Liability insurance alone can cost $750 to $12,000 depending on
how elaborate the house is and how much coverage is sought, Brown
said.
   Rates are also based on the number of visitors expected and the
length of time the haunted house will be open, she said.
   Major insurance companies seldom sell temporary policies for
spook houses. Hartford's Travelers Corp., for example, says it is
not financially feasible to sell them.
   Some companies, like Massachussetts-based Lexington Insurance
Co., are picky about what they'll insure and what they won't.
Lexington avoids insuring houses with rolling floors for fear they
will collapse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
