<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneTurbulence     10-31 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Turbulence,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Injured When Jet Hits Turbulence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen seconds of turbulence that one
passenger likened to the San Francisco earthquake sent drinks
flying and knocked people into partitions, injuring seven aboard an
American Airlines flight.
   The Boeing 747 en route from San Juan, Puerto Rico, to Detroit
with 100 passengers and seven crew members landed as scheduled at
Nashville International Airport on Monday night after weathering
the turbulence over the Atlantic.
   ``It was hair-raising,'' said passenger Sharon Hart of Dallas.
``People were flying all over the place, and the drink cart was
totaled.''
   ``I was in the earthquake in San Francisco, and it was just like
that,'' said Mervyn Gorouszy. ``Suddenly we just dropped. Bang.
People were hitting their heads on the bulkhead.''
   Three passengers and four crew members complaining of such
ailments as sore backs and shoulder and hip pain were treated at a
hospital, officials said.
   The turbulence hit about 90 miles north of Nassau in the
Bahamas, at 31,000 feet, said American spokesman Al Becker. The jet
was checked for damage, then continued on to Detroit.
   The Federal Aviation Administration will investigate, officials
said.
   Passengers said that they noticed clouds gathering moments
before the incident and that the seat belt sign had not been turned
on. But John Raymond, another American spokesman, said the jet
encountered unforeseeable ``clear air turbulence.''
   ``There is no scientific way to predict it, but fortunately it
doesn't happen very often,'' he said.
</TEXT>
