<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     10-31 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Asks Jesse Jackson to Intervene with Bush Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said he has
asked the Rev. Jesse Jackson to persuade U.S. officials and
lawmakers to support the disbanding of the Nicaraguan Contra rebel
force.
   A presidential communique said Ortega spoke by telephone Monday
with Jackson, an unsuccessful candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination last year.
   Frank Watkins, a Chicago spokesman for Jackson, said Jackson was
in Washington when he spoke with Ortega. Jackson did not issue a
statement on the conversation.
   Ortega said in his statement that he asked Jackson to try to
have U.S. money allotted for the Contras diverted to the United
Nations and the Organization of American States. He said that would
speed demobilization of the rebels and assure the Nicaraguan
elections set for Feb. 25 would be held in peace.
   ``We asked ... Jackson to focus his mediation efforts on (having
the United States) stop placing obstacles on the demobilization of
the Contras,'' the communique said.
   Ortega stunned a meeting of 17 nations at a Costa Rican
independence celebration on Saturday by announcing he intended to
suspend the 1{-year-old cease-fire in the government's war with the
rebels.
   He accused the rebels of disrupting voter registration by
ambushing security units and intimidating citizens. Ortega said he
would make a final decision on the truce by today.
   At the United Nations in New York, Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar urged Ortega to extend the truce.
   In a message to Ortega the U.N. chief said Monday he shared
Ortega's concern about ``the attacks which the Resistance (Contras)
have been carrying out despite the cease-fire, which has been
observed in general terms since March 1988.''
   But, he said, war in Nicaragua would hurt peace efforts for
Central America as a whole.
   In Washington, presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater
said the Bush administration was ``waiting and watching'' to see
what action Ortega takes.
   ``We, obviously, are urging that the cease-fire be maintained,''
he said.
   About 11,000 Contras withdrew to camps on the Honduran side of
the border after the United States suspended weapons and ammunition
supplies in February 1988. An estimated 2,000 to 3,000 are in
Nicaragua, conducting sporadic attacks.
   Washington has continued non-lethal aid to the rebels.
   Under an agreement signed Aug. 7 in Tela, Honduras, by Ortega
and four other Central American presidents, the Contras are to
disband and be relocated from their Honduran base camps by Dec. 8.
   In exchange, Ortega's Sandinista government advanced the date
for presidential elections to Feb. 25 and promised political
reforms, including greater campaign freedom for the opposition.
   Government and Contra leaders signed a cease-fire agreement
March 23, 1988. Talks broke down the following month but the
government has declared monthly unilateral cease-fires since the
temporary truce expired.
</TEXT>
