<FIRST>u w PM-EmploymentCosts     10-31 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Employment Costs,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rising Wages, Benefit Costs Push Employment Costs Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost to employers to pay the wages and
benefits of workers climbed 1.6 percent in the third quarter and
5.1 percent in the past year, with health insurance premiums again
driving up benefit costs at a faster pace than salaries, the
government said today.
   The 1.6 percent gain was up from a 1.3 percent increase in the
July-September period last year. The 5.1 percent jump in overall
compensation costs for the year ended last month was up from 4.7
percent for the 12 months ending in September 1988, the Labor
Department said.
   The department's Employment Cost Index report confirms that
tight labor markets and rising health care costs are driving up the
cost of doing business. But the biggest wage gains came in the
government sector, where the pricetag for salaries is traditionally
higher in the third quarter because of new contracts for teachers
and other public employees. Wages in the private sector grew at a
faster rate than last year but the gains have not been as
pronounced as some analysts have predicted.
   Excluding benefits' costs, wages and salaries rose 1.6 percent
in the quarter for all civilian workers _ double the 0.8 percent
gain posted in the second quarter, with state and local government
workers posting a 3.1 percent gain largely because of new
collective bargaining agreements. The wage gains for private-sector
workers averaged 1.2 percent in the third quarter, up from 1.0
percent compared to both the second qyarter and the July-September
period last year.
   For the year ended last month, wages and salaries for all
civilian rose 4.6 percent, up from 4.3 percent for the 12 months
ending in June and up from the 3.9 percent year-to-year gain posted
at this time last year. Because of tight labor markets,
particularly in high-skilled fields, economists have been
predicting persistent, if not dramatic, wage inflation.
   The wages and salaries for private sector workers were up 4.4
percent in the last 12 months, compared to 4.1 percent for the year
ending in June and 3.7 percent from October 1987-September 1988.
   Here again the wage gains were greater for state and local
government workers, whose wages and salaries climbed 5.5 percent in
the last year, up from 5.0 percent for the 12 months ending in June
and 4.7 percent year-to-year gain posted at this time last year.
   Salaries for school teachers, college and university professors
and health and hospital workers in the public sector all rose by
more than 6 percent in the last 12 months, the Labor Department
said. Union workers continue on average to make more than non-union
workers but the year-to-year wage gains on non-union employees were
nearly double those of union workers, 4.9 percent compared to 2.5
percent, continuing a six-year trend.
   On paper, the data reflected some relief for employers, who have
seen the costs of benefits in general and health care costs in
particular skyrocket in recent years.
   The third quarter increase in benefits costs was 1.4 percent,
down slightly from the 1.6 percent posted for the three months
ending in June, the government said.
   For the year ended last month, the costs of benefits alone grew
by 6.0 percent, up from 5.6 percent for the year ending in June but
down significantly from the 6.7 percent increase posted last year.
The decline, however, is almost entirely attributable to the fact
that the Social Security tax did not rise this year. It rose 5.0
percent last year and drove up overall benefit costs.
</TEXT>
