<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial     10-31 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Questioning of Potential Jurors Continues in Police Shooting Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said she feared riots might break out
if a policeman is acquitted in the slaying of a black motorcyclist
was among five people excused as potential jurors at the officer's
manslaughter trial.
   Lawyers on Monday began questioning potential jurors one at a
time about their knowledge of the Jan. 16 shooting, which touched
off three days of rioting that left one person dead and caused
millions in damage.
   People were called into the courtroom from a jury pool created
last week and were asked how they felt about past riots and the
potential for more violence after a verdict.
   A white woman in her 50s said she couldn't put aside her fear of
violence and was dismissed.
   ``It's frightening,'' she said. ``You're afraid that if you were
on the jury and brought in a verdict the black community didn't
want to hear, there'd be rioting.''
   In all, nine people were retained and five excused Monday. Those
excused included two men and a woman, all white, who had formed
strong opinions on the case, and a black woman with seven children.
   Selection of potential jurors was to continue today.
   The trial of Colombian-born William Lozano, 30, has raised fears
of more violence in Miami, which erupted in 1980, 1982 and 1984
after slayings of black men by police or the officers' acquittals.
   The Miami officer is charged in the deaths of Clement Anthony
Lloyd, 23, who was shot in the head during a chase, and Allan
Blanchard, 24, a passenger killed in the crash of Lloyd's
motorcycle.
   Lozano contends he fired in self-defense.
   Some of those questioned said there was the potential for unrest
whichever way the verdict went.
   ``There's two sides and somebody's going to be dissatisfied,''
said one middle-aged woman. She was retained for the jury pool.
   This year's disturbance started on the Martin Luther King
holiday and came as Miami got ready to be host of the Super Bowl.
</TEXT>
