<FIRST>r a PM-TooeleGroundbreaking     10-31 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tooele Groundbreaking,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ground Broken For Nation's First Chemical Weapons Disposal Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tooele is pronounced too-EL-luh.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOOELE ARMY DEPOT, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the United States and Soviets
resumed talks at the United Nations on reducing chemical weapons,
ground was broken on a windswept plain here on the first plant with
that goal in mind.
   The plant, scheduled for completion in 1992, is the first of
eight planned in the continental United States for dismantling and
incinerating old mustard and nerve gas weapons, many of which date
from World War II.
   Ronald Lehman II, the Bush administration's chief arms
negotiator, said Monday that construction of the $212 million plant
represented the ``leading edge'' of the U.N. talks 2,500 miles away.
   The facility is 50 miles southwest of Salt Lake City on a
sagebrush-strewn corner of the Tooele Army Depot dotted with
concrete igloos housing more than 40 percent of the nation's aging
chemical stockpile.
   Lehman and others said renewed negotiations at the United
Nations in New York and talks at the U.N. Disarmament Conference in
Geneva had bolstered hopes for limiting and ultimately destroying
old chemical weapons.
   Both nations have called for the destruction of existing
chemical weapons but differ on the timetable and the rules under
which new ``binary'' chemical weapons might be manufactured.
   Binary weapons contain two chemicals that are not harmful until
combined for use.
</TEXT>
