<FIRST>r a PM-BoatSinks     10-31 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat Sinks,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cruise Ship Converted to Restaurant Sinks Suddenly at Dockside</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cruise ship converted into a dockside
restaurant mysteriously rolled over and sank in the harbor with a
shattering of glass as a security guard who had gone aboard to
investigate popping noises scrambled ashore.
   ``She fell splat into the water and then it was glog, glog,
glog,'' said Michael Barnes, first mate of a passenger ship nearby
Monday.
   The 68-year-old S.S. Princess Louise, which had plied the
Pacific for decades before being retired, went down in 23 feet of
water, leaving half the 331-foot, 6,000-ton vessel submerged, Fire
Department spokesman Jim Wells said.
   The cause of the sinking was under investigation.
   The security guard escaped without injury. No one else was
aboard; the ship had closed its restaurant in January.
   ``Chairs started flying all over the place, glass was breaking.
I was just trying to get out of there,'' said the guard, Minnie
Morgan.
   The Princess Louise Restaurant, a fixture on the harbor for two
decades, fell on hard times last year and went out of business. It
is now owned by the Bank of San Pedro and was being refurbished for
sale when it sank.
   The ship had spent three weeks in dry dock for some hull work
and had been put back in the water last week, said Lance Oak, bank
president and chief executive officer. He said the ship was insured
for $1.5 million.
   Built in 1921, the Princess Louise ferried passengers between
Vancouver, British Columbia, and Alaskan ports. It was converted to
a restaurant ship in 1966.
   Its seven banquet rooms and three dining rooms could accommodate
1,200 diners.
</TEXT>
