<DOCNO> AP891031-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Guns-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0546 10-31 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guns-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0546,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colt Semiautomatic Rifle is Gun of Choice Among Colombian Drug-Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 6th graf pvs bgng, `Drug traffickers,' with 1 graf to UPDATE
figures on bombings, killings; INSERTS 1 graf after 12th graf pvs bgng,
`Colt Industries' to UPDATE with quote from Colt spokesman; Colt Industries
Inc, no period, is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gun of choice among Colombia's drug
traffickers is the Colt AR-15 semiautomatic assault-style rifle,
say U.S. firearms officials tracing the guns seized in that
country's drug crackdown.
   Most guns traced thus far were delivered either individually or
in small batches, dispelling the notion that huge shipments of guns
are heading to Colombia, say officials with the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms.
   The ATF said it needs to send agents to Colombia permanently to
get more information on the guns being seized.
   ``My understanding is the Colombia officials think that is a
good way to proceed'' and Drug Enforcement Administration and
Treasury Department officials also support the plan, ATF Director
Stephen E. Higgins said in an interview Monday. State Department
spokeswoman Catherine Shaw said she expects the ATF proposal to be
approved.
   Colombian President Virgilio Barco and then-Colombian Justice
Minister Monica de Greiff called on the United States in September
to help halt gun shipments to drug traffickers who declared ``total
war'' on the government after it launched a crackdown in August.
   Drug traffickers have been held responsible for many shootings
as well as 237 bombings in the past 10 weeks that killed 33 people
and injured 222.
   During the summer, two ATF agents went to Colombia to help trace
the guns being used and to train Colombians in firearms
identification, Higgins said.
   Thus far, the ATF has traced 242 of the 700 weapons on which
Colombia has sought information, according to ATF spokesman Jack
Killorin.
   The most popular weapon among the guns traced thus far is the
Colt-manufactured AR-15 semiautomatic assault-style rifle, but many
other weapons also have turned up, he said.
   ``They cover the gamut,'' Killorin said. ``There are a lot of
rifles, AR-15s, some Mac-11s, also some traditional Colt .45
pistols and Smith and Wesson revolvers. The single most prevalent
weapon in the trace is the AR-15.''
   The AR-15 was the most popular U.S.-made weapon similar to the
imported AK-47 and Uzi carbines that were banned from the United
States in the spring.
   Colt Industries Inc suspended retail sales of the AR-15 after
the Bush Administration imposed a temporary import suspension on
the foreign-made semiautomatic assault-style weapons in March.
Company spokesman Mike Dunn said today that sales to U.S.
government agencies and law enforcement continue.
   It was unclear exactly how each of the AR-15s wound up in the
hands of the Colombians, but Dunn said, ``We don't sell guns to
drug dealers.''
   Killorin said the information uncovered thus far rebuts the
``perception that things are leaving the country by huge shiploads
of thousands of guns. That's not true. What appears to be going on
is very widespread small purchases, not in any particular organized
fashion, more opportunistic.''
   Typically, he said, a cocaine cartel employee in Florida
awaiting a big drug shipment might ``wander into a gun store and
buy a couple of guns,'' and hand them over to other cartel workers
who deliver the cocaine, he said.
   But some cartel employees have sought to buy much larger
quantities of weapons from ATF agents working undercover as
gun-sellers, he said.
   ``They've been approached by people working for one or the other
cartel, seeing what they can pick up,'' he said. The buyers
occasionally have sought to purchase 100 to 200 guns as well as
``things not available, for example, machine guns.''
   During the summer, Customs Service officials ``grabbed 37 rifles
on an airplane going down to Barranquilla, Colombia,'' he said.
``We were able to run down those guns, lock up some of the
purchasers. We found they had bought an additional number of guns,
about 150'' prior to the bust. Those guns were not recovered.
   One reason the ATF wants to base agents in Colombia is the lack
of specific information coming from government officials there,
Killorin said.
   ``We're hearing reports and the Colombians are saying they're
seizing thousands of weapons,'' he said. ``We're getting lists of
guns, but not the kind of information like, `These are hot off a
Medellin seizure, off Pablo Escobar's boudoir.''' Escobar reputedly
is a leader of the Medellin cartel.
</TEXT>
