<FIRST>r a PM-WaterDeathTrial     10-31 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Death Trial,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mom Acquitted Of Most Serious Charges After Son Dies From Too Much
Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother whose boy died from being forced
to drink up to nine quarts of water was convicted of involuntary
manslaughter but cleared of murder after claiming she was trying to
flush stale sherbet out of his system.
   Angela West, 30, was convicted Monday in the 1988 death of
6-year-old Christopher West and was sentenced to 12 years in
prison. She could have received the death penalty if found guilty
of murder.
   Prosecutors contended Ms. West and her boyfriend, Jonathan
Crawford, forced Christopher to drink the water to punish him for
eating lime sherbet without permission.
   Doctors said the water caused the boy's brain to swell, leading
to seizures and death.
   Defense attorneys said the two were trying to get the sherbet
out of Christopher's system because it was 3 weeks old and they
believed it was dangerously stale. Prosecutors said there was no
evidence the dessert posed any danger.
   ``We believed, like they said, that they were trying to flush
out his system and it somehow went haywire and it was too late to
realize what was happening,'' said juror Belinda Lynn.
   Prosecutor Steve Balog said he was disappointed in the verdict,
which came after three days of deliberations.
   ``I think it is difficult for the average person, including the
average juror, to believe that a mother will d this to her child,
so I'm sure that was a factor in the case,'' he said.
   Crawford was found guilty of murder earlier this year and
sentenced to life in prison.
</TEXT>
