<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Summit 1stLd-Writethru a0562 10-31 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0562,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Superpower Summit to be Informal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Shevardnadze comment on report that main
purpose of summit is for Soviets to seek economic aid, NATO comment; no
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first summit between President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and President Bush will be an informal meeting to help
them get acquainted and will not cover any major issues, the Soviet
foreign minister said today.
   Eduard A. Shevardnadze bristled at the suggestion the unexpected
meeting will be held so the Kremlin can ask for U.S. aid for its
faltering and shortage-plagued economy.
   The summit, set for Dec. 2-3 aboard U.S. and Soviet warships in
the Mediterranean, was announced simultaneously in Moscow and
Washington.
   Gorbachev is to visit Italy from Nov. 29 to Dec. 1.
   Shevardnadze said the superpowers do not plan to reach agreement
on any specific issue at the unusual meeting on Soviet and American
ships. He said the talks are intended to set the stage for a
``full-scale summit'' in the United States in the first six months
of 1990.
   ``The upcoming talks between the Soviet and American leaders
will be informal, aimed at allowing them to know each other
better,'' Shevardnadze told reporters.
   He said the meeting ``should be regarded as the most important
stage in preparing negotiations which will take place during the
official state visit by Mikahil Gorbachev'' to the United States
next year.
   Of the December summit, Shevardnadze said: ``I do not doubt that
this meeting between the two leaders would contribute to broadening
the changes taking place in the Soviet-American relationship.''
   Later, taking reporters' questions, Shevardnadze reacted with
visible displeasure when asked whether a Washington Post report in
today's editions was correct in saying the key element of the
December summit would be the Kremlin's quest for American economic
aid.
   ``I would ask you not to use this term _ `to help the Soviet
economy,''' Shevardnadze retorted.
   The Kremlin's current economic reforms are the affair of the
Soviet people alone, who seek ``mutually advantageous cooperation''
in trade and other fields with the Americans, he said.
   ``This meeting is not directly connected with perestroika,''
Shevardnadze said.
   In Brussels, Belgium, Manfred Woerner, the secretary-general of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, called the summit ``a
useful opportunity to discuss and improve East-West relations.''
   Woerner, according to a NATO spokesman, thinks the meeting is
``clearly of interest not only to the major powers but is ... in
the interests of the entire alliance.''
   Shevardnadze refused to identify the naval vessels on which the
Bush-Gorbachev summit will take place.
   Bush, then president-elect, attended the last meeting of
superpower leaders in New York in December 1988 when Ronald Reagan
was president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
