<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru a0502 10-31 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Votes to Hold Referendum on Timing of Presidential Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with parliament setting date
for national referendum on presidential election; pickup 5th graf pvs,
`The Socialist...' ^By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament voted today to hold a
national referendum on when and how to elect someone to fill the
new post of president.
   The house voted to hold the referendum Nov. 26, the date that
had tentatively been chosen for a popular vote to select a
president under an agreement signed by the ruling Socialist Party
and most of the major opposition groups.
   But two opposition groups, the League of Free Democrats and the
League of Young Democrats, had opposed that. They collected more
than 200,000 signatures on petitions calling for a referendum on
the method and timing of such elections.
   The groups want the president chosen by parliament after the
general elections, which are to be held by June. They say they need
more time to organize an effective campaign to make their
candidates better known.
   The agreement between the Socialists and most opposition groups
had called for a one-time popular vote to select a president, with
parliament choosing all subsequent presidents.
   If Hungarians vote in favor of electing a president before the
parliamentary elections next year, the presidential balloting would
be conducted Jan. 7, the lawmakers decided today.
   The presidency was created by constitutional amendments adopted
two weeks ago and the office's responsibilities include command of
the armed forces and calling elections.
   The Socialist Party is the successor to the Communist party,
which dissolved itself at a congress this month. The Socialists
promise to end one-party rule and replace it with constitutional
democracy.
   Hungarian legislators today also planned to discuss and vote on
government proposals on a suspended Danube river hydroelectric
project with Czechoslovakia. Hungary has been increasingly at odds
with that Warsaw Pact ally over the project's suspension and
Hungary's path of reform.
   Czechoslovakia's Communist leaders have refused to ease their
tight control of society and allow any degree of power-sharing.
   In declaring a moratorium in May on the Gabcikovo-Nagymaros dam
project, the Hungarian government expressed concern about potential
enviromental damage. Czechoslovakia has said it will continue
construction and demand compensation if the Hungarians don't rejoin
the project.
   On Monday, Parliament overwhelmingly approved legislation
creating a state auditor's office to control government and party
finances.
   The laws, to take effect in November, were among several on the
agenda on the opening day of Parliament's first session since it
rewrote the Communist constitution to embrace democratic ideals.
   At its previous session, which ended Oct. 20, Parliament adopted
a series of laws and constitutional amendments establishing the
legal framework for the first multiparty elections since the
Communists consolidated power in 1948.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
