<FIRST>u w PM-Summit 7thLd-Writethru a0566-a0567 10-31 1204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0566-a0567,12. Merc spot per 00</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Gorbachev to Hold Shipboard Summit in December</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, new material and editing throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush announced today he would hold a
shipboard summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Dec. 2
and 3 aboard American and Soviet naval vessels in the
Mediterranean. A similar announcement came simultaneously from
Moscow.
   ``It's a chance to put our feet up and talk,'' Be the fallout, so be
it.''
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, questioned by reporters about the
summit, said, ``I think it's a very positive thing.'' He also
expressed his hope that the U.S.-Soviet session will ``stimulate
greater speed in moving on the arms control proposal.''
   An early Bush meeting with Gorbachev could give the
administration an opportunity to underscore its support for the
Soviet leader's program for restructuring the Soviet economy.
   Baker said in a speech Oct. 16 that the United States was
prepared to provide Moscow with advice and technical assistance. He
said perestroika presented a ``historic opportunity'' to make a
lasting improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations.
   In an interview Monday, Baker said Gorbachev ``clearly faces
some very major problems.'' But, Baker told The Associated Press,
``it would be a mistake, notwithstanding that, just to stand pat.
We ought to try and take advantage of what we think is an
opportunity.''
   Bush's predecessor, Ronald Reagan, initially was skeptical of
Soviet motives in arms control negotiations and East-West relations
generally. But he held five meetings with Gorbachev after the
Soviet leader took power in 1985.
   Baker said at this point ``there are only nuances of
differences'' among senior U.S. officials on whether Gorbachev can
succeed in coping with ``extraordinary problems'' as he tries to
transform the country politically and economically.
   Calling that a question of ``durability,'' Baker said, ``I don't
think there is any policy difference in the administration on the
question of the desirability'' of the Soviet leader's perestroika
policy.
   Baker's comments were designed to put to rest the notion that
differences among top officials were slowing a U.S. response to
Gorbachev's bold approaches, particularly in Eastern Europe.
   Just last week, Baker acted to quash a speech by Robert M.
Gates, the deputy national security adviser, that took a
pessimistic view of Gorbachev's chances after Baker in two speeches
had set forth the administration's position welcoming the changes
in the Soviet Union. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has voiced
reservations similar to those in Gates' speech.
   A decision was made to hold the meeting on two ships in the
Mediterranean, said a senior administration official who briefed
reporters on the condition of anonymity, `because they wanted it
informal, isolated'' and to promote the concept of neutrality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
