<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SajakShow     10-31 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sajak Show,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Unveils Slimmed-Down `Pat Sajak Show'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moving faster than a speeding bullet, though not
at all as powerful as a locomotive, CBS' ``The Pat Sajak Show'' has
begun life anew with a 60-minute format.
   Sajak's late-night talk show, begun in January, was a relatively
leisurely 90-minute affair that failed to yield Nielsen results
against NBC's ``Tonight Show'' and Arsenio Hall's syndicated talk
and music festival.
   Hmm, said CBS, let us tighten Sajak to one hour. The network
even installed a vice president, Rod Perth, to oversee the
retooling.
   The result, which made its debut Monday from Los Angeles,
indicates that CBS thinks salvation lies in a far brisker pace and
more high energy.
   If so, CBS is out of its nut.
   Sajak, tieless and wearing a gray jacket that matched the show's
gray sofa, joked with announcer Dan Miller about the new format,
said haste is needed, but claimed that the hour format is a better
one.
   That done, he welcomed Joan Rivers, who recently began her own
syndicated talk show. Looking slightly haggard but quite energetic,
Rivers commenced a rapid-fire string of observations, some on the
tasteless side.
   Inquiring minds who wanted to know and those who didn't learned
about her flu attack and gastrointestinal state; about breasts, and
what happens to California women whose string bikinis are too
tight. She also said she took Marlon Brando to Marineland for sushi.
   She kidded Sajak, 43, several times about his fiancee before
assailing _ just joking, of course _ the lady's character in what
proved to be her exit line.
   Enter jazz-rock violinist Jean-Luc Ponty. He played fast and
furiously, then was grilled by Sajak on such issues as why he took
up violin and his early problems with English. Ponty talked fairly
slowly.
   The final visitor, ``Chicken Soup'' co-star Lynn Redgrave, spoke
quickly of the silliness of censorship and playfully emitted a few
not-so-shocking examples of what some might still consider naughty.
She also said, with pride, that her 8-year-old daughter has two
lines of dialogue on tonight's Halloween episode.
   Censoring herself, Redgrave said her show is on a network whose
name ``begins with the first letter of the alphabet.'' Sajak,
casting caution to the airwaves, later said the show was on ABC.
   It was a strained night of fast pace and forgettable chatter. No
doubt it was due to a platoon of network executives who proposed so
many ideas that the show's suggestion box suffered a double hernia.
   Sajak may not be to blame for the poor restart of his series.
His manner is low-key. Asking him to go supersonic is folly. Those
who knew his early TV work in Nashville, particularly in the
late-movie announcer's booth, say he has an Ernie Kovacs mind.
   If that's the case, CBS might ask him what it was he did there
and give it a whirl. He might be able to build a following.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
