<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--GamelessHomecoming     10-31 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gameless Homecoming,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homecoming Goes on Despite Lack of Football Team</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARMET, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marmet Junior High School's annual
homecoming event was complete with a halftime ceremony featuring a
marching band and the crowning of a queen. What was missing was the
football game.
   The school's team disbanded several weeks ago after the coach
quit, but that was no reason to cancel the homecoming celebration.
   ``It was already scheduled so we went ahead and held it,''
acting Principal James Dillinger said. ``It would be like not
having a prom in high school.''
   Last week, students led a parade through Marmet to the football
field, where a homecoming queen was crowned before hundreds of
spectators. The ceremony ended with introductions of the football
team.
   ``It's a little bit unusual,'' the principal said. ``It would be
nicer to have a football game.''

</TEXT>
