<FIRST>r a PM-VietnameseStowaway 1stLd-Writethru a0520 10-31 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnamese Stowaway, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0520,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Stowaway Denied Asylum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with State Department denying asylum
but INS reviewing it; PICKS UP 8th graf, `The crew...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese man who escaped from
his homeland by lashing himself to the rudder housing of a tanker
for two days in monsoon seas has been denied asylum in the United
States, a senator said today.
   The request for immediate asylum was rejected by the State
Department, but the Immigration and Naturalization Service will
allow the stowaway to stay in the country while it reviews the
request, said Bill Bryant, a spokesman for Sen. Claiborne Pell,
D-R.I.
   Bryant did not know how long the review would take.
   The Polish captain of the tanker has taken up the cause of the
23-year-old man, discovered during a routine lifeboat drill two
days out of Ho Chi Minh City.
   ``I know what living in a closed society is like,'' the captain,
Jerzy Kolasinski, said Monday, when the man was interviewed here by
INS officers.
   Officials refused to release the name of the stowaway, who was
met by immigration officials when the tanker docked at the Mobil
Oil Co. terminal Monday. He was confined to the ship pending the
appeal.
   The crew of the Cypriot tanker Success made two checks of the
ship for stowaways before leaving Ho Chi Minh City, Kolasinski
said. Then, on Aug. 30, they spotted the man, perched on a
makeshift plywood seat on the rudder housing, about four feet above
the water.
   He had been exposed to the waves and 100-degree heat for more
than 48 hours while the ship steamed down the Saigon River into the
South China Sea, the captain said.
   The refugee had only a container of water that was almost empty,
a package of cigarettes and a butane lighter, and had tied himself
to the ship with a length of hemp, Kolasinski said.
   ``This was ... the monsoon season in the southwest China Sea. It
was very stormy and he could have been washed off at any time,''
the captain said.
   Kolasinski detoured to Singapore and asked immigration officials
there to take the man. They refused, citing their lack of
diplomatic ties with the communist country, he said.
   The captain said he also tried seeking asylum for the man in
Bahrain in the Persian Gulf; Dubai, part of the United Arab
Emirates and Yambu in Saudi Arabia.
   ``Nobody cared about this man,'' Kolasinski said. ``He is
normal, intelligent person, and a normal person would not have
risked what he did for economic reasons.''
   The man, communicating to the Polish crew in sign language,
volunteered to work for passage, and Kolasinski said he was kept
busy with odd jobs.
   The ship's insurance agent, William W. Whit, a representative of
Lloyds of London, said that if the asylum request is denied,
Lloyd's will be responsible for returning the man to Vietnam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-BushText 3rdAdd   10-31 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush Text, 3rd Add,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: ...your question.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q: Mr. President?
   A: Yes, Maureen? Let me get there in back.
   Q: Mr. President, but then what changed your mind? Because this
is exactly the kind of meeting that you and your aides have been
saying for months, you did not want, and it seems exactly the kind
of meeting that Gorbachev, given his domestic troubles, needs very,
very much. What changed your mind, and why were you the one _
   A: My _ I'll tell you what changed my mind on it was
consultation with our allies; the rapidity of change in Eastern
Europe; the emergence of democracies in this hemisphere; and this
concept that I just didn't want to, in this time of dynamic change,
miss something, something that I might get better first-hand from
Mr. Gorbachev. Yes, in the back.
   Q: Mr. President _
   Q: Mr. President, what made you decide to meet on a ship?
   A: Well, we can do it without too much fanfare. We can do it
without _ where there's a relatively few number of people, not a
lot of crush of bodies out there, and a _ chance to put our feet up
and talk in the kind of meeting that I have just described for you.
And it will _ I think it's easy logistically for both sides.
   Q: How much time do you think you will spend face to face? In
your mind, what do you think it's going to take to get _
   A: A lot. A lot. And I can't tell you in hours, but we're going
to have small numbers of participants on both sides. I _ maybe I'm
getting a little ahead of the power curve there, but I know that's
my intention and I think the Soviet side has agreed to that and
it'll _ by doing it in this manner, we can have, I would say, more
time without the press of social activities or mandatory joint
appearances, things of that nature for public consumption.
   Q: Mr. President, between hemispheric summits and drug summits
and Gorbachev summits and economic summits, you're doing a lot of
mountaineering. Let me ask you this _
   A: This one isn't a summit. So scratch this one off your list of
things to worry about. I've got to make that point over and over
again. ``Summits'' take on a definition, an expectation of grand
design and grand agreements, and that's not what this is.
   Q: Let me ask you about this expectation then. About six months
ago, you proposed your conventional force reductions for Europe. If
something came through on your six-month deadline, presumably you
would want a summit with Mr. Gorbachev to sign it. Are we going to
have a third Gorbachev summit in 1990?
   A: No anticipation of it. But, look, we'll meet as often or as
little as we need to.
   Q: Well, how is that going? How is the conventional forces thing
going?
   A: Reasonably well. We still have to driving for the best we
can, our alliance, to be sure that we keep moving forward to meet a
rather ambitious time frame. Dave, and then we'll go back.
   Q: Mr. President, one of the criticisms that's been made is _ by
the Democrats particularly _ is that this is a really unique time
for you, that after 40 years of calling for free markets and open
society, that you have chance to perhaps cement some of these
changes in the Eastern Bloc in Europe and in the Soviet Union? Do
you have some kind of plan or vision for getting that accomplished?
Is this part of it?
   A: We're seeing it move, aren't we? We're seeing dynamic change,
and I want to handle it properly. I want to do whatever the U.S.
can do to facilitate these kinds of changes. You heard what I had
to say yesterday _ some of you all did _ in terms of Poland and the
group we're sending over there to help solidify the changes that
are taking place. And I've got a good group of people working with
me in this administration, knowledgeable about Europe, that assures
me that we can move this whole process _ process forward properly.
Some things have to _ the United States can't wave a wand, and say
how fast change is going to come to Czechoslovakia or to the GDR.
Way in the back. Carl, and Craig.
   Q: Mr. President, you say there will be no agreements at this
meeting. Is it possible, however, that you might firm up the date
for the meeting next year, for the official meeting?
   A: Could be. Could be. And I don't want to say that _ I guess
maybe I ought to retreat a little, and say _ not saying there would
be no agreements. The meeting is not being set up to achieve
agreements. I would hope we'd see eye to eye on certain things when
we get through, and maybe more narrowly define _ more precisely
define what differences we have. Craig, and then John.
   
