<FIRST>r a AM-HauntedCrackHouse 1stLd-Writethru a0589 10-31 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haunted Crack House, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0589,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Town's House of Drug Horrors Attracts More Than 1,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts third graf to delete reference to ``tonight.'' Also
moved for PMs ^LaserPhoto BA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER BRANDLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CENTREVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 people have lined up for
hours to see the fate of teen-age drug abusers in a ``haunted crack
house'' in this rural town, where the police chief says no real
cocaine dens exist.
   Since this Eastern Shore village of 2,000 opened its Halloween
attraction late last week, children and adults have mobbed the town
square to enter the house of horrors in the former county jail.
   On Monday evening, the night before the final performance, the
line started forming 1{ hours before the first show.
   ``They say it's real spooky. They say it's going to scare you to
death. ... It's supposed to teach you a lesson,'' Randy Robinson, a
high school student from nearby Grasonville, said as he waited to
get in.
   ``Some of them go through two or three times. I don't think it's
just that it's such a good scare, I think people just like what's
going on in there,'' said Leon Demby, a volunteer who portrays
``Mr. Cocaine'' in one scene. ``Some people think this should have
been done a long time ago.''
   Visitors tour 11 stations starting with a courtroom starring a
real-life judge and ending with a graveyard, where actors in black
costumes and white makeup beg for help from their tombs.
   The show was organized by and stars dozens of local government
workers, members of civic groups and high school drama club
members, who rallied around the idea proposed by Police Chief John
Lechliter.
   ``Every time you pick up a newspaper, what do you see? Crack,
crack, crack,'' Lechliter said. ``This is a drug abuser's odyssey,
if you will.''
   He supervised the planning of the program, which begins outside
with a police helicopter zooming over the crowd to shine its
spotlight on a young man selling drugs to a teen-age girl. Real
police burst out of the bushes; the man pulls out a pistol and the
officers fire shotguns loaded with blanks.
   Groups of 12 are then led through the house by figures dressed
as ghosts and ghouls to witness the pair's arraignment and scenes
of children confessing their drug addictions to parents. In one
room, a teen-ager succumbs to her friends' cajoling and takes a
fatal drug overdose.
   In the next room, the feeling of being under the influence of
crack, a highly addictive form of cocaine, is portrayed by flashing
strobe lights and loud thumping sound effects. Then comes an
emergency room scene, the morgue and the graveyard.
   Even Lechliter, who said he thought the performance might give
children nightmares, was unprepared for the macabre fascination the
attraction aroused. On the first night, organizers said more than
600 people showed up to take the half-hour tour, and nearly half
had to be turned away.
   On Saturday, Lechliter said he had to stop people from joining
an even longer line an hour after the house opened. Even so,
volunteers gave tours until after midnight.
   The house received national attention and even attracted a film
crew from Japan. Cub Scouts arrived by bus from Kentucky and
Pennsylvania.
   ``In a small town, this is the biggest thing that's ever
happened,'' said Elaine Pratzner, owner of Centreville's video
store.
   Residents, including Lechliter, say drugs do not pose a major
crime problem in Centreville, which is 40 miles southeast of
Baltimore. But they say the danger should not be taken lightly.
   ``Are there drugs in town? Yes. Is it a big problem? No, except
that any drugs are a problem,'' Lechliter said. ``We're pro-active.
We're out to prevent it.''
   After the tour, two youngsters scooted away when asked if they
considered the presentation frightening. Their mother followed them.
   ``They're too scared to talk,'' she said, before disappearing
into the night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
