<FIRST>u a PM-PrisonDisturbances 2ndLd-Writethru a0594 10-31 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Disturbances, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0594,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>All Inmates Accounted For at Riot-Torn Pa. Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with all inmates accounted for;
PICKS UP 11th graf pvs, `Crews have ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corrections officials today said they have
accounted for all inmates at the riot-torn state prison here and
attributed an earlier report that five prisoners were missing to
paperwork errors.
   Authorities searched the fire-ravaged prison, double-checked
records and recounted prisoners today to find the last of the five
inmates.
   Meanwhile, hundreds of inmates who slept outdoors for three days
were returned to cells at the prison near Harrisburg, where 123
people were injured and half the buildings gutted or damaged by
fires set Wednesday and Thursday.
   Disturbances at Camp Hill and three other Pennsylvania prisons
have injured nearly 200 inmates and prison staff in the past week
and a half.
   In Illinois on Monday, an inmate with a homemade knife held four
medical workers hostage for five hours, demanding to be moved to
another state. He surrendered without harming anyone after talking
to a TV news crew.
   Authorities said Monday that five inmates were unaccounted for
at Camp Hill. Corrections Department spokesman Kenneth Robinson
said the discrepancies were resolved after all prisoners were
returned to their cells, making possible a more accurate count.
   Officials had said they didn't believe the prison's double ring
of fences had been breached during the riots.
   Crews have been working since Friday, when the riot was quelled,
to repair damaged cellblocks and reinforce some with chains.
   Over the weekend, hundreds of inmates slept in prison yards
because of the shortage of cells. The prison held about 2,600
inmates when the riots began. By Saturday, 744 had been transferred
to other state prisons.
   Officials said the federal prison system would accept at least
700 state prisoners temporarily.
   On Oct. 23, 29 prison staffers and 19 inmates were injured
during a three-hour uprising at the state prison at Huntingdon,
about 100 miles west of Camp Hill. On Saturday night, inmates at
the Holmesburg Prison in Philadelphia seized a cellblock for about
four hours. Twenty prisoners and three guards were injured.
   On Sunday night, about 100 inmates at the Northeast Detention
Center in Philadelphia were moved to a gym while firefighters
cleared smoke from a fire set in a trash can.
   In Joliet, Ill., prisoner Mark LaRue, 35, took a male doctor and
three woman dental clinic workers hostage at the Stateville
Correctional Center. LaRue, who recently was transferred from a
prison in Washington state in an exchange of troublemakers,
demanded to be moved out of Illinois, said Corrections Department
spokesman Nic Howell.
   Officials refused his demand for a plane to fly him back to
Washington but agreed to transfer him to another prison, Howell
said.
   He was transferred to Illinois in May 1988 and to Stateville in
March.
   LaRue has been in nine federal and state prisons as a result of
being transferred for discipline reasons, said state Corrections
Director Michael Lane.
   He was serving a 10-year sentence for assault in Washington, and
while in prison was sentenced to an additional 23 years on two
assault charges and a weapons-possession charge.
</TEXT>
