<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Refugees     10-31 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Refugees,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Detention Center Opens For Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Tuesday opened a new detention
center for 400 Vietnamese boat people despite the objections from
residents.
   Construction of the High Island Detention Center had drawn
contempt from residents in the Sai Kung area, who staged
demonstrations at the site for nine days in August until police
hauled them away.
   The residents feared the Vietnamese might escape, and they
thought the center would pollute a nearby reservoir.
   The center, circled with a 15-foot fence with barbed wire, will
hold 7,000 people when it is finished in two months.
   The surge of boat people continued, with 736 Vietnamese arriving
in Hong Kong in October, compared with 82 a year ago.
   There are 43,840 boat people in Hong Kong waiting to be
screened. They will be repatriated to Vietnam unless they can prove
they fled persecution.
</TEXT>
