<FIRST>r w AM-PeaceCorps-Poland     10-31 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peace Corps-Poland,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Corps May Send Volunteers to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace Corps Director Paul D. Coverdell said
Tuesday the agency has embarked on talks that could lead to sending
75 to 100 American volunteers to Poland next year.
   Coverdell, who has just returned from a visit to Poland and
Hungary, said a three-member Peace Corps team will go to Warsaw in
late November to continue talks with Polish officials about
establishing a program there.
   ``We would characterize our discussions at this point as
preliminary, but I found great enthusiasm for the idea when I was
in Warsaw last week,'' he said. ``I personally would like to see 75
to 100 volunteers there in 1990.''
   In July, during a visit to Eastern Europe, President Bush
announced in Budapest that Peace Corps volunteers would be going to
Hungary _ marking the corps' first effort in an Eastern European
country. That program is to involve about 60 volunteers to train
Hungarians in the teaching of English.
   Coverdell went to Poland after signing a memorandum of
understanding in Budapest that paves the way for starting the Peace
Corps program in Hungary.
   He told a news conference that English teaching also was among
prime interests expressed by Polish officials during his talks in
Warsaw.
   ``Today most professions, particularly those dealing with
science and technology, require a strong grasp of the language,''
he said. ``English also is the primary language of commerce, so we
intend to expand our programming in this area throughout the
world.''
   While he was in Poland, Coverdell also talked with several
government ministers about establishing Peace Corps programs there
dealing with the environment, health and small business development.
   ``We want the Peace Corps to respond to any country that is
requesting legitimate assistance,'' he said. ``I particularly want
the Peace Corps to be on the cutting edge in nations where in the
past there has been a lack of communications mixed with tension and
suspicion. I believe we can make a difference in situations where
these currents of change are flowing.''
   Coverdell's trip also included talks dealing with Peace Corps
programs in the Philippines and Thailand.
   In Manila, he met with President Corazon Aquino and discussed
the possibility of sending Peace Corps volunteers back to the
southern island of Mindanao. Volunteers were withdrawn from
Mindanao four years ago because of threats to their security from
communist insurgents.
</TEXT>
