<FIRST>u a PM-OptometristFlap     10-31 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Optometrist Flap,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Optometrist's License Put on Probation for Having Patients Strip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state licensing board, under fire for
clearing an optometrist who had women patients strip to the waist
for eye exams, today ordered him to stop the practice and put him
on three years' probation.
   The Iowa Board of Optometry Examiners had previously voted
against disciplining Monticello optometrist Gary Fisher but
reconsidered under public pressure.
   The board, after a 2{-hour private meeting, voted without debate
or dissent for probation and ordered Fisher to halt the screening
tests that had the women disrobe. Fisher already had said he was no
longer performing the examinations.
   Fisher was hauled before the licensing board on ethics charges
after some women patients complained he had them partially disrobe.
Fisher said he did so to check for curvature of the spine
associated with some eye disorders.
   In its ruling last month, the board said Fisher was ``honestly
attempting to provide the best care.''
   The decision prompted an uproar, angering some women, pitting
health professionals against each other and raising questions about
closed meetings of medical regulators.
   ``It was kind of like a foot doctor looking at the brain,'' said
Sen. Jack Nystrom.
   The board reconsidered after Attorney General Tom Miller and the
board that governs the medical profession asked for the case to be
reopened. The medical board had threatened to sue, saying Fisher
strayed into the practice of medicine, for which he isn't licensed.
   Fisher complained about being hounded by reporters, before all
sides stopped commenting on the advice of lawyers, who expect the
issue will eventually land in court.
   ``The board, after 20 hours of hearing, two full days,
exonerated me completely,'' said Fisher. ``Now I'm being retried in
the press.''
   The optometry panel is made up of five optometrists and two
members of the public, all appointed by Gov. Terry Branstad. After
initially giving the board a vote of confidence, Branstad urged
another hearing.
   ``Here's a situation where the optometry board is now on trial,
and I think it's appropriate for them to see all of the evidence
before they make a decision,'' he said.
</TEXT>
