<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany-Commentator Bjt   10-31 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Commentator, Bjt,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German TV's Noted West-Basher Loses Job After 30 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karl-Eduard von Schnitzler, who belabored
imperialists, revisionists and assorted capitalist villains on East
German television for nearly 30 years, has lost his job to creeping
reform.
   East Germany's most prominent TV commentator said farewell
Monday on the final edition of his 20-minute weekly show ``The
Black Channel.'' He was unrepentant, as befits a man born into a
titled Prussian family 71 years ago.
   No matter that countrymen came to revile him as a symbol of the
Cold War philosopy used to justify decades of harsh rule.
   No matter the joke that said ``Schni ...'' represented the
shortest time span in East Germany, just enough to turn off the
television as it was uttered.
   ``I have nothing to be ashamed of,'' Schnitzler told his
audience Monday night, grim-faced as ever.
   ``Revisionism is still with us and the class struggle
continues,'' said the man who once declared proudly that ``no one
has ever proved a falsification'' in his broadcasts.
   Revisionism, to Schnitzler, is something practiced by West
Germany, his regular target. He helped found a West German radio
station soon after the country was divided at the end of World War
II, but later returned to East Berlin.
   Since Egon Krenz became Communist Party chief two weeks ago,
succeeding 77-year-old Erich Honecker, the state-controlled media
have undergone a dramatic transition.
   Once-drab newspapers are filled with debate and complaints about
the nation's problems. The two TV channels have begun carrying
everything from illegal street protests to investigative reports on
government bungling and excess.
   Schnitzler, however, remained steadfast, true to the old line.
Only last week, he said East Germany faced the biggest offensive
``from the enemies of socialism'' in its history.
   Many influential people inside the Communist Party, as well as
the general populace, had come to view ``The Black Channel'' as a
shrill anachronism.
   Pro-reform demonstrators shouted ``Schnitzler to the Muppet
Show!''
   After 1,519 episodes of invective since 1960 _ during which he
often showed West German TV reports followed by biting commentary _
Schnitzler got five minutes for his farewell.
   He told viewers he would continue his television work ``in
another fashion'' and pledged to be, as always, ``a weapon in the
defense and development of my socialist fatherland.''
   There had been increasing signs the end was near for Schnitzler,
a clear liability to a government professing willingness to
consider reform.
   His program ``no longer fits with the times,'' the official news
agency ADN reported a week ago.
   A Lutheran Church publication said his unrelenting orthodoxy
contributed to the flight of tens of thousands of East Germans to
freedom in the West and to the frustrations behind mass
pro-democracy protests.
</TEXT>
