<HEAD>With AM-Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not a summit, insisted President Bush.
   It is an ``interim, informal meeting'' that he'll be having in
the Mediterranean with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``This one isn't a summit,'' he told reporters Tuesday,
announcing his forthcoming conversations. ``So scratch this one off
your list of things to worry about.
   ``I've got to make that point over and over again,'' Bush said.
``Summits take on a definition, an expectation of grand design and
grand agreements, and that's not what this is.''
   Rather, he said, it will be ``a chance to put our feet up and
talk.''
   ``You know, there was one time when I felt that such a meeting
wouldn't be productive,'' he said, ``and I think it is going to be
productive, but it's not going to be _ we first set this _ an
agenda meeting.''
   After all, Gorbachev will be in the neighborhood, having already
scheduled a visit with Pope John Paul II in Vatican City just in
advance of the meeting with Bush aboard Soviet and American naval
vessels on Dec. 2 and 3.
   Bush said he and Gorbachev already have agreed to ``a full-scale
U.S.-Soviet summit'' next spring or summer and to seek to reach an
arms control agreement there. That summit is ``separate and apart''
from their Mediterranean rendezvous.
