<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru a0643 10-31 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0643,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Violence Greatest Challenge to Bhutto Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to add AP logo.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto faces
her biggest government crisis this week in a no-confidence motion
that grew out of brutal ethnic violence and has won support from
some of Ms. Bhutto's one-time allies.
   The motion goes to the floor of the National Assembly on
Wednesday and must be voted on by Thursday.
   Ethnic violence in this nation of 109 million people has chipped
away at Ms. Bhutto's power base, turning the slums of Pakistan's
largest city into virtual war zones and creating a big business in
illegal arms.
   Ms. Bhutto is confident her left-of-center Pakistan People's
Party will survive the vote, but some observers fear that whatever
the outcome, it could ignite new violence.
   Ms. Bhutto's party has 116 seats in the National Assembly and
needs 119 votes to survive the confidence motion, and she said it
can easily muster three votes from independents and minority
parties.
   ``Nor a single PPP member will join hands with the opposition,''
Ms. Bhutto said last week.
   Opposition spokesmen say at least 129 assembly members will vote
against the government. So far, 105 have pledged to do so.
   The opposition Islamic Democratic Alliance blames the ethnic
violence on Ms. Bhutto's populist party, saying it refused to take
a tough stand, to decentralize power or to spend money to improve
the welfare of the masses.
   Ms. Bhutto's major opponents are Sindh nationalists from Ms.
Bhutto's native Sindh province, who want a loose federation or
outright independence, and ``mohajirs,'' Indian immigrants to
Pakistan since the partition of the two countries in 1947.
   Fourteen assembly members who announced they will vote with the
opposition belong to the Mohajir Nationalist Movement, which until
recently supported Ms. Bhutto's 10-month-old government.
   The lawmakers announced their defection Oct. 24, claiming the
People's Party failed to deliver on promises to provide more jobs
and to free mohajir political prisoners.
   More than 700 people have died in mohajir-Sindhi riots in
Karachi, the nation's largest city, and in Hyderabad and other
Sindh cities since 1986.
   The province was the only one Ms. Bhutto's party won handily in
November 1988 elections.
   ``We are scared that if the motion is carried, Sindhis will hold
the (mohajirs) responsible for overthrowing a Sindhi prime
minister. And if it's defeated, then there will be jubilation by
PPP workers which could lead to violence,'' said Rifat Ali Khan, an
industrialist in Karachi, where many of the 9 million people live
in filthy slums.
   As a group, urban Mohajirs economically are better off than the
natives. They say this makes them the target of poorer, less
educated Sindhis, the majority of whom are fiefs of rural, feudal
landlords.
   Only a quarter of Sindh's population is mohajirs, but mohajirs
account for 80 percent of Karachi's population. ``We are on the
verge of being converted into a minority on our own soil,'' said
Hafiz Pirzada, a spokesman for the Sindh National Alliance, a
grouping of Sindhi organizations.
   The problem has created a huge illegal arms market in Sindh.
Weaponry is smuggled in from northern Pakistan, where skilled gun
craftsmen churn out arms ranging from assault rifles to grenade
launchers.
   According to unofficial estimates, there are more than 300,000
illegal weapons in Sindh.
</TEXT>
