<DOCNO> AP891031-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Poindexter     10-31 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poindexter,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poindexter Lawyer Objects to Two Iran-Contra Prosecutors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two newly hired Iran-Contra prosecutors should
be disqualifed from handling the criminal case against John
Poindexter because they could have seen his televised congressional
testimony, Poindexter's lawyers argued Tuesday.
   Richard Beckler told a federal court hearing that independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh violated his office's own procedures by
hiring Dan Webb in September to head the prosecution team against
Poindexter, who was President Reagan's national security adviser.
   Another member of the Poindexter prosecution team, Howard Pearl,
a longtime colleague of Webb, was hired a few weeks ago.
   At the hearing, Webb disclosed he plans to call 46 witnesses in
the government's case, including former National Security Council
aide Oliver North, who in May was convicted of three felonies in
the Iran-Contra scandal.
   Webb also said many of the same witnesses from the North case
will be called when Poindexter is put on trial. Webb did not
elaborate. The witnesses at North's trial included former National
Security Adviser Robert McFarlane, Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., and
former Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   North worked in 1985 and 1986 for Poindexter, who is charged
with conspiracy, two counts of obstructing Congress and two counts
of making false statements. The alleged crimes occurred in
connection with North's secret resupply operation to the Nicaraguan
Contras and in regard to a shipment of Hawk missiles to Iran in
1985 assisted by the CIA.
   Walsh set up elaborate regulations in 1987 to insulate his trial
lawyers from being exposed to the immunized congressional testimony
of Iran-Contra figures, including Poindexter.
   Webb, a former U.S. attorney in Chicago, has been in private law
practice and so has undoubtedly been tainted by Poindexter's
nationally televised testimony, Beckler suggested.
   ``This almost borders on bad faith,'' Beckler told U.S. District
Court Judge Harold Greene, who has set Jan. 22 to start
Poindexter's trial.
   ``Here you have a prosecutor who has built a Chinese wall to
block off the ... taint and then he has gone out and hired people
to go around the Chinese wall or go through it or under it,''
Beckler complained. ``It makes a complete mockery of the process.''
   Webb has filed an affidavit saying he didn't watch or read
Poindexter's immunized congressional testimony.
   Webb offered to undergo questioning by Beckler in Greene's
courtroom on the question of exposure to immunized testimony and
Greene indicated he would take Webb up on the offer.
   A Supreme Court ruling says that no portion of a criminal case
may be derived from a witness's immunized testimony.
</TEXT>
