<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Yankee Don Mattingly has been
sued by the company that makes the famous Louisville Slugger
baseball bat, accused of violating his contract by endorsing
another company's bats for children.
   The lawsuit, filed Monday in county circuit court by the
Louisville-based Hillerich &amp; Bradsby Co., charged that the
perennial All-Star first baseman violated a contract he had signed
in 1980 as a 19-year-old minor-league player.
   The suit says Franklin Sports Industries of Massachusetts
produced a set for tee-ball, a variant of baseball aimed at very
young children, in 1987 and a Little League bat in February that
both carried Mattingly's autograph.
   Under the 1980 contract, Mattingly gave exclusive rights to the
use of his name, autograph, nickname, initials and picture to
Hillerich &amp; Bradsby for the promotion of the Louisville Slugger bat
or any other bat the company makes, the suit says.
   In an Oct. 6 letter signed by his attorney, Mattingly said the
agreement was ``unconscionable and unenforceable.''
   In the letter, Mattingly also alleged that Hillerich &amp; Bradsby
failed to pay him royalties, and the slugger threatened to file his
own suit if Hillerich &amp; Bradsby did not stop trying to interfere
with his contract with Franklin.
   The company signs contracts with many minor league players,
supplying them with custom-made bats with the intention of using
the endorsements of the few _ such as Mattingly _ who make it big,
said James Milliman, Hillerich &amp; Bradsby's attorney.
   Hillerich &amp; Bradsby has faced other challenges to its contract
system, but ``nothing this direct,'' said Milliman.
</TEXT>
