<FIRST>u a PM-SailorsOverboard 3rdLd-Writethru a0609 10-31 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sailors Overboard, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0609,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Sailors and 38 Missiles Washed Overboard; Two Sailors Rescued</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs with sailors in the water for an hour; PICKS
UP 8th graf pvs, `Burnett said ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three sailors and 38 non-nuclear missiles on
the aircraft carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower were washed overboard
during exercises today, the Navy said. Two sailors were rescued and
one was missing.
   Lt. Cmdr. Steve Burnett said that the 18 Sparrow and 20
Sidewinder missiles went down in deep water and that the air-to-air
missiles posed no risk.
   ``They were not nuclear-powered. They were not armed,'' said
another spokesman, Senior Chief Petty Officer Cindy Adams.
``Therefore, they're harmless.''
   The Navy said two of the sailors were rescued at 2:15 a.m. after
an hour in the water and were treated on board. One was reported in
critical but stable condition, the other in good condition. Their
names were withheld.
   It was the third serious Navy accident in as many days.
   On Sunday, a student pilot crashed while trying to land on the
carrier Lexington in the Gulf of Mexico, killing him and four
people on ship. On Monday, a pilot accidentally dropped a bomb on
the guided missile cruiser USS Reeves in the Indian Ocean, injuring
five sailors.
   In today's accident, the sailors were moving gear from the
flight deck to the hangar deck when a wave washed them overboard
about 90 miles southeast of Cape Hatteras, N.C., he said.
   Burnett said helicopters from a squadron in Jacksonville, Fla.,
took part in the search for the third sailor.
   By far the worst Navy accident this year was the explosion in a
turret of the USS Iowa in April. The blast killed 47 sailors.
   In Washington, Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman said he saw no
connection between the three recent Navy accidents. Hoffman said
the Navy has an excellent safety record.
</TEXT>
