<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     10-31 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Home Sales Off Dramatically, but Analysts See Improvement Ahead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New home sales fell a dramatic 14 percent last
month, the government reported Tuesday, but analysts said a truer _
and more optimistic _ picture of the housing industry would be
obtained by averaging sales over several months.
   Many economists also predicted mortgage interest rates would
continue to fall, leading to some improvement in the industry but,
as one said, ``no major resurgence.''
   The Commerce Department said new single-family homes were sold
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 618,000 units in September
compared to 719,000 units in August, the sharpest drop since a 19
percent decline in January 1982 during the last recession.
   The August sales had been revised sharply downward from 758,000
but still approximated the level in July, when sales gained 14.6
percent to an annual rate of 742,000 units.
   ``The September numbers reflect a market correction from
extraordinarily high sales activity in July and August that could
not be sustained,'' said chief economist John A. Tuccillo of the
National Association of Realtors.
   ``Buyers flooded the new home market last summer when mortgage
rates started falling and as a result borrowed sales from
September.''
   ``A better measure is probably gotten by averaging the three
months,'' agreed chief economist David Berson of the Federal
National Mortgage Association. ``That shows that home sales picked
up in the third quarter, primarily because of a decline in mortgage
rates.''
   Analysts had credited the July advance to a decline in
fixed-rate mortgages to 9.81 percent by the end of that month from
a peak of 11.22 percent last March.
   But rates edged back up to 10.22 percent by the end of August
and remained in that range throughout September, according to
surveys by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Richard Peach, an economist with the Mortgage Bankers
Association, said rates should continue to fall between now and
mid-1990 resulting in further improvement in the housing industry,
but ``no major resurgence.''
   The Realtors reported last week that sales of existing homes
rose 4.3 percent in September to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.63 million units, the highest level this year.
   New home sales for the first nine months were down 4.5 percent
from the same period in 1988.
   Sales fell 35.6 percent in the Northeast in September after
declining 10.9 percent the previous month. They were off 15.7
percent in the South after a 5.3 percent gain in August, and 9.8
percent in the West following a 1.7 percent rise the previous
month. Sales in the Midwest were unchanged after falling 24.4
percent in August.
   In another report Tuesday, the Realtors said an index measuring
the ability of the typical American family to buy an existing home
rose in September to the highest level in six months, reflecting
both falling home prices and relatively stable mortgage rates.
   The National Association of Realtors said its index rose to
104.7, meaning that a family with a median income of $33,248 had
104.7 percent of the income needed to buy a median-priced existing
home costing $93,400.
   The median means that half of the families earn more and half
less, or that half the homes sell for more and half for less.
</TEXT>
