<FIRST>r a AM-VanAid     10-31 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Van Aid,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bands Throwing Benefit Concert to Save Man's Impounded Van</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First there was Live Aid, then Farm Aid. And now
there's Van Aid _ a benefit concert to rescue a man's impounded
vehicle from the city of New York.
   John Rinaldi used his van to move equipment for local bands, but
the city seized it Oct. 9 because of dozens of unpaid tickets. He
needs $5,000 to get his van back from the Parking Violations Bureau.
   ``When the PVB towed the van, I couldn't work. So the bands
banded together and they're all going to play and donate the
money,'' Rinaldi said.
   It won't be the usual benefit lineup of superstars Friday night
at a Manhattan club. Raising funds for Rinaldi, 21, will be the
Rats of Unusual Size, the Deans of Discipline, The Thing, Woo, the
Wilmingtons and a band with an unprintable name. Rinaldi's own
band, Lech Patrol, is headlining.
   The $10 cover charge is expected to raise most of the money, but
Rinaldi, who is a guitarist, came up with a supplemental plan: He's
raffling off a 23-inch-by-17-inch photo of himself shaking hands
with Parking Violations Bureau boss Elizabeth Brickfield. Both are
standing in front of a tow truck.
   ``We consider him a good customer, so why not?'' said Ms.
Brickfield, the PVB director of enforcement.
   Rinaldi said T-shirts will be sold to raise additional money and
a video of the concert will be made for sale in the future ``so I
can keep getting tickets and paying them off.''
</TEXT>
