<HEAD>Infant Pulled From Car in River Clings to Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infant who was submerged in an
icy river for 45 minutes after an auto accident clung to life today.
   Month-old Samantha Venable was in critical condition on life
support systems at St. Mary's Hospital, a nursing supervisor said.
   A doctor lowered himself down a 60-foot rock wall Sunday to pull
the baby from an upside-down car after it slid off a snowpacked
highway and plunged into the Roaring Fork River, the Sheriff's
Department said.
   The baby's mother, Kary Venable, 19, of Kingwood, Texas, and two
grandparents were killed in the accident. Investigators said the
family was hitchhiking after their own car slid into a snowbank.
   The baby had no pulse when Dr. Steve Ayers pulled her from the
water but was resuscitated with help from more than 35 medical and
rescue workers.
   Two teen-age driver and a passenger managed to kick out the
windows and crawl to safety, said sheriff's spokesman Steve
Crockett.
   If Samatha survives, it will be a few years before doctors will
know if she suffered permanent damage, said pediatrician Dr.
William Mitchell.
