<FIRST>r w AM-Hunt-Education     10-31 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunt-Education,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Gov. Hunt Says Math, Science Must Woo Women, Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt told a
House panel Tuesday that the United States must make special
efforts to interest minority and women students in math and science.
   ``There will be no stopping this nation if we do what we'are
capble of doing,'' said Hunt, who heads the National Board for
Professional Teaching Standards, a private group that pushes for
national teacher qualifcation standards.
   ``We've got to have teachers who can turn students on to science
and math. It's tough, but there are those who can do it.''
   Hunt, governor of North Carolina from 1977-85, was among 10
witnesses testifying before the House science, research and
technology subcommittee in support of an $80 million bill
introduced by Rep. David Price, D.-N.C.
   ``The United States is losing its competitive edge in the global
economy, and our stature as a major economic power will suffer
unless we take action now to improve the skills of our workforce,''
Hunt said.
   The Price measure, co-sponsored by Rep. Sherwood Boehlert,
R-N.Y., would provide 50 percent matching grants from the National
Science Foundation to organizations to develop and distribute new
curricula in math and the sciences, and grants to local school
districts to acquire new curricula.
   It also would provide similar matching grants from the National
Science Foundation to groups that agree to develop and disseminate
new methods for teaching science and technology.
   Yet another would establish a grant program at the National
Science Foundation for community colleges that ``offer exemplary
advanced technician training,'' and would establish 10 National
Centers of Technician Training to serve as clearinghouses.
