<FIRST>r i AM-Marcos     10-31 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds March for Return of Marcos' Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANIQUI, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of protesters chanted
slogans Tuesday for the return of Ferdinand Marcos' body as his
supporters marched through the stronghold of President Corazon
Aquino's family.
   During the rally, about 400 townspeople joined about 500 others
who since Oct. 24 have been marching the 250 miles from Batac south
to Manila to demand Marcos' body be brought back from Hawaii, where
the former president died Sept. 28.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow Marcos' body and members of his
immediate family to return to the Philippines, citing national
security concerns.
   On Tuesday, the caravan stopped in this city of 55,000 people
about 75 miles north of Manila. Paniqui is the hometown of Eduardo
Cojuangco, Mrs. Aquino's first cousin but a strong Marcos supporter.
   Protesters chanted: ``Return the body of President Marcos!''
and, using Cojuangco's nickname, ``Return Danding!''
   Although a relative of Mrs. Aquino, Cojuangco fled to the United
States after the 1986 popular uprising that toppled Marcos. The
government has forbidden the return of Cojuangco.
   Marchers carried placards reading ``There must be justice in the
Aquino administration'' and ``Danding forever.''
   ``This administration must do justice to the Filipino people,
especially for the return of the former president,'' said former
Mayor Vivencio Tayag.
   Minibuses, jeeps and trucks lined the streets. March leaders
said they planned to drive through Tarlac, the provincial capital
and stronghold of the Aquino family, and Pampanga province, near
the U.S.-run Clark Air Base.
   On Friday, the Philippines Supreme Court, in an 8-7 decision,
upheld Mrs. Aquino's ban on the return of Marcos' body and
relatives. Marcos' body was entombed in Hawaii on Oct. 15 in what
his family said was a temporary arrangement until the body could be
returned to the Philippines.
</TEXT>
