<FIRST>r i AM-East-West     10-31 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO, Warsaw Pact Lawmakers Discuss Security, East Bloc Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At an unprecedented meeting of NATO
and Warsaw Pact lawmakers Tuesday, a Polish delegate accused the
West of lacking the vision of postwar America that gave rise to the
rebuilding of Western Europe.
   Western participants said too much has transpired in 40 years
for the West to launch a similar recovery plan for nations like
Poland and Hungary.
   Members of the Polish, Hungarian and Czechoslovak parliaments
are taking part for the first time in a session of the North
Atlantic Assembly, the advisory body of lawmakers from the 16
nations of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization meeting through
Thursday.
   The assembly decided at its annual meeting in Rome last month
that lawmakers from the two dominant military alliances should
discuss how to enhance security while Europe undergoes sweeping
changes.
   The Czechoslovaks ignored Western slaps at their brutal
dispersing of demonstrators in Prague over the weekend. Hungarians
and Poles used the session to seek Western support for reform
programs.
   ``We need a Marshall Plan,'' said Jacek Szymanderski, a
Solidarity member of Poland's Parliament and deputy head of the
defense committee. He referred to the financial aid program drafted
in 1947 by U.S. Secretary of State George C. Marshall that
underwrote the recovery of war-ravaged Western Europe.
   ``You don't have the vision that Marshall had for the future of
Europe,'' Szymanderski told the NATO delegates.
   The Polish delegate and Hungary's parliamentary defense
committee chairman, Laszlo Gyuricza, argued that their nations
should be viewed as potential allies and trading partners and that
Western aid should be directed toward their eventual integration.
   U.S. and West European leaders have pledged generous financial
aid to Poland and Hungary as they take steps toward democratic
governments and market-oriented economies.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl will visit Poland next week,
bearing more than $1 billion in debt relief and financing for new
projects.
   The East European lawmakers complained Western efforts are
unfocused.
   ``We want more than economic assistance, we would like a
political guarantee that you have a concept that integrates us into
Western Europe,'' Szymanderski said.
   Western participants suggested their aid will fall short of the
East's expectations.
   ``We don't see the possibility to combine the two economic
systems,'' Claude-Gerard Marcus of the French Parliament said.
``Good will is not enough to solve the problems.''
   Heinrich Vogel, head of the West German government's Institute
for Eastern and International Studies, said conditions in Eastern
Europe differ greatly from Western Europe in the late 1940s and
that four decades of East-West confrontation cannot be overcome
with simple measures.
   He advised the NATO nations to agree to short-term humanitarian
aid to all nations of Eastern Europe to help solve food and
medicine shortages.
   ``The commitment of the West will be judged by its humanitarian
nature, not its political aims,'' Vogel said.
   Another West German, Dieter Kastrup, suggested doing away with
the term ``East bloc'' because he said the reform movements in some
Warsaw Pact states have resulted in an alliance of drastically
varied nations.
   Klaus Francke, also a West German delegate, noted that some East
European nations have made little effort at reform and told the
Czechoslovak delegates their government's arrest of pro-democracy
demonstrators over the weekend was ``not acceptable.''
   Bohuslav Kucera, vice president of the Czechoslovak parliament,
responded to criticism with a lengthy defense of his nation's
economic policies.
</TEXT>
