<HEAD>Hurricane, Earthquake Give Man Vacations to Remember</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Barrie in 8th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREDERICKTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Want to hear about Brad Fearn's two
vacations this year? His golf trip to South Carolina was wrecked by
Hurricane Hugo and his World Series trek to San Francisco came just
in time for the earthquake.
   ``It's been a pretty bad year for vacations. It's just one of
those things that happens,'' said the sales manager for a travel
agency.
   Fearn was in Myrtle Beach, S.C., when the hurricane hit Sept. 21.
   ``I never dreamed it was going to be anything like it was,''
Fearn said. ``We moved inland farther to a small motel and kind of
weathered the storm there.''
   Fearn arrived Oct. 17 to attend the third game of the World
Series and visit a friend in San Francisco with his 12-year-old
son. They headed straight from the airport to Candlestick Park for
the baseball game.
   ``We were sitting about 13 rows from the field, just sitting and
watching batting practice,'' Fearn said. ``And then it happened.
   ``We were supposed to stay with our friend. He lived in the
Marina district and we couldn't get there because of the fire and
all of that. So we slept in our car the first night and then got a
motel room the next day.''
   Fearn, 39, and his wife, Barrie, who was not along for the
earlier trips, plan a vacation together in a couple of weeks.
   ``We're going to Marco Island, Fla., for a long weekend,'' Mrs.
Fearn said. ``And I'm kind of apprehensive about going with him.''
   Fearn has taken a lot of ribbing from his friends in this
north-central Ohio town about 50 miles northeast of Columbus.
   ``I have a tough time getting people to sit in the same
bleachers with me at a soccer game,'' he said.
</TEXT>
