<FIRST>r i AM-Mozambique-Americans     10-31 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mozambique-Americans,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detainee: Overzealous Border Guards Responsible For Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Briton said Tuesday that he
and six Americans were detained in Mozambique because of
overzealous border guards who arrested them in neighboring Malawi.
   Peter Hammond, who lives in South Africa, was picked up Oct. 24
with the Americans and a South African for allegedly entering
Mozambique illegally from Malawi.
   The Mozambican government held the eight for six days before
releasing them Monday. Although one official said they had no
``malevolent intention,'' all were asked to leave Mozambique.
   The Americans are part of the Christian Emergency Relief Team, a
missionary medical group based in Carlsbad, Calif. They were sent
to assist refugees who have fled war-torn Mozambique for Malawi,
according to organization officials in the United States.
   Hammond said in Johannesburg that the group was on an isolated
road in Malawi and made a wrong turn, taking it toward a Mozambican
border post. While on the Malawi side of the border, the group
asked the Mozambicans for directions, Hammond said.
   He said the Mozambican guards raised their guns, crossed into
Malawi and detained the eight. The two sides spoke no common
language, he said.
   The eight were interrogated on several occasions and eventually
taken to Mozambique's capital, Maputo, where they were held in
solitary confinement at the Machava Prison, Hammond said.
   The six Americans are Dr. Ken Daugherty of San Diego; Dr. Fred
Leist and his wife, Lucille, of Bremerton, Wash.; John Cannon, a
dentist from Davenport, Iowa; and paramedics Carol Roberts of
Syracuse, N.Y., and Steve Sherrill of Stroudsburg, Pa.
   Hammond has been linked to helping the rebels of the Mozambique
National Resistance, which has been fighting the leftist government
since 1977.
   Hammond, head of the Frontline Fellowship missionary group,
denied he had political ties to the rebels. He acknowledged having
met a rebel official in Zimbabwe and having preached to rebel
fighters.
   Mozambique's national news agency AIM described Hammond's
organization as a ``far-right, quasi-religious outfit ... openly
supportive'' of the rebels.
   The Christian Emergency Relief Team has sent missionary medical
teams to Lebanon, Afghanistan, Nicaragua, the Philippines and other
war-torn countries since 1974. The organization is led by David
Courson, an outspoken foe of communism.
   Hundreds of thousands of Mozambican's have died in the war and a
similar number have fled into Malawi. About half of Mozambique's 15
million people are in need of some sort of food aid.
</TEXT>
