<FIRST>r w AM-WhiteHouseHalloween 1stLd-Writethru a0674 10-31 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House Halloween, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Trick-or-Treaters A Real Scary Story</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RESTORES dropped material in last 3 grafs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House helped 500 local school
children celebrate Halloween Tuesday, and along with the treats the
kids got an admonition from President Bush to beware of something
truly scary: illegal drugs.
   Bush and wife Barbara _ ``the first family of ghosts and
goblins,'' as emcee and TV weatherman Willard Scott called them _
emerged through the mouth of a 15-foot jack-o-lantern erected over
the staid diplomatic entrance of the White House.
   The White House collected pledge cards from the children
foreswearing drugs.
   ``You know they say that there's a ghost in this old house, and
the most famous one is Abraham Lincoln,'' said Bush. ``Barbara and
I haven't seen the ghost of Abraham Lincoln walking the halls, but
this is our first Halloween in the White House, so maybe we'll see
him tonight.''
   The president said, ``Halloween is a time for ghosts and
goblins, for haunted houses and scary stories.''
   But there is one ``scary story that isn't make-believe,'' he
said. ``You know what I'm talking about ... illegal drugs and how
they hurt people, how they hurt families, hurt kids, some of them
just like you.''
   He read a letter from a 5th grade girl named Ana Zamora at
Pickard School in Chicago:
   ``Dear President Bush ...
   ``I never go outside because my Mom gets scared that I will get
hurt because of the gang fights. ... I have heard that you are
pushing for a war on drugs. Please help remove drugs from our
neighborhoods. I will do my part by saying no to drugs, and I hope
you can do yours. I know this is hard, but you can do it.''
   Bush promised, ``We will do our best.''
   The kids, decked out in their own Halloween costumes, left the
White House with loot bags and starfish pins to remind them of the
story Bush told last month in a lunchtime address to students about
the war on drugs.
   In that tale, an old man asks a young boy why he bothers to
throw starfish back into the ocean when there were millions drying
up and dying on the beach. It ``can't make any difference at all,''
the old man says.
   The boy just throws another starfish back in, saying, ``It makes
a difference to this one.''
   It showered briefly on the White House Halloween Spectacular, as
it was billed, but for the most part the leaden skies held their
rain until Bush was back inside and the children were on their
buses.
   Even some Secret Service agents came garbed as clowns, while the
children disported themselves as ghouls, caped crusaders,
princesses, warriors and even one lad who came wearing a George
Bush mask.
   The Bushes were joined at the festivities by 3-year-old
granddaughter Marshall, dressed as a turtle, as well as her mother,
Margaret Bush, and Marilyn Quayle, wife of the vice president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
