<FIRST>u a AM-RandallTerry Bjt   10-31 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Randall Terry, Bjt,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Activist Keeps Low Profile in Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion foe Randall Terry has spent the first
four weeks of his two-year sentence behind bars and out of the
limelight, but his critics still accuse him of using his jail time
as a publicity ploy.
   Terry, the outspoken leader of Operation Rescue, is serving time
for leading a wave of demonstrations outside women's clinics in
Atlanta during the Democratic National Convention last year.
   The 30-year-old born-again Christian and former car salesman has
been jailed 34 times previously for his protests, the longest time
for about a month in 1987. Unlike other jail terms, Terry hasn't
been allowed to do jailhouse interviews this time and is limited to
one 10-minute phone call a week.
   ``We don't get the access that we had before,'' said Barbara
Magera, spokeswoman at Operation Rescue's headquarters in
Binghamton, N.Y. ``We just got a little note from him, just
encouraging us and telling us he is doing well. That was all that
we heard from him.''
   Operation Rescue is a loose-knit grassroots organization founded
by Terry in November 1987, three years after he and his wife,
Cindy, began standing outside a clinic in Binghamton trying to
discourage women from having abortions. It has a mailing list of
about 20,000 people; Ms. Magera claims 35,000 supporters have been
jailed for protests.
   Terry was moved last week to the Alpharetta Correction and
Rehabilitation Center, north of Atlanta. He had been held in the
Fulton County jail since Oct. 5.
   Al Pierce, warden in charge of the medium-security facility,
said Terry is being treated like any other inmate. He lives in a
dormitory and has been assigned a job, Pierce said, although he
didn't know what the job was. Ms. Magera said she had been told
Terry worked on a crew installing water pipes.
   ``As far as I know, he's adjusting quite well. If he wasn't I
would have heard about it,'' Pierce said.
   Terry was given a 24-month sentence Oct. 5 for his criminal
trespass and unlawful assembly convictions over protests at an
Atlanta women's clinic July 19, 1988. Fulton County State Court
Judge John Bruner said he would suspend the sentence if Terry would
pay two $500 fines, stay out of the five-county metropolitan
Atlanta area for the 24 months and agree not to break any more
Georgia laws.
   Terry refused, and also refused to pay a $2,000 bond that would
have kept him out of jail while Operation Rescue appeals his
sentence. He said the amount was too high.
   No date has been set for the appeal. Terry has said he would
serve the full two years, if need be. The activist could go free
any time he decided to meet the requirements and pay the $1,000
fine.
   ``True to form, he has taken a media-grabbing tack of going to
jail rather than paying the fine. We would be surprised if his
melodramatic posturing as an ideological martyr keeps him in jail
for more than a few days,''' Patricia Ireland, executive vice
president of the National Organization for Women, said at the time
of the sentencing.
   However, Sally Tyler, executive director of the Georgia Abortion
Rights Action League, said recently that abortion supporters are
really not surprised that Terry has remained in jail this long.
   ``I do think he's there because he wants to be and is working
for an angle in that way,'' she said. ``He's not getting as much
media while in jail as he had hoped for.''
   Terry counts the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. as one of his
heroes, but civil rights leaders object to his comparing Operation
Rescue to their movement.
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, a former aide to King, said Terry
had hoped the state would simply drop its charges against him, as
the city did.
   ``He was arrested blocking and interfering with people who were
pursuing their health care, and we never did that. He was trying to
deny people's legitimate rights, rights that are protected by the
Constitution, and we never did that,'' Young said.
   Ms. Magera responds: ``That kind of criticism is invalid. He is
a prisoner of conscience because he chose not to pay the fine and
agree to the banishment.''
   When arrested in Atlanta for anti-abortion demonstrations in
July 1988, Operation Rescue protesters clogged city jails, some for
as long as 40 days, by identifying themselves only as Baby Jane Doe
or Baby John Doe, to express solidarity with aborted fetuses.
   Some complained about police treatment, the length of their jail
stays, and about not being able to see their families.
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, said that behavior contrasts with civil
rights activists' passive resistance.
   ``In civil disobedience, you willingly accept the penalty,''
Lowery said. So if jail is the penalty for your offense, then you
accept it as the price you pay for supporting your cause.''
</TEXT>
