<FIRST>r a AM-JabbingAttacks     10-31 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jabbing Attacks,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police: New York City Jab Attacks May Be Racial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Street attacks on women by bands of teen-age
girls using needles or other sharp objects appear racially
motivated, a police commander said Tuesday.
   All but one of 28 women jabbed between Oct. 21 and Oct. 27 along
a mile stretch of the city's diverse upper west side were white.
All were attacked between the hours of 6:30 p.m. and 8:30 p.m. and
none was seriously hurt.
   ``The victims are selected. It appears that they're selected on
the fact that they're white,'' said police Capt. Maurice Collins,
commander of the Bias Incident Investigation Squad, which is
investigating.
   The attackers were described as black females between the ages
of 12 and 19. No arrests had been made and the city plans to post a
$10,000 reward for information leading to a conviction.
   Each of the victims was jabbed once, either in the upper or
lower back, in an arm or on the side of the face. They range in age
from 14 to 50, but most were in their 20s and early 30s, police
said.
   Most of the victims were walking alone on a street and ``were
approached usually from behind. They felt a pricking as the black
female teen-agers passed them. They observed laughing and
giggling,'' Collins said.
   Investigators said they did not know what kind of an object was
used in the attacks.
   ``It could be any kind of a sharp object. It could be a needle,
it could be a brooch pin, it could be a compass point. Something
that's sharp enough to prick the skin. ... The wounds are basically
shallow,'' Collins said.
   The thought that the weapon could be a hypodermic needle
heightened concerns that the victims could be infected with
diseases such as AIDS or hepatitis.
   ``I would doubt if it was a hypo needle,'' Collins said. ``These
are very quick jabs. For somebody to be injecting anybody with a
hypo needle would take time.''
   During most of the attacks, no remarks were passed. However, in
one of the assaults, a teen-ager cursed her victim, and in another
case, a teen-ager was heard to say, ``We're going to cut your hair
off,'' Collins said.
</TEXT>
