<SECOND>AM-Martin-Banshee,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Congressman Says Record Got it Wrong, Martin No ``Banshee''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., a ``banshee?''
   No, said Rep. Pat Roberts, R-Kan., who said he was misquoted in
the record of last week's debate over a federal project at the
University of Kansas.
   On the House floor Tuesday, Roberts said he called Mrs. Martin
``Bambi,'' the young deer featured in a Walt Disney movie, not
``banshee.''
   Last Thursday, Mrs. Martin criticized lawmakers who had inserted
a few pet projects into a spending bill.
   Roberts later stepped to the microphone and said Mrs. Martin
``has approached this issue like a virtual banshee in a dark
forest,'' according to the Congressional Record.
   In folklore, a banshee is a female spirit believed to wail
outside a house as a warning that a death will occur in the family.
   Roberts insists he had said Bambi, and Mrs. Martin backs him up.
The Congressional Record conceded the error.
   During lunch that day, Mrs. Martin explained, she had told
Roberts that ``Bambi'' was one of her favorite movies.
   Roberts is known for his colorful oratory. A defender of his
rural constituents, he once remarked that if then-President
Reagan's plane flew too low over Kansas it would get a ``pitchfork
in the belly'' in retaliation for unpopular farm policy.
