<DOCNO> AP891031-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-CongressionalBoundaries     10-31 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressional Boundaries,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Something Extra Riding on Elections: Who'll Control Redistricting?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters decide on a governor and the makeup
of the Legislature's lower house Nov. 7, shaping New Jersey's
political power base in a race similar to one that landed the state
before the U.S. Supreme Court in 1983.
   The next Assembly and the current state Senate will redraw the
state's congressional districts in line with the population changes
found in the 1990 census.
   ``As long as the Legislature insists on retaining the power to
redraw districts, it's an additional prize to be won by whatever
party can control the majority,'' said Ed McCool, chairman of New
Jersey Common Cause.
   The Democrats, who already have majority status in the Senate,
are confident that this election will bring them the Assembly and
the governor's office and leave the Republicans empty-handed when
the districts are drawn.
   But if that happens, and the Democrats are too blatant about
drawing the lines for partisan advantage, they can count on finding
the map just where it was last time around _ in court.
   New Jersey's changes after the 1980 census, described by
Congressional Quarterly as a ``four-star gerrymander,'' were
overturned by the Supreme Court in 1983. The high court said the
districts varied too greatly in population to uphold the equal
representation principle.
   The replacement map, still in use today, was drawn by a federal
court and approved by the Supreme Court in 1984.
   Assemblyman Robert Franks, a former state GOP committee
chairman, says the Democrats' suspect intentions are demonstrated
by the Senate's refusal to pass GOP-sponsored reform bills that
have passed a Republican-controlled Assembly.
   The proposals call for getting redistricting out of the
Legislature and appointing a bipartisan commission to draw the
lines, the way state legislative districts are now devised.
   With the current Senate in place until 1992, the Democrats
``know they're going to be in power during the congressional
map-making process,'' Franks said. ``They've obviously been hoping
a Democratic Assembly and governor would be elected and (allow
them) to put partisan politics ahead of public interest.''
   The plan drawn by the Democratic-controlled Legislature and
signed by Democratic Gov. Brendan T. Byrne hours before he left
office in 1982 looked more like doodles than a congressional
district map.
   Many of the contorted shapes spawned nicknames, such as The
Flying Duck in northern New Jersey and The Bunny in the central
part of the state.
   A shape dubbed The Fish Hook survived the court's rewriting. It
includes a thin ribbon hugging the shore at Monmouth County. The
boundary comes so close to the water that a judge once joked that
the district was contiguous _ as required by federal law _ only at
low tide.
   Besides getting to slice the pie, the Legislature this time
might have one less piece to cut. Under the complicated process
that determines a state's number of seats, New Jersey could find
its delegation shrinking from 14 to 13.
   Franks says he hasn't given up his fight to enact reforms before
the next exercise in redistricting. But barring unforeseen election
results Nov. 7, the Democrats are likely to find themselves with an
opportunity too good to refuse, observers say.
   ``I think it's safe to assume all legislators, by their
definition, would take the opportunity,'' McCool said. ``They would
call it taking care of their side.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Vargas     10-31 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vargas,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Mourn Beloved Tenor Pedro Vargas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MO2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Basilica of Guadalupe echoed with
applause Tuesday as thousands of mourners gave a final round of
applause to singer Pedro Vargas, whose rich tenor serenaded fans
from cabarets to Carnegie Hall for 60 years.
   The basilica, which holds over 5,000 people, was jammed and
thousands more gathered outside during the standing-room-only Mass.
Vargas, 85, died in his sleep of heart failure Monday. He was
cremated Tuesday after the funeral Mass at the basilica, which is
the shrine of Mexico's patron saint.
   The music of Vargas, one of Mexico's biggest stars, helped
define an era of popular culture and reached an audience of
millions worldwide. Among his fans was President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, who paid his respects by standing in an honor guard at the
casket during Vargas' wake Monday night.
   Vargas' songs evoked ``all the emotions that throb in the hearts
of Mexicans,'' Salinas said. Also in the honor guard was the film
star Cantinflas.
   ``He was one of a very few who brought renown to Mexico in the
musical world,'' said Cantinflas, whose real name is Mario Moreno.
``He was an example to all.''
   Vargas, known as the ``tenor of the Americas,'' made scores of
films during the golden age of Mexican movies, in the 1930s and
'40s. His recording career spanned the era of 78-rpm records to the
compact disc.
   He sang at the White House for Presidents Roosevelt and Truman,
performed at Carnegie Hall and Madison Square Garden and counted
Frank Sinatra and Sammy Davis Jr. among his friends along with the
major stars of the Spanish-speaking world.
   Vargas' collaboration with composer Agustin Lara was regarded as
one of Latin America's noted musical partnerships. Together they
popularized the bolero and the paso doble, a lively Spanish
two-step.
   Born in 1904, Vargas first began singing in high school. He was
a shy child whose parents hoped he would enter the priesthood.
Instead he had a fling with bullfighting, then studied medicine for
a time before turning to music.
   His hits included the songs ``Bolero,'' ``Grenada''
``Fleur-de-Lis'' and ``Woman,'' but one of his best-known was the
life-affirming ``Gracias a la Vida,'' which goes:
   ``Thanks to life which has given me so much
   ``Which has given me two eyes that, when I open them,
   ``Distinguish perfectly between the black and the white.''
   The shrine rang with applause as the service ended and Pedro,
Mario and Alejandro, three of Vargas' five sons, carried his casket
outside, holding it aloft in a sea of mourners that filled the huge
plaza.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
