<DOCNO> AP891031-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1654EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Summit-WhyNow Bjt   10-31 0953</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Why Now, Bjt,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Seizes Opportunity to Quash Critics, Aid Perestroika, Help Self</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's shipboard summit with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev responds to pressure to deal more
forcefully with upheaval in the communist world. It also provides
an opportunity to support Perestroika with more than kind words.
   Gorbachev reacted positively, and no wonder. The Soviet leader
also faces political and economic pressures a summit could ease.
   There are risks in the unstructured two-day session in the
Mediterranean next month with the disarming and nimble Kremlin
chief. But the president insisted Tuesday that no agenda was needed.
   ``It's a chance to put our feet up and talk,'' Bush said of the
plans for the unexpected meeting with Gorbachev Dec. 2 and 3 aboard
U.S. and Soviet naval vessels.
   That free-form approach was reminiscent of the meeting three
years ago in Iceland between Ronald Reagan and Gorbachev. The two
leaders wound up in a breathtaking joust over who would be willing
to go further toward banishing nuclear weapons _ all of them _ and
the summit collapsed in discord.
   Even so, Bush is willing to gamble. And there are potential
political and economic benefits for both leaders.
   The Soviets would like U.S. trade credits, membership in world
lending institutions and a loosening of security restrictions on
Western technology.
   Bush, who so far has offered only vague best wishes for
Gorbachev's success, could respond with a lowering of trade
barriers that he has made conditional on new emigration legislation
and further easing of limits on sales of some types of computers.
   While risky, this summit born in secrecy is an opportunity for
Bush to cope with an image that has dogged him over more than a
quarter-century in politics, that he is reluctant to assume command.
   ``Timid'' is the word his critics use. ``Wimp'' was the crueler
term that surfaced in the presidential campaign.
   On foreign policy fronts, Bush has been unable to talk Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega out of power in Panama _ and unwilling to
use force to unseat him _ and prospects for Arab-Israeli
negotiations remain dim.
   Gorbachev could stand some international event to boost his
stock, as well.
   His prodigious perestroika program has not improved the people's
lot, while several of the nationalities bound together in the
U.S.S.R. are straining against the system and threatening to break
out.
   Hungary's attachment to the Warsaw Pact could be weakening.
Criticism of Gorbachev from more avid reformers like Boris Yeltsin
has become commonplace.
   As it turned out, Bush had broached the initiative in a letter
to Gorbachev in July while insisting all along in public he would
not be ``stampeded'' into a unprepared summit meeting.
   In his best laid-back style, Bush had said ``there will,
obviously, at some point be a meeting. But I still feel I'd like
the meeting to be seen as productive rather than just the meeting
itself.''
   These reservations have been quietly cast aside by both leaders.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze were instructed to set up the meeting even
as they worked on a more formal superpower summit to be held in
late spring or early summer. That one will be focused on arms
control.
   Amid all the secret diplomacy, withheld from most State
Department officials, Senate Democratic leader George J. Mitchell
of Maine was accusing the administration of not engaging Gorbachev,
of failing to encourage change in Eastern Europe.
   The NATO allies, led by West Germany, quietly have urged the
administration to be more responsive to Gorbachev's initiatives in
order to reduce tensions in Western Europe. Perestroika is also
good for business, and the West Europeans and Japan are way ahead
of the United States in pursuing business deals in the East.
   Bush finally responded while announcing the Mediterranean
session. ``In this time of change,'' he said, ``I don't want to
have two gigantic ships pass in the night because of failed
communications.''
   That is what Mitchell had feared was happening as Bush responded
last summer to revolutionary change in Poland and Hungary with a
modest _ and since improved _ aid package and expressing of
good-wishes to Gorbachev on perestroika.
   ``What we have demanded for over four decades is beginning to
occur,'' Mitchell said in a Senate speech Sept. 18. ``This is
unquestionably a triumph for the United States. Now is the time for
the United States to encourage and capitalize upon the changes we
have sought for so long.''
   But doubts were raised within the Bush administration.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger cautioned in a
Georgetown University speech on Sept. 15 that Gorbachev was no
anti-communist. ``He intends to make the Soviet Union as strong as
he possibly can,'' Eagleburger said.
   Vice President Dan Quayle and Defense Secretary Dick Cheney were
other outspoken administration skeptics. Robert M. Gates, the
President's deputy national security assistant, was ready last week
to offer another pessimistic appraisal _ until Secretary of State
James A. Baker III quashed the speech.
   By then, Baker had made a landmark address to the private
Foreign Policy Association in New York on Oct. 16 saying the
administration was prepared to provide Moscow with advice and
technical assistance.
   That speech by the president's close friend and political and
foreign policy adviser marked the fact the debate within the
administration essentially was over.
   The shipboard meeting may answer the next question of how far
the president is willing to go to assist the nation that has been a
Cold War adversary for more than a generation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid has covered seven summit meetings
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
