<FIRST>r w AM-Mexico-Drugs     10-31 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Praises Mexican Record on Drug Enforcement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Drug Enforcement
Administration on Tuesday praised Mexican President Carlos Salinas
de Gortari for revitalizing his government's efforts to curb
cross-border drug smuggling.
   John C. Lawn said Mexico has hired more people for the anti-drug
effort and expanded the country's aerial crop eradication
capabilities since Salinas took office 11 months ago.
   He also noted that a number of suspected Mexican drug barons
have been arrested this year.
   ``We've seen a substantial change in law enforcement efforts,''
Lawn said. ``Anti-drug efforts are a major priority (in Mexico).''
   Lawn took part in a panel discussion on the narcotics issue at
the Heritage Foundation, a conservative research group.
   Javier Trevino, a minister-counselor at the Mexican Embassy,
said that a 23-ton seizure of cocaine by Mexican authorities
several months ago meant that 373 million doses of the drug never
reached U.S. markets.
   Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III stressed the need for a
continuing effort to reduce drug demand in the United States. He
said surveys indicate the number of narcotics users in the country
dropped by 30 per cent between 1985 and 1988.
   Meese cautioned, however, that despite dramatic drug seizures by
authorities in the United States and Mexico, there is a ``drug
glut'' in U.S. markets. This has resulted in declining prices for
high potency drugs.
   Meese also criticized those who persistently find fault with
Mexico's record on drug enforcement. He said this ``constant
Mexico-bashing must stop,'' calling it ``demeaning, ineffective and
counter-productive.''
   Meese mentioned no names but the most prominent critic of Mexico
on Capitol Hill is Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who maintains that the
country's law enforcement effort is riddled with corruption.
</TEXT>
