<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Rioters     10-31 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Rioters,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Sentenced to Death in Uzbekistan Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court found 12 people guilty of first-degree
murder in the summer riots that convulsed the Uzbekistan republic
and sentenced two of them to execution by firing squad, the Tass
news agency said Tuesday.
   The 12 were convicted of hunting down four Meskhetian Turks who
tried to flee rioting in late May and early June that killed 100
people.
   Prosecutors charged the 12 with beating the four, burning their
car and leaving them tied up in field overnight, then dousing them
the next day with gasoline and setting them on fire.
   They also were convicted of robbery, malicious hooliganism and
other crimes, the report said.
   Two defendants who Tass identified only as Parpiyev and
Dzahurayev will be shot by firing squad. The other 10 were
sentenced to long jail terms, Tass said. The news agency gave no
indication when the executions would be carried out.
   Defendants included a deputy director of a school, a vocational
school teacher and farm and factory workers, Tass said.
   Meskhetian Turks were forcibly resettled in the Fergana Valley
of eastern Uzbekistan, a republic of Soviet Central Asia, by Josef
Stalin from their native republic of Georgia.
   Thousands of them were forced to flee their homes in the Fergana
Valley because of the rioting and many have been resettled at farms
and in villages throughout the country.
   Some have blamed the rioting on overcrowding and unemployment in
the valley. Others have blamed it on Uzbek nationalists.
</TEXT>
