<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 2038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PollutedLakes     10-31 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polluted Lakes,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pollution Clogging Nation's Lakes, EPA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pollution is clogging one-fourth of the lakes
examined in the latest government survey and more will soon meet a
similar fate if pollution trends continue, according to the
Environmental Protection Agency.
   The EPA's latest survey of lake water quality covering lakes in
32 states shows that serious pollution problems have impaired more
3 million of the 12 million acres of lake area examined. Another 20
percent of the acres of water examined soon will be threatened with
impairment.
   According to the EPA, water is considered impaired if it no
longer can be used for its intended purpose _ such as swimming or
fishing in some cases _ because of pollution.
   The EPA said that in 76 percent of the cases, lake pollution was
caused by agricultural or urban runoffs, while in 11 percent of the
cases the pollution was attributed to industrial or sewage
releases. In the remaining cases, the culprit was naturally caused
pollution.
   The most significant cause of lake impairment was reported to be
excessive plant and algae growth as a result of the release into
the waters of high levels of nutrients. Often those releases came
from sewage facilities or agricultural runoffs, the study said.
   The unwanted plant and algae growth often impedes recreational
activity and reduces a lake's scenic value. More importantly, it
also depletes the lake of necessary oxygen, choking off fish and
other parts of the lake's ecosystem, said Erik Olson, an attorney
with the National Wildlife Federation.
   Olson said that while the EPA findings were a matter of concern,
they understated the true problem with water pollution nationwide
because not all pollutants that affect water quality are included.
   ``If you consider all the pollutants that have potentially
devastating effects on fish and wildlife, perhaps on people as
well, the number (of impaired lake acres) would be significantly
higher,'' he said.
   EPA officials acknowledged that the degree of lake pollution has
been difficult to document nationally because of shortcomings in
data collection.
   For example, the latest report on lake quality, which was
required for submission to Congress, did not include data from 16
states because they did not report. It also did not include data
from the Great Lakes, the country's biggest lake system that has
had major pollution problems.
   About one-fourth of the pollution was attributed to excessive
nutrients or other sources of organic enrichment being put into the
water, often from sewage or agricultural runoffs.
   Other causes of damage are high levels of sediment from rocks
and soil being deposited into lakes, warm water discharges that
disturb fish habitat and the release of pesticides and other
toxics. According to the report, 15 percent of the pollution
problem on the lakes examined was attributed to metals and
inorganics and another 3 percent to pesticides.
   The study reflected lake water quality studies in 32 states,
Puerto Rico and the District of Columbia where more than 18 million
lake acres were reported. Of these, 12.4 million acres were
actually assessed and 45 percent were determined to be either
impaired or threatened with impairment.
   The study did not include any of the Great Lakes, although
several of the states that border those lakes were among the states
included in the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
