<FIRST>u i AM-France-Plane     10-31 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Plane,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Reports Progress in French Airliner Bombing Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have concluded that sheets of the
explosive penthrite packed in a suitcase were used to blow up a
Paris-bound flight over a Niger desert on Sept. 19, the newspaper
Le Figaro reported Tuesday.
   Le Figaro, without citing sources, said the discovery enabled
authorities to link the attack to the Palestinian group Arab
Organization of May 15.
   It said a similar bomb was used on Feb. 23, 1985, in an attack
on the Marks &amp; Spencer department store in Paris that killed one
person and wounded 14, and that the May 15 group was believed
responsible for that attack.
   The airliner bombing killed all 171 people aboard. The French
airline UTA Flight 772 from Brazzaville, Congo, to Paris exploded
over Niger about an hour after taking off from N'Djamena, Chad,
following a stopover there.
   Le Figaro said investigators were able to determine that the
suitcase bomb was placed in the baggage container loaded onto the
plane at Brazzaville.
   Previous French news reports said traces of penthrite were found
in the wreckage.
   On Tuesday, the Transport Ministry issued a preliminary report
of the joint France-Niger commission of inquiry into the crash
saying an explosion must have caused the disaster. It said analysis
found ``strong traces of an explosive material'' in the debris, but
did not specify the explosive or speculate who might have put it on
board.
   The May 15 group, named for the date the 1948 Arab-Israeli war
began, is led by a man whose war name is Abu Ibrahim. It has been
held responsible for bombings or attempted bombings aboard airlines
or at airline offices.
   Le Figaro suggested the group was probably acting on behalf of
the extremist Lebanese Shiite Moslem organization Hezbollah, which
was angered by French support for the Maronite Christian side in
Lebanon's civil war.
</TEXT>
