<DOCNO> AP891031-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Agriculture     10-31 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Agriculture,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Lobby Government for Earthquake Aid to Recoup Millions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers are lobbying for governmental
disaster loans and other aid to help recoup earthquake damage that
could reach as much as $20 million in Santa Cruz County alone.
   ``There are no low-interest loans available to help growers
rebuild and we are working to find out why,'' said Steve Siri,
president of the Santa Cruz County Farm Bureau.
   ``Agriculture has been forgotten after the quake,'' Siri said.
``I know a lot of growers who are on their knees right now. You can
see their suffering in their faces.''
   Early damage estimates by the University of California Extension
Service placed countywide agricultural damage at at least $9.8
million. Agricultural officials in the surrounding couties of Santa
Clara, Monterey and San Benito said they did not have estimates on
agricultural damage but all agreed that Santa Cruz County was
hardest hit.
   The $9.8 million figure is expected to more than double, said
Siri. ``That early estimate included only about 40 percent of the
farming business in the county,'' he said.
   The estimate included crops lost and structures damaged by the
Oct. 17 quake that registered 7.1 on the Richter scale.
   Agriculture is among the county's top revenue producers,
grossing about $168 million annually, Siri said. The bureau has
about 1,100 members countywide, mostly small farmers who work 50
acres and less.
   ``We probably won't see most of the damage until the spring,
when we're able to inspect the pipelines and wells,'' he said.
   Among those who suffered especially heavy losses was the A.
Nagamine Nursery in Watsonville, Siri said.
   The quake leveled a one-acre greenhouse containing miniature
pink carnations and an equal number were threatened when they were
exposed to the cold.
   ``This could be a big loss for us,'' said owner Roy Nagamine.
``These plants would have been ready for Valentine's Day.'' He
estimated his losses could reach $1 million.
   Apple growers also were hard-hit when the quake shook fruit off
trees, tossed and bruised already picked fruit and damaged
cold-storage facilities, Siri said.
   ``With the Alar scare, they certainly didn't need this,'' he
said, referring to the recent national concern about use of the
chemical Alar on apples. Siri said although it's not used in Santa
Cruz County, growers suffered when consumers stopped buying apples.
   Luckily, the quake came at the end of the season for lettuce and
strawberry growers, causing those important crops only minimal
damage, he said.
   Siri said he isn't worried the quake will have a permanent
effect on labor. Early reports said many farmworkers had moved back
to Mexico because they had been frightened by the temblor.
   ``We normally have a migration at this time of the year,'' he
said. ``This may have speeded up the process; some growers reported
they lost some of their workers early this year.
   ``But I'm confident they will return next season.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
