<DOCNO> AP891031-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Hesse     10-31 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hesse,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auditors Examining Records of Energy Official's Expenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal auditors are examining records of
expenses _ including $374 for a torn blouse _ billed to the
government by Martha Hesse, chairwoman of the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission, a commission spokesman said Tuesday.
   The inspector general's office at the Energy Department began
reviewing the documents early last week, said Ron Harris, a
spokesman for the commission. The five-member commission falls
under the Energy Department's responsibilities.
   Judy DeMaire, executive director of the inspector general's
office, said that as a matter of policy she could neither confirm
nor deny the existence of an investigation of Hesse's expenses.
   Harris said the auditors were supplied with commission documents
on Mrs. Hesse's official travel expenses as well as spending
related to security precautions taken by the government in response
to alleged personal threats against Mrs. Hesse.
   Harris said there had been no allegations of wrongdoing. He said
he did not know what triggered the inspector general's interest in
Mrs. Hesse's official expenses.
   ``Everything was approved, everything was legal,'' he said.
   The inspector general's inquiry was first reported in Monday's
editions of the weekly publication Legal Times. It reported that
among other personal charges billed to the government by Mrs. Hesse
was $374 to replace a $535 blouse she ripped while on the job.
   The Legal Times also cited commission documents indicating that
Mrs. Hesse had taken 11 foreign trips as commission chairman since
1987, and that so far this year she had made at least 19 trips
domestically. It said the foreign trips cost the government $28,000.
   Harris said Mrs. Hesse would not respond to the Legal Times
story. He said all the reported trips were ordinary speaking
engagements that Mrs. Hesse accepted as a spokeswoman for federal
regulation of U.S. energy and power industries.
   Harris acknowledged that Mrs. Hesse has traveled more frequently
than her predecessors. He said it was ``just her style'' to keep a
heavier schedule of public speaking.
   The Legal Times also reported that the government paid $3,825
for a home security system and $3,090 for a cellular phone for Mrs.
Hesse's use. It said the equipment was deemed necessary in light of
allegations that her former government chauffer threatened her
numerous times after being removed from his job in 1988.
   Harris said the security system and the phone were
``preapproved'' costs and that it was understood from the start
that the equipment would be returned to the government when Mrs.
Hesse leaves the commission.
   The Legal Times also reported that the government picked up the
bill for $4,270 in repairs to Mrs. Hesse's Porsche automobile,
which allegedly was vandalized in the commission's parking garage
by the former chauffer accused of threatening Mrs. Hesse.
   Mrs. Hesse announced earlier this month that she planned to quit
the commission at the start of 1990 to become senior vice president
for corporate affairs at First Chicago Corp., a major banking
organization. Her term expires in October 1991.
   Mrs. Hesse has been chairman of the commission since Oct. 6,
1986. Before that she was assistant secretary for management and
administration at the Energy Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
