<FIRST>u w AM-Summit-ShipboardMeetings     10-31 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Shipboard Meetings,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shipboard Summit Not a First</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's rendezvous with Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbechev on the Mediterranean Sea will not be the first
time a U.S. president has taken to shipboard diplomacy.
   Franklin Delano Roosevelt joined British Prime Minister Winston
Churchill in 1941 off the Newfoundland coast to draw up the
Atlantic Charter, proclaiming freedom of the seas and leading to
the arming of U.S. merchant ships.
   They met aboard the United States cruiser August and the British
battleship Prince of Wales, in August 1941, five months before the
United States entered World War II.
   Presidents Richard Nixon and Harry Truman also put the
presidential yacht Sequoia to diplomatic use. Nixon hosted Soviet
leader Leonid Brezhnev on board and Truman held the first
international conference on nuclear arms control on the yacht.
   Bush and the Kremlin announced Tuesday that the U.S.-Soviet
meeting will occur Dec. 2-3 aboard Naval ships in the Mediterranean.
   The White House said it was not yet clear exactly where on the
sea the ships would go for the summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
