<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Georgian Nationalists Protest in Tbilisi</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of nationalists in the Caucasus republic
of Georgia on Tuesday began a protest against Soviet power in front
of the main government buildings in Tbilisi, an activist source
said.
   David Nadiradze said in a telephone interview from the Georgian
capital that more than 200 people had begun a sit-down strike in
front of the buildings where 19 demonstrators were killed on April
9 in a charge by soldiers.
   The demonstrators were surrounded by several thousand people who
were trying to ensure their safety, Nadiradze said.
   The crowd had broken through a fence erected around the
government buildings on Rustaveli Prospekt on Sunday, he said,
adding that only a handful of police were present.
   Nadiradze said the demonstrators were protesting the drafting of
Georgian youths into the Soviet Army, the incorporation of Georgia
into the Soviet Union in 1921 and unrest among the republic's
Abkhazian minority that they say is being fomented by Moscow to
destabilize the republic.
   The protest was organized by the National Democratic Party, the
Party of National Independence and other Georgian nationalist
groups, he said.
