<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Nicaragua     10-31 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Nicaragua,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush May Consider Military Aid To Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday he will review
U.S. policy toward Nicaragua, including the possibility of renewing
military aid to the Contra rebels, if President Daniel Ortega calls
off the cease-fire that has been in place for 19 months.
   At a news conference, Bush also escalated his criticism of
Ortega for suggesting at the hemispheric summit conference last
weekend in Costa Rica that he might respond to Contra military
attacks by suspending the March 1988 truce.
   ``I've never seen a meeting where all the participants were so
unanimously against all the outrages of one. And we're still
getting messages in here about the outrageous performance of Daniel
Ortega,'' he said.
   Asked whether he might consider asking Congress for a resumption
of military aid to the Contras if Ortega calls off the truce, Bush
said, ``I would re-evaluate this situation in a minute if the
cease-fire is broken.''
   Congress suspended military aid to the Contras a few weeks
before the cease-fire agreement was reached in early 1988. Bush has
abandoned use of the military option against the Sandinistas,
preferring instead economic and diplomatic pressure to try to
promote a democratic outcome there.
   Ortega was to announce a final decision Tuesday on whether to
suspend the cease-fire.
   Bush spoke a day after Secretary of State James A. Baker III
said threats by Ortega to call off the truce may be a prelude to
cancellation of national elections set for February in Nicaragua.
But Ortega has said the elections will take place ``war or no war.''
   The administration's belief that Ortega may be in trouble
politically at home is based partly on a recent poll, taken by the
Costa Rican affiliate of Gallup International, showing that Ortega
trails opposition candidate Violeta Chamorro by 40 percent to 29
percent.
   But some analysts regard such polling as not necessarily
reliable because of the difficulty in obtaining an accurate
sampling in a country consisting largely of a peasant population.
   Ortega contends the Contras have systematically violated the
cease-fire, leading to the deaths of more than 730 Sandinista
soldiers since it went into effect.
   But a senior State Department official who briefed reporters on
Monday, insisting on anonymity, said the Sandinista army has
conducted ``aggressive and continuing search-and-destroy operations
against resistance forces'' since the truce began.
   From May through September 1989, at least 105 rebels have been
killed in such operations, he said, adding that the Contra
casualties run about 15 to 20 a month since the truce went into
effect.
   The bulk of the Contras are stationed at camps in Honduras but
up to 3,000 remain inside Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
