<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Sheldon Horowitz'' will soon grace the
menu of the Stage Delicatessen alongside sandwiches that honor
people everyone is supposed to have heard of.
   Horowitz, a 57-year-old lawyer from Tuckahoe, won a contest
sponsored by the deli, which has restaurants in New York, Boston
and Los Angeles.
   The ``Sheldon Horowitz'' sandwich was chosen from among hundreds
of entries submitted from across the country and was concocted by
his wife.
   ``Because my husband is renowned for his honesty,'' wrote Gloria
Horowitz, ``this sandwich should be open-faced, revealing all the
beautiful truth of its contents.''
   The ingredients: Tongue, smoked turkey, lumpfish caviar, red
bell peppers, lettuce and mustard on pumpernickel bread.
   Sheldon is to take the first bite at a ceremony Wednesday at the
Stage in New York.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERWICK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postmaster Nick Antonacci hadn't walked a
route in 10 years, until he made good on a promise to his
accident-free carriers.
   Antonacci, a borough postmaster, pledged in October 1988 to
again tote a mail bag if his workers went for a year without
on-the-job accidents.
   Nobody fell down or got bit by a dog, so Antonacci had to
deliver to 569 houses Monday.
   ``And I was on schedule, by the way,'' he said. ``It makes me
realize where I put on those 12 pounds.''
   Antonacci's carriers enjoyed rubbing it in.
   ``We thought we might have to send an ambulance out with an
oxygen tank half way through the route,'' said one, Ron Seferyn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KENDRICK, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Bateman is the maintenance man with a
star.
   When he became maintenance man for his hometown of Kellogg, the
city marshal's badge was part of the bargain.
   ``I never really wanted to be the marshal,'' said Bateman, 64.
``But that's part of the job description. I didn't think it would
take up much time at first.''
   Bateman, who has been on the job for nine years, spends a lot of
his time dealing with accidents along three steep stretches of road
leading into the town of 450 people. That is, when he's not working
on the sewers.
   ``I get called out a lot, for every wreck,'' he said. ``A lot on
Saturday and Sunday, mostly after 2 a.m. when the bars close.
That's when you start to have your fun.''
   The city gave Bateman a two-door, compact car with a blue bubble
light on the roof for patrol duties. And he even has a desk at City
Hall.
   ``It's mostly just keeping the peace and quiet,'' Bateman said.
``When neighbors get to squabbling, that's the worst thing in the
world. A lot of them will turn on you when they get real mad.''
</TEXT>
