<DOCNO> AP891031-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Donations     10-31 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Donations,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Hears Arguments on Corporate Donation Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Michigan law restricting political donations
by private corporations abridges their free-speech rights and gives
their foes an unfair advantage, a lawyer for the Michigan State
Chamber of Commerce told the Supreme Court Tuesday.
   But Michigan Solicitor General Louis J. Caruso defended the law,
saying wealthy corporations could dominate the political arena if
allowed to make direct contributions to candidates.
   The Chamber of Commerce filed suit seeking to have the state law
declared unconstitutional, and the case is likely to have a broad,
nationwide impact on the way campaigns for federal and state
offices are financed.
   The law, which carries a $10,000 fine, generally prohibits
corporations from spending in behalf of political candidates.
However, corporations may establish political action committees
that funnel voluntary contributions to candidates.
   Caruso drew a crossfire of sharp questions from Justices Antonin
Scalia and Anthony Kennedy challenging his contention that the
state has a compelling interest in limiting corporate participation
in politics.
   ``Why is there a great risk to the political process from
expenditures by a family owned corporation ... but if Donald Trump
wants to come in and spend all the money he likes, that would be no
problem?'' Scalia asked.
   ``I find it difficult to see what the evil being driven at is,''
he said later. ``Is the state going to be swept away by ads signed
by General Motors?''
   Caruso said the Supreme Court historically has given states
broad authority to regulate corporate political activity.
   ``The fact is that corporations have an unfair advantage in the
political marketplace,'' he said. ``The Chamber of Commerce can
have a serious impact on the political process.''
   Chamber lawyer Richard D. McLellan argued that ``both the
purpose and the activities of the Chamber of Commerce are
ideological.'' The chamber, he said, lobbies for specific
legislation and ballot initiatives and conducts public-education
campaigns in favor of its positions on the issues.
   McLellan said the state law is unfair because it exempts
unincorporated labor unions, the Michigan business community's top
political adversaries.
   The chamber in 1985 wanted to advertise in the Grand Rapids
Press supporting a Republican candidate for the state House of
Representatives. Fearing the ad would violate the law, the chamber
decided against running it and filed suit.
   A federal judge upheld the law, ruling that it applied to the
Michigan State Chamber of Commerce.
   But the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the
decision, ruling that indirect expenditures by ``a non-traditional
corporation ... formed for essentially ideological purposes ... do
not pose the threat or appearance of corruption.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia     10-31 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian President Rejects Negotiations With Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco pledged on
Tuesday that drug traffickers will not succeed in forcing the
government to grant them amnesty through the use of terrorism.
   Barco declared in a nationally broadcast speech, ``The Colombian
people will not accept reconciliation with those who have shown
they do not respect the most basic human rights.''
   He said the drug lords in the last few weeks had tried to gloss
over a violent terrorist campaign with proposals for peace talks
with the government.
   ``The government has rejected and will continue rejecting such
proposals,'' the president said.
   Barco and Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez, head of the nation's
intelligence force, spoke at the headquarters of the Department of
Administrative Security at ceremonies commemorating the force's
36th anniversary.
   The president said the struggle against traffickers was
difficult because of ``the internationalization of their
activities, their complex organization and their enormous
resources.''
   Maza Marquez, who survived a May 31 bomb attack that killed
seven people in this capital, said traffickers have declared war on
the Colombian establishment at its highest level, but that this
nation would be victorious in its crusade against ``drug
trafficking's dark scourge.''
   Leaders of Colombi's most powerful cocaine cartel, based in
Medellin, have asked for peace talks five times the past two months.
   They offered to lay down their arms, end a terrorist bombing
campaign and abandon the drug business if the government will grant
them amnesty and stop extraditing traffickers to the United States.
   The Barco administration extradited five Colombians wanted for
trafficking after beginning its drug crackdown on Aug. 19, the day
after Sen. Luis Carlos Galan was assassinated. Galan, the leading
presidential candidate, was an outspoken foe of the drug traders.
   Traffickers responded with a renewed campaign of bombings and
assassinations. A judge, eight journalists and a leading leftist
politician were among 34 people killed in a two-month spasm of
violence by the drug runners.
   Bombs badly damaged two leading newspapers, El Espectador and
Vanguardia Liberal, which denounced traffickers.
   Three bombs and a hand grenade exploded Monday night in Bogota,
killing two people, including a policeman.
