<HEAD>ABC Has Top Show But World Series Ratings Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `ABC ended ...,' to CORRECT CBS weekly rating
to 13.0, sted 14.2.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' was the highest rated
television show for the week ended Oct. 29 as the network's
earthquake-delayed World Series coverage took a nose dive in the
Nielsen report.
   The third baseball game between the San Francisco Giants and the
Oakland Athletics was in 18th place. The fourth game on Saturday,
in which the Athletics wrapped up the series in four straight, was
29th.
   ABC's Monday Night Football game between the Chicago Bears and
the Cleveland Browns did much better, finishing in ninth place.
   Two weeks before, the first two World Series games had put ABC
in first place, breaking NBC's 68 week-dominance of the network
ratings. The two games in the week ended Oct. 15 were near the
bottom of the top 20 shows. The second game was 16th and the first
game tied for 18th place. But the San Francisco Bay area earthquake
on Oct. 17 delayed the series.
   ABC ended the week close behind NBC in second place. NBC's
average in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey was 14.9. ABC was second
with 14.2 and CBS was third with 13.0. A rating is the percentage
of the nation's 92.1 million homes.
   ``Roseanne'' was first with NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and
``Cheers'' close beind. NBC had five shows in the Top 10, ABC three
and CBS two.
   Here's the Top 10: ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``The Cosby Show,''
NBC's ``Cheers,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' NBC's ``A Different World,''
CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,'' ABC's ``The Wonder Years,'' NBC's
``Golden Girls,'' ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' and NBC's ``In
the Heat of the Night.''
   ``Roseanne'' and ``The Wonder Years'' are on ABC's strongest
night, Tuesday. It opens with ``Who's the Boss?,'' in 13th place
this week. But the ratings drop after ``Roseanne'' with the new
comedy ``Chicken Soup,'' starring Jackie Mason. ``Chicken Soup''
was in 19th place this past week.
   Despite that, ``Chicken Soup'' is still the highest-rated new
show of the season. The next highest new show in the current period
is ABC's ``Doogie Howser, M.D.'' in 25th. CBS' ``Major Dad'' in
36th place comes next.
   Johnny Carson's celebration of the 27th anniversary of ``The
Tonight Show'' placed 15th.
   Fox Broadcasting Co.'s highest-ranked show was ``Married...With
Children,'' in 39th place.
   ABC once again had the top-ranked evening news show. The
ratings: ABC 10.3, CBS 10.0 and NBC 9.6.
   The lowest-rated network show was CBS' ``Wolf.'' Here are the
bottom five network shows: ABC's Saturday World Series preview,
CBS' ``Saturday Night with Connie Chung,'' ABC's ``Ghostbusters''
Halloween special, CBS' ``Tour of Duty,'' and CBS' ``Wolf.''
