<FIRST>r w AM-DollarDispute     10-31 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar Dispute,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Admininstration, Fed on Value of the Dollar: Same Hymnal, Different
Hymns?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Bush administration official Tuesday
denied that there is a serious policy rift between the
administration and the Federal Reserve over efforts to push the
value of the dollar down to improve the country's trade balance.
   But the comments of Treasury Undersecretary David Mulford
weren't totally backed up by later statements from Federal Reserve
Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson.
   In testimony before a House Banking subcommittee, both men
sought to minimize differences between the administration and the
Fed.
   However, Johnson left no doubt that the central bank was still
concerned about fighting inflationary pressures in the U.S. economy
and gave that effort a much higher priority than the
administration's desire to see the dollar stabilized at a lower
value in order to boost U.S. exports.
   President Bush and other administration officials have made
various comments that they believed the Fed was overly concerned
about inflation and should be doing more to lower interest rates to
boost the U.S. economy.
   Lower interest rates not only stimulate domestic demand but also
serve to push the dollar's value lower because foreign investors do
not earn as much on their U.S. investments when U.S. interest rates
fall. These lower earnings serve to divert investments to other
countries where returns are relatively better, thus driving up
those currencies against the dollar.
   A lower dollar may help U.S. exports by making American products
cheaper in terms of other currencies and thus more competitive
overseas. By the same token, U.S. imports become more expensive.
   The Fed-administration debate was brought to a head following a
Sept. 23 announcment by the Group of Seven industrial nations that
they planned to cooperate jointly on the dollar and interest rate
policies in an effort to curb the dollar's rise this year.
   However, while interest rates were increased by both Japan and
West Germany, the Federal Reserve has not changed its interest-rate
policies even though the administration has been lobbying for such
a change.
   Mulford told the committee that he believed news reports of a
dispute between the Fed and the administration had been
``substantially overstated.''
   ``The consultations between the Treasury and the Fed has been
close and friendly,'' he said in response to questions about the
policy dispute.
   While the Banking panel had originally sought to have both
Mulford and Johnson testify and answer questions at the same time,
Johnson waited to testify until Mulford had finished his two-hour
appearance and left the room.
   In his testimomy, Johnson left no doubt that the central bank
still viewed fighting inflation as its No. 1 priority. He indicated
that efforts to push the dollar lower as a way of curing the
country's trade problems were doomed to failure as long as more
basic problems such as the huge U.S. budget deficit and America's
low savings rate were not addressed.
   ``There is little room for substantial further reduction in U.S.
(trade) deficits absent a significant reduction of the
saving-investment balance,'' he said.
   Many economists support Johnson's view, contending that the
country's trade problem is primarily caused by the fact that
American consumers have been on a consumption binge, buying more
than can be produced domestically.
   To correct this imbalance, the personal savings rate and the
U.S. budget deficit must both be cut to lower personal and
government consumption, these economists believe.
   There appeared to be a substantial split among members of the
committee over the long-term success of intervention in currency
markets, the process by which governments buy and sell currencies
on the open market in an attempt to influence their price.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, argued that with $400 billion in foreign
currencies being traded every day, any amounts of intervention by
central governments would have little long-term impact on the
markets.
   Mulford agreed with this, but he said that joint intervention
was still a useful exercise to demonstrate the resolve of the
United States and its major allies to work together in solving
trade imbalances and other economic problems.
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., criticized the administration and
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady for being too complacent about
the dollar's rise this year. He said that unless stronger efforts
were taken, backed by the Fed, then the country's trade deficit, as
measured by the current account, could well balloon to a record
$200 billion in a few short years.
   Mulford said that it was possible that the current account
deficit, which declined to $126.6 billion last year, may worsen
next year after two years of significant improvement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
