<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NominationBattle     10-31 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nomination Battle,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Says Judge's Nomination Threatened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican senator said Tuesday that a
number of liberal organizations are mobilizing ``to do a job on''
the nomination of Clarence Thomas as a federal appeals judge.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo. told lawmakers that Thomas ``has
one thing going against him and that is that is is a black lawyer
of fairly conservative political and judicial philosophy.''
   ``I am concerned about what I fear might happen to my friend
Clarence Thomas when he comes before the Senate Judiciary Committee
in his hearings,'' Danforth said.
   The Bush administration on Monday nominated Thomas as a judge of
the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia. It
is considered a prestige post because many of the most heavily
spotlighted cases come before the court.
   Also on Tuesday, Thomas received only a ``qualified'' rating
from the American Bar Association's judicial screening panel.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel confirmed that the
ABA's Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary had rated Clarence
Thomas ``qualified'' instead of ``well qualified''.
   Runkel downplayed the fact that Thomas received a ``qualified''
instead of a ``well qualified'' rating, saying that ``anyone who is
qualified is by definition an appropriate nominee.''
   According to the ABA's judicial screening handbook, a
``qualified'' rating means that the nominee meets minimum
qualifications for satisfactory performance as a judge.
   To be rated ``well qualified,'' a nominee ``must have the
committee's strong affirmative endorsement...and be regarded as one
of the best available for the vacancy from the standpoint of
integrity, competence and temperament,'' the handbook said.
   Thomas, 41, has drawn considerable criticism from Capitol Hill
during his seven-year tenure at the Equal Employment Opportuniny
Commission. After President Bush announced in June his plan to
nominate Thomas, 14 House members signed a letter asking him to
reconsider.
   Critics say Thomas has not been vigorous enough in enforcing
civil rights laws.
   The senator took the floor and said: ``I know him to be an
absolutely first-rate lawyer and beyond that I know him to be a
first-rate human being.''
   ``The interest groups that did a job on William Lucas in the
Senate Judiciary Committee are going to be mobilizing again to do a
job on Clarence Thomas,'' Danforth said.
   When such organizations wage a campaign, Danforth said,
``anything goes in an effort to destroy the person who is the
nominee with whom you disagree.''
   A wide array of liberal and civil rights organizations including
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and
the NAACP Legal and Educational Defense Fund opposed the Bush
administration's nomination of former Wayne County Sheriff William
Lucas, a black Republican, as head of the civil rights division of
the Justice Department.
   The nomination died in the Senate Judiciary Committee with a
number of Democratic lawmakers saying they did not detect a deep
enough commitment to civil rights on the part of Lucas.
   Meanwhile, a number of civil rights groups that opposed the
Lucas nomination sent a letter to the Senate Judiciary Committee,
asking the lawmakers ``to withhold judgment until a thorough
examination is conducted to determine whether mr. thomas ... is
fit.''
   The groups included the Alliance for Justice, the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the National
Education Association, the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees and the Mexican-American Legal Defense and
Education Fund.
   The letter stopped short of recommending defeat of Thomas. But
it said that his ``actions as head of the EEOC ... suggest that he
lacks the commitment to equal justice, the qualifications and the
judicial temperment for a lifetime appoint to one of the nation's
most important courts.''
   Ralph Neas of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights said
said many of the umbrella group's member organizations have
concerns about the Thomas record but that the conference has not
adopted a position thus far.
</TEXT>
