<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Ortega     10-31 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Ortega,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Condems Ortega Intention to End Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted unanimously Tuesday to
condemn Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega's Saturday announcement
that he will cancel the 19-month cease-fire in the war with the
Contras.
   The strongly worded resolution, approved 95-0, demands Ortega
renew his commitment to the cease-fire and conduct elections
scheduled for Feb. 25 in a free, fair and open manner.
   It expresses concern that Ortega's cancellation of the
cease-fire ``could be a prelude to a Sandinista effort to cancel or
postpone the elections.''
   Ortega had been scheduled to officially announce Tuesday whether
he would call off the cease-fire, but his spokesman said the
announcement had been postponed until Wednesday.
   ``Even Ortega's strongest apologists in Congress are having a
hard time coming up with excuses for this one,'' said Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas, referring to the declaration
made by Ortega that he would end the cease-fire because of alleged
violations by the Contras.
   Ortega made the announcement while attending a hemispheric
meeting of heads of state in Costa Rica.
   Dole said the Senate resolution is a means of letting Ortega
know ``that we _ all of us, both parties, across the political
spectrum _ are not going to put up with this outrage.''
   The resolution sends the message that ``enough is enough,'' Dole
said.
   ``He's up to his old tricks and he's treating us to the same,
tired tap dance of tyranny,'' Dole said.
   ``This resolution expresses the dismay of the Senate,'' said
Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine.
   ``After so much hope has been invested in the electoral process,
to have Daniel Ortega, in such a cavalier manner, announce that he
is going to resume the conflict is an outrage to all civilized
mankind,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.
   ``What clearly has happened is that a very strong signal of
intimidation has been sent to the people of Nicaragua by Daniel
Ortega,'' Graham said.
   The Senate resolution calls Ortega's action ``totally
unjustified, a major breach of the Sandinista regime's commitments
to its democratic neighbors and its own people and a serious threat
to regional peace and stability.''
   It calls on Ortega ``to end his reckless rhetoric.''
</TEXT>
