<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Budget     10-31 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Budget,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislature Passes Budget With 60-Billion Ruble Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet legislature approved a 1990 budget
Tuesday that cuts the deficit in half, to the equivalent of about
$100 billion, by reducing military spending and capital outlays.
   Members approved the budget 357-6 after a tie vote of 181-181
that in effect rejected a proposal for 10 percent reductions in the
budgets of the government news agencies Tass and Novosti, and state
radio and television.
   A proposal to raise the prices of beer, tobacco and luxuries
went down 338-44.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the legislators, in remarks
carried on television: ``We have made a big step toward healing the
financial and economic situation by adopting this document, but
these are only our decisions. To implement them in life, we have to
work harder than we ever worked before.''
   He said the budget still was not satisfactory, ``but we have to
stop here because it stems from reality.''
   Gorbachev commented at the end of a five-hour joint session of
the two houses of the Supreme Soviet, and after Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze in Moscow and President Bush in Washington
said the two presidents would meet meet on Dec. 2-3 aboard naval
vessels of the two nations in the Mediterranean.
   Shevardnadze denied U.S. media reports that possible U.S.
economic aid to the Soviets would be on the summit agenda.
   Tass said the 1990 budget anticipates income of 429.9 billion
rubles ($693.4 billion at the official exchange rate) and
expenditures of 489.9 billion ($790.2 billion).
   Those figures are almost exactly what the government proposed in
September and, if the government sticks to them, it will halve this
year's deficit of 120 billion rubles ($193 billion). The U.S.
deficit in fiscal 1990 is required by law to be no more than about
$110 billion.
   Officials proposed a cut in the defense budget this year from
77.3 billion rubles ($125 billion) to 70.9 billion ($114.3 billion)
and large reductions in expenditures for new factories and
equipment.
   Gorbachev's economic planners say the country must make better
use of the resources it has rather than constantly building new
factories and buying new equipment.
   Tass said the final budget and economnic plan calls for sharply
higher production of consumer goods, a sore point with citizens who
face perpetual shortages. It also said the budget allocates 13.4
billion rubles ($21.6 billion) to improve living standards, but was
not more specific.
   The attempt to reduce the budgets of Tass, Novosti and the
Gostelradio broadcast conglomerate appeared to be an expression of
frustration over reporting by the official media. Opponents of the
cuts said agencies needed the money to report more rapidly and
accurately.
</TEXT>
