<FIRST>u i AM-Iraq-Journalist     10-31 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Journalist,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jailed Journalist Appears on Iraqi TV, Admits to Espionage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian-born reporter with the London
weekly Sunday Observer said in a TV interview broadcast Tuesday
that he was spying for Israel when arrested on Sept. 15 in Iraq.
   Farzad Bazoft, 31, has an Iranian passport with the right of
residence in Britain. He was traveling on British documents when
arrested.
   In the 25-minute interview over state television, he said the
British government was aware that he was an Israeli spy posing as a
reporter.
   In London, Observer editor Donald Trelford said it was clear
Bazoft's statement was made under duress and requested immediate
consular access to him.
   ``Not a word of it should be accepted without objective
supporting evidence. Only two weeks ago the Iraqis accused him of
being a British spy. Now they say he is an Israeli spy. I don't
believe either charge is true,'' he said on Independent Television
News.
   Bazoft said he was desperate to stay in Britain but did not have
the means when ``recruited by Israeli intelligence officers in
London in 1987'' who gave him money and found him the job with the
Observer.
   They later trained him in espionage, he said, assigning him ``to
gather information about Iraq's economic and military industrial
targets, and information about the political situation and the
morale of the people during and after the gulf war.''
   A cease-fire halted the Persian Gulf war between Iran and Iraq
in August 1988.
   Bazoft spoke in English and an interpreter translated his
answers into Arabic. It was not clear when the interview was
recorded.
   The Observer said Bazoft disappeared while investigating reports
that an explosion at a military industrial complex south of Baghdad
may have killed about 700 people. Iraq reported the death of 19
people in what was described as a fuel depot explosion.
   The British government has protested to Iraq about Bazoft's
detention.
   The International Press Institute sent a protest message in
October to President Saddam Hussein.
</TEXT>
