<DOCNO> AP891031-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Baker     10-31 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heads For Australia To Promote Economic Cooperation In Asia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III headed
for Australia Tuesday night to promote closer economic cooperation
in Asia as a way of fostering open markets and democratic trends
around the world.
   He will also hold talks with Prime Minister Bob Hawke, whose
plan for a new economic community in the fastest-growing area of
the world could enhance investment opportunities for American firms
in Asia.
   U.S. trade with east Asia has more than tripled over the last
decade _ from $80 billion in 1978 to $280 billion last year. By
comparison, trade with Europe in 1988 was $180 billion.
   American investment in Asia, meanwhile, has climbed to more than
$33 billion, providing 23 percent of overseas profits earned by
U.S. firms.
   But even while Asia has moved past the European Common Market in
productivity, ``the network of U.S. ties with the Pacific is much
weaker than it is with Europe,'' a senior U.S. official said.
   In a briefing for reporters on ground rules that prevent use of
his name, the official said Baker's participation in the 12-nation
conference next week in Canberra has political as well as economic
objectives.
   Citing South Korea as an example, he said ``open market systems
tend to be associated with greater freedom.''
   Baker's eight-day trip will take him away from Washington at a
busy time in U.S. foreign policy. President Bush announced Tuesday
he would meet Dec. 2-3 with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
Arabs and Israelis still have not come together on Mideast
negotiations.
   Baker said in an interview Monday he did not expect a
``make-or-break'' deveopment on Mideast talks while he was away.
And, he said, ``we will continue to try to work it, and I hope we
can have some conversations'' while he is in Australia.
   Baker has been conducting most of his Mideast diplomacy by
telephone with Foreign Ministers Moshe Arens of Israel and Esmat
Abdel Meguid of Egypt.
   The 12 nations attending the Canberra conference are Australia,
Japan, South Korea, Canada, the United States, Indonesia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand, Brunei and New Zealand.
   China was not invited because it has a Marxist economy. Taiwan
and Hong Kong also will not attend.
   The United States had suggested China and Taiwan be granted
observer status and Hong Kong attend as a full participant, said
the official. But, he said, all decisions are being made by
consensus, and the suggestion was withdrawn when no consensus could
be achieved.
</TEXT>
