<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0713 10-31 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Quayle Lash Congress, Press for Legislative Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, ``The White,'' and adds 2 grafs with Republican
offer on budget legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday blamed Congress for
failure to act on his legislative proposals and Vice President Dan
Quayle joined the attack, saying it's time to pass stalled budget
legislation and ``get on with it.''
   ``We've told them what we want. And I wish they'd get some
action going on the proposals that I have put forward. I think the
American people are entitled to that,'' Bush said at a news
conference.
   While the president and vice president fueled the partisan
wrangling between the White House and Capitol Hill, the
administration also reached a compromise to end a lenghthy battle
with Democrats over raising the minimum wage.
   The agreement, involving concessions on the part of both the
White House and the Democrats, would take the minimum wage to $4.25
by 1991 and couple it with a subminimum ``training wage'' for
teen-agers with little work experience.
   But battling continued on other issues, as Republicans dismissed
a Democratic offer to resolve differences over passage of a federal
debt ceiling needed to avoid government default by next week.
   That and other legislative matters have been stalled by what has
become the most dominant issue in Congress _ Bush's proposal to cut
the capital gains tax.
   Bush blasted Congress when asked about capital gains.
   ``Were not in the posture of trying to tell the Congress how
they ought to resolve these difficulties. We sent up clear
proposals on the anticrime package, on the minimum wage, on the
capital gains. And it has gotten so confusing up there that they
ought to move now,'' he told reporters. ``I think the American
people see that it is this Congress that is frustrating getting the
deficit down. And so they ought to move and move promptly.''
   But Bush said he would not specify how Congress should resolve
the matter.
   ``I can't sit there and fine-tune for them _ well, if you'll
only throw this one issue in with that one, why you can do your
business,'' he said.
   Quayle put out the word that the administration is going to make
Congress the whipping boy for the inability to agree on legislation.
   In a speech to the American Stock Exchange, Quayle said that,
``On Feb. 9, President Bush submitted his budget to the Congress.
Today is Oct. 31, and the budget reconciliation package is still on
Capitol Hill and has not passed the Congress.''
   ``Now it is Congress' responsibility to pass a budget
reconciliation and to get on with it,'' he said. ``It's time to get
on with the nation's business.''
   Capital gains has become the dominant issue before Congress,
blocking agreement on a $16 billion deficit-reduction bill,
legislation to boost aid to Poland and Hungary and on the measure
raising the government's debt ceiling.
   The White House comments came as congressional Democrats and
Republicans swapped offers on plans for passing a new federal debt
ceiling, needed by next week to avert a default by the Treasury,
and other pressing fiscal legislation.
   Despite the allure of wrapping up the session before
Thanksgiving, Senate Republicans rebuffed the offer because the
Democrats wouldn't give up their procedural blockade of a capital
gains tax cut.
   ``We all gave it a horse laugh. We assume they're not serious,''
said Sen. William Armstrong, R-Colo., following a GOP lunch.
   ``This would kill capital gains and it was deliberately designed
to do so. I hope it is rejected out of hand,'' said Sen. Bob
Packwood, R-Ore., a chief sponsor of the proposal, prior to a White
House afternoon meeting.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., and Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, announced a parliamentary plan to
secure Senate action on a separate capital gains bill, not tied to
other budget work. However, Mitchell said he wouldn't surrender the
right to filibuster the bill, a threat of endless debate which can
only be stopped by a 60 vote majority.
   The Democrats also offered to strip from the fiscal 1990
deficit-reduction bill a Democratic-sponsored child care initiative.
   Republicans countered with an offer of their own that would
allow quick passage of debt limit and deficit-reduction
legislation, and pile the capital gains tax cut, a rollback of the
Medicare catastrophic care program and several other controversial
proposals into a single measure.
   ``We too want to get the job done and get it done on time,''
said Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
