<SECOND>AM-Congress-Japanese-Americans,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Payment Measure Delayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Tuesday delayed final
congressional action on legislation guaranteeing $20,000
reparations payments to the estimated 60,000 still-living Japanese
Americans who were interned during World War II.
   The delay came about when the Senate adopted an unrelated
amendment involving a jurisdictional dispute between the
Appropriations Committee and the Foreign Relations Committee. The
action will have the effect of sending the conference committee
report on the measure back to the House.
   The Senate will continue work on the $17.2 billion
appropriations bill on Wednesday.
   The $1.2 billion reparations program will pay out $20,000 in
compensation to each of the surviving Japanese-American internees
over a three-year period beginning next Oct. 1.
   The measure also provides appropriations for the State Justice
and Commerce Departments and contains major funding for the war on
drugs.
