<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-31 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0291</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wintry weather overcame unseasonably warm weather in the upper
Great Lakes as snow and rain fell from Wyoming to New York state
Tuesday.
   Snow fell on sections of Montana, Idaho, Wyoming, North Dakota,
Minnesota and Michigan.
   By Tuesday morning, 6 inches of snow had fallen west of
Sheridan, Wyo. Other snowfall included up to 2 inches in Sheridan
and 2 inches in Worland, Wyo., and Helena Mont.
   Advisories for snow and blowing and drifting snow were in effect
through Tuesday night for Wyoming's Big Horn Mountains and the
northern mountains of Colorado.
   In Nebraska, advisories for Tuesday night warned of low
temperatures and gusty winds, which were expected to bring wind
chills and snow showers.
   Rain fell on northeast Wisconsin and lower Michigan, and
extended from Ohio to eastern Kentucky, West Virginia, Virginia,
southern New England, southeast New York, eastern Pennsylvania, New
Jersey, Maryland and Delaware.
   The cold front that brought the rain and snow also brought low
temperatures, ending nearly a week of mild weather in the Great
Lakes states.
   In Indiana, frost and freezing-temperature advisories were in
effect for Tuesday night. Below-normal temperatures were expected
in Illinois.
   At 3 p.m. EST, temperatures around the nation ranged from 22
degrees in Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 86 degrees in Miami.
   Alamosa, Colo., broke its low-temperature mark for the date with
a reading of 2 degrees, and was the coldest spot in the Lower 48
states Tuesday morning. The city's previous record of 6 degrees was
set in 1971.
   The temperature in Grand Junction, Colo., dipped to a record 18
degrees, exceeding the mark of 20 degrees set in 1979.
</TEXT>
