<FIRST>r i AM-French-NuclearTest     10-31 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-French-Nuclear Test,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Conducts Another Nuclear Test in South Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France early Wednesday exploded a
20-kiloton nuclear device at its underground test site on Mururoa
Atoll in the South Pacific, New Zealand scientists said.
   The blast, equivalent to 20,000 tons of dynamite, was the sixth
this year in French Polynesia and the second in what appears to be
a series of four, said Warwick Smith of the Department of
Scientific and Industrial Research.
   Smith in a statement said the explosion, monitored by
seismographs at Raratonga, Cook Islands, occurred at 5:57 a.m.
   It was the 109th underground test on Mururoa in 1975, Smith
said. The last test, at 25 kilotons, was made Oct. 24.
   France, which considers the tests vital to maintaining nuclear
deterrance, has come under strong criticism from Australia, New
Zealand and South Pacific island states.
   ``This is the second test in French Polynesia in the current
series,'' Smith said. ``A series of four were held in May and June,
and on the basis of the past five years, we can expect another two
tests in the current series before the end of the year.''
</TEXT>
