<FIRST>r p AM-Governor'sRace     10-31 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governor's Race,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gubernatorial Candidate Attacked on Right to Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0759 with `p' category code.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat L. Douglas Wilder, sitting on a
15-point lead in a poll on Virginia's $25 million campaign for
governor, said Tuesday he hopes he will be judged on his
accomplishments rather than his race.
   ``I've never lost an election, and I think it's too late to
start now,'' Wilder, the state's black lieutenant governor, told a
girls' school audience.
   Wilder's Republican opponent, former Attorney General J.
Marshall Coleman, showed no signs of giving up before the Nov. 7
election.
   Coleman, 47, spent the day campaigning from southwestern Bristol
on the Tennessee border to the Atlantic Ocean resort city of
Virginia Beach.
   A poll published Sunday in The Washington Post showed Wilder
leading Coleman 52 percent to 37 percent, giving a boost to
Wilder's contention that racism ``plays no part at all'' in a
campaign that could produce the first elected black governor of a
U.S. state.
   Coleman said he did not believe the poll's findings ``and I'm
not going to sit still for it.'' The poll has a margin of error of
3 percent, which means the results could be off by that amount.
   Coleman held a news conference in Bristol with members of
Virginia's Fraternal Order of Police, which endorsed his candidacy.
The organization backed Wilder's bid for lieutenant governor in
1985.
   During a question-and-answer session with students at St.
Catherine's School _ a mostly white, private Episcopal school
attended by members of upper-income Richmond families _ Wilder, 58,
was asked whether he was concerned that the racial symbolism of his
candidacy might overshadow any of his initiatives.
   ``I hope the shadow isn't there,'' Wilder said. He said his
campaign was geared to the idea that education and economic
development ``are the greatest social equalizers.''
   When people judge his record, Wilder said, he hopes the judgment
will be based on performance ``and what I look like won't be
considered.''
   In Richmond, meanwhile, the National Right to Work Committee
released a tape recording of a private meeting between Wilder and
United Mine Workers members last summer. Wilder appears to say he
would support an amendment to the state's right-to-work law that
could require non-union members to pay dues to unions negotiating
bargaining agreements on their behalf.
   The committee's political arm plans to begin airing radio
commercials in support of Coleman, using portions of the tape.
   Committee President Reed Larsen said he didn't know who made the
recording and if he did, ``I wouldn't want to carry the fire
insurance on his house.''
   Wilder met the UMW members July 31 in Castlewood in the wake of
a bitter, violence-plagued strike still under way in the southwest
Virginia coalfields against The Pittston Coal Group Inc.
   According to an edited transcript of the recording, Wilder said
the right-to-work law has as much chance of being scrapped ``as a
snowball in hell'' and that he supports the law. Then he added, ``I
have to do that.''
   Asked whether he would support a so-called ``free-rider''
amendment allowing labor contracts in which non-union members could
be required to pay union dues, Wilder responded, ``That's
correct,'' according to the transcript.
   Wilder spokeswoman B.J. Northington said the tape was an effort
to ``make something out of nothing. We're not surprised by this.
The lieutenant governor has consistently supported the
right-to-work law.''
   Coleman's press secretary, Jay Timmons, said the Republican's
campaign did not know ahead of the release what was on the tape.
</TEXT>
