<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 2103EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103     10-31 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Palestinians on Trial in Sweden Linked to Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CECILIA LONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police investigation of four
Palestinians on trial in Sweden uncovered apparent links to the
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, which killed 270 people in Scotland
last Dec. 21, according to court records.
   The four are charged here in connection with the preparation of
five bombs used in 1985 and 1986 against U.S. and Jewish targets in
Stockholm; Copenhagen, Denmark; and Amsterdam, the Netherlands. One
person was killed and dozens were wounded in the bombings.
   Court records, examined by The Associated Press on Tuesday,
showed that Mohammed Abu Talb, thought to be the squad leader,
visited Malta in October 1988. That Mediterranean island nation was
believed to be the point of origin for the bomb that destroyed Pan
Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   Air Malta on Tuesday denied published reports that the bomb may
have been transferred to Frankfurt, West Germany, on a Malta
flight, inside an unaccompanied suitcase. It said its flight to
Frankfurt on Dec. 21, 1988 carried 39 passengers and 55 pieces of
baggage.
   ``All pieces of baggage have been accounted for and every one of
the 39 passengers has been identified,'' Air Malta said in an
official statament.
   West German investigators suggested a Maltese connection on
Monday.
   Scottish investigators have contended for months that the bomb
was put on the jet in Frankfurt, where Flight 103 originated.
Passengers and luggage were transferred to a Boeing 747 at Heathrow
Airport in London.
   Other court documents here showed Tuesday that Swedish police
arrested a brother of two defendants on suspicion of smuggling
plastic explosives to the West German apartment where the Pan Am
bomb was believed to have been assembled.
   The brother was released last November for lack of evidence.
Prosecutors told the AP that parts of the investigation against him
were classified.
   On trial are Abu Talb, 35, Marten Imandi, 35, Mahmoud Said Al
Moghrabi, 24, and Mustafa El-Mougrabi, 23. Moghrabi and Mougrabi
are brothers. Their names are spelled differently on the charge
sheet.
   Prosecutor Stefan Karlmark said before the trial opened Oct. 16
the Swedish investigators were not probing the Pan Am bombing,
since it was not relevant to their case.
   He also said he found no link between the four and the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, the group
suspected of the Pan Am bombing.
   Abu Talb has admitted belonging to the Palestine Popular
Struggle Front, which like the PFLP-GC, is an extremist faction
which rejects the moderate policies of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   According to his passport, Abu Talb was in Malta Oct. 19-26,
1988, after spending one day in Cyprus.
   The passport supports a report in The New York Times Tuesday
that Abu Talb was seen in Malta that month with Hafez Dalkamoni,
the suspected PFLP-GC officer now in custody in West Germany in
connection with the preparation of bombs.
   The Times quoted U.S. officials as saying Abu Talb retrieved an
altitude bomb assembled in an apartment in Neuss, West Germany, and
passed it on to another person. The bombs, packed in radiocassette
players, detonate when the plane reaches a pre-set altitude.
   Sixteen members of the PFLP-GC were detained in a sweep by West
German police Oct. 26, 1988, at the Neuss apartment, seizing bombs
similar to the one believed to have destroyed Flight 103. All but
two have been released.
   Abu Talb was quoted by The Times as telling investigators he
passed on a bomb overlooked in the raids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
