<DOCNO> AP891031-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-StHelena     10-31 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-St Helena,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Launches Lifeline Ship for Remote Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain launched a new ship Tuesday to
keep the lifeline open to its remote Atlantic Ocean colony of St.
Helena.
   The Duke of York, who visited the island in 1984, christened the
6,500-ton vessel St. Helena at Hall Russell's yard in Aberdeen, on
Scotland's east coast.
   The new ship is the only passenger and cargo link between
Britain and St. Helena. It will make six round trips a year between
its home port of Avonmouth near Bristol and the island and will
also pay one visit a year to Tristan da Cunha, the even more remote
island colony in the south Atlantic.
   St. Helena, where the Emperor Napoleon Bonaparte was exiled and
died in 1821, is 1,140 miles west of Africa and used to be a port
of call for liners on the Britain-South Africa run. It is 10 miles
long and 6 miles wide, with a population of 5,500. It is 16 days by
ship from England.
   Tristan da Cunha is 1,320 miles to the southwest of St. Helena
and has 300 residents.
   The ship cost $31.4 million and was ordered by the island's
government with funding from the Foreign Office to replace a vessel
of the same name that has served St. Helena for 27 years.
</TEXT>
