<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Election     10-31 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Election,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Candidate Enters Brazilian Presidential Race Near End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire businessman and TV
entertainer Silvio Santos on Tuesday announced he would run for the
Brazilian presidency two weeks before the election, a move analysts
say could alter the outcome of the campaign.
   Santos, 59, who says he knows little about politics, told
reporters during a raucous press conference at the Congress he
would run under the small and relatively unknown Brazilian
Municipalist Party.
   Santos is owner of SBT network, the country's second largest,
and host of a 6-hour Sunday raffle and prize show that is immensely
popular among Brazil's poor.
   Santos' sudden candidacy, coming 15 days before the country's
first direct presidential election in 29 years, was labeled as
``opportunism'' by businessmen and the work of presidential
operatives by other candidates.
   Analysts said Santos could hurt two leading candidates, Fernando
Collor de Mello, of the center-right National Reconstruction Party,
and Luis Inacio Lula da Silva, of the radical-left Workers' Party.
Both candidates rely heavily on support from Brazil's lower classes.
   A sharp, last-minute swing at the polls was possible since ``the
majority of the electorate has not become overly enthusiastic about
any of the 22 candidates in the race,'' wrote Clovis Rossi, a
columnist for the respected Folha de Sao Paulo newspaper.
   Antonio Ermirio de Moraes, one of Brazil's leading businessmen,
called the announcement ``handiwork of the presidential palace,''
to weaken Collor de Mello, a harsh critic of President Jose Sarney.
   Collor de Mello, who holds a two-to-one lead over his closest
opponent in nationwide polls, said he would try to invalidate
Santos' candidacy with a law that requires public personalities to
stop their professional activities three months prior to the
election.
   Santos, a descendent of Greek immigrants, worked as a street
vendor before gaining national attention for amassing a fortune
that today includes a a TV network, a bank, a chain of supermarkets
and stores.
   On Nov. 15, 82 million Brazilians _ a majority of them from the
lower class _ are to choose Sarney's successor for a five-year
term, the first popular vote for president since 1960.
   If no candidate wins a majority on Nov. 15, the two top
vote-getters will face each other in a runoff in December.
</TEXT>
