<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     10-31 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Cabinets in Lebanon Squabble over U.N. Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's rival cabinets clashed on
Tuesday over a complaint sent to the U.N. Security Council by
hard-line Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun protesting the presence
of Syrian troops here.
   Also Tuesday, seven Algerian army officers arrived in Beirut to
help set up a security zone for a Parliament meeting to elect a new
president for Lebanon, despite Aoun's opposition to convening such
a meeting.
   Aoun's forces fought six months of artillery battles with the
Syrian army that killed more than 900 people.
   In the name of his three-man Cabinet, Aoun asked U.N. Secretary
General Javier Perez de Cuellar to distribute his cable as an
official document to Security Council members. It did not request a
debate on the issue.
   ``We reserve the right to ask for a formal Security Council
session on the Syrian and Israeli occupation of Lebanese
territory,'' the cable said. The text was released by Aoun's
administration.
   ``We wish to lay stronger emphasis on the occupation of the
Syrian army of the greater part of this territory,'' it said.
   About 40,000 Syrian troops control 70 percent of the territory
in Lebanon, which has been rent by 14 years of civil war. The
Syrians deployed in 1976 under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
But Aoun said in March they betrayed the mandate by siding with the
Moslems and declared a ``war of liberation'' against them.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the rival,
Syrian-backed Cabinet, asked the Security Council in a separate
telegram to ``ignore the complaint.''
   Hoss said the protest was ``illegitimate'' because, he said,
Aoun does not represent all of Lebanon.
   Aoun's move came after separate meetings with the ambassadors of
Britain, France, the Soviet Union and China _ representing four of
the five permanent member states of the Security Council.
   The United States withdrew its diplomatic mission from Lebanon
on Sept. 6, complaining of harassment by Aoun supporters.
   The Algerian officers will now await instructions from Arab
League envoy Lakhdar Ibrahimi, a police spokesman said.
   Ibrahimi, assistant secretary-general of the 22-member Arab
League, heads a security committee comprising representatives of
Aoun's 20,000-strong mainly Christian army as well as the main
warring factions in Lebanon.
   He said Monday he was ``optimistic that the parliamentary
session to elect a new president will be held before Nov. 7.''
   Sixty-three of Lebanon's 73 surviving parliamentarians attended
a special session in Taif, Saudi Arabia, in October and agreed to a
peace plan to end the civil war in their country.
   The plan was brokered by an Arab League committee, comprising
the leaders of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, has rejected the peace accord and
threatened to dissolve the Parliament because the plan does not
include a fixed timetable for Syrian withdrawal from Lebanon.
</TEXT>
