<FIRST>r w AM-ReportingContest 1stLd-Writethru   10-31 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reporting Contest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0642,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Seniors Compete</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with winner, runners-up; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old high school senior from Mesa,
Ariz., won a full, four-year college scholarship on Tuesday in a
day-long reporting contest featuring students from all 50 states.
   Peter Robison, a senior at Mesa High School, hopes to use the
scholarship from the contest, sponsored by the Pilot Pen Corp., at
Stanford University next fall.
   Four runners-up were also chosen based on their writing on the
full day of news conferences, network bulletins and other material
on a fictitious conflict in Africa.
   The runners-up, each awarded a check for $2,500, were Michele
Helm, Regina High School, Harper Woods, Mich.; Christopher
Heimarck, Moorhead Senior High School, Moorhead, Minn,; Elizabeth
McDonald, Colonie Central High School, Albany, N.Y.; Tara Keys ,
North Medford High School, Medford, Ore.
   ``We hope that this competition, held at the National Press
Club, will focus interest in a dramatic way on the field of
journalism,'' said Ronald G. Shaw, Pilot Pen president.
   ``It was fun,'' said Robison, who was told of his victory at a
banquet following the day's events.
   Pilot Pen, based in Trumbull, Conn., is a leading supplier of
writing instruments. The fictional international situation began at
8:30 a.m., with changes developing every 15 minutes, news
conferences by both sides and culminated with a mock presidential
news conference announcing the United States was sending troops to
support its ally.
   The 50 student finalists were culled from more than 50,000
entrants from 1,000 high schools nationwide. The finalists were
required to write a 500-word newspaper story reporting the day's
events.
