<SECOND>AM-Halloween Shooting,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three-Year-Old Critical after Halloween Party Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRYAN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old boy was shot in the head
Tuesday with a pistol that police believe was part of a day care
worker's Halloween costume.
   Kenny Archer of Normangee was in serious in stable condition at
Texas Children's Hospital in Houston, about 90 miles southeast of
Bryan, said hospital spokeswoman Tina Foster.
   The child, whose breathing was being assisted by a ventilator,
was taken to Texas Children's after four hours of neurosurgery at
St. Joseph Hospital.
   Authorities said they planned to talk Wednesday with the owner
of Twice As Nice day care center in Normangee and a worker who
reportedly wore the .22-caliber handgun as part of a western
costume.
   ``I've heard that someone was dressed up for Halloween and had
their husband's pistol and didn't know it was loaded,'' said Leon
County Sheriff Royce Wilson.
   Wilson said he heard two accounts of the shooting Tuesday.
   ``One said the child reached and got the pistol and the other
said that another child got it,'' Wilson said.
   He said the interviews were delayed a day because of the shock
among the witnesses following the shooting.
   Workers at the day care center said they were told not to answer
questions, but to refer all calls to the center's owner, Janice
Roberts, who was not at the center at the time.
   Wilson and Leon County District Attorney David Barron said no
charges have been filed in the case pending the interviews
Wednesday.
