<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-31 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buddhist Monk Among 38 Killed in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers raided a Buddhist shrine
where members of a radical group had taken refuge and killed a monk
who was the tactical planner for the underground organization, a
military official said Tuesday.
   He said the monk, Pasgodawaye Sarankere, was armed with an
automatic rifle and was shot when he tried to escape during
Monday's raid on a temple in Pattigolla, 48 miles southeast of
Colombo.
   The official, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said Sarankere was military coordinator of the People's Liberation
Front, the ultranationalist Sinhalese group fighting the government.
   Two other members of the front, both young Sinhalese men, were
also killed, he said. It was not immediately disclosed if the
soldiers suffered casualties or if any radicals escaped.
   The government reported at least 35 other killings in
Sinhalese-dominated southern and central Sri Lanka in the 24 hours
ending Tuesday evening.
   The bodies of 11 men were found in the central Kandy district
and in Gampaha, north of Colombo, the official said.
   The victims were believed to be radicals killed by vigilante
groups who support the government. The government denies it is
involved.
   The military official said nine Sinhalese men were killed by
radicals for giving information to the police. At least eight
radicals and two soldiers were killed in fighting between security
forces and members of the front across the Sinhalese heartland, he
said.
   Sinhalese radicals were believed responsible for detonating a
landmine under a police jeep in the central Anuradhapura district
on Tuesday. At least five policemen died, the official said.
   The front has fought to overthrow the government for more than
two years, saying too many concessions were given to the minority
Tamil community.
   Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, make up 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and dominate the government and the
military. The mainly Hindu Tamils form 18 percent and claim they
are discriminated against in jobs and education by the majority
community.
</TEXT>
