<SECOND>AM-Teacher Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Reached in Beverly Hills Teacher's Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with ratification vote scheduled,
further talks, rally, quote; picks up 4th graf, `The school ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union and school negotiators
reached a tentative agreement Tuesday, ending a 3-week-old strike
by 300 teachers that paralyzed education in this city of the rich
and famous.
   The agreement was subject to ratification by the Beverly Hills
Education Association and the city Board of Education, said board
President Dan Tomarken.
   The teachers were to meet Wednesday morning at the Beverly
Hilton Hotel to debate the agreement and cast ballots, said Stan
Kaplan, a strike captain and elementary-school teacher. A simple
majority vote was needed to approve the pact, Kaplan said.
   The Board of Education was to meet and consider the pact after
Wednesday's teacher vote.
   If approved by both sides, teachers would return to classes
Thursday, Kaplan said.
   The agreement was reached after more than 5{ hours of
negotiations that began in the morning. Details of the pact were
not released.
   Negotiators for the two sides reconvened late Tuesday to work
out further details of the agreement.
   About 200 of the district's 300 striking teachers marched
outside school district headquarters in a show of solidarity. Some
carried signs reading, ``Gucci Mentality _ Pic 'N' Save Salaries.''
   ``We've been hopeful that we could get back and we were a little
down this morning,'' said Beverly Hills High School teacher John
Borsum. ``But we're hopeful that we have a good, tentative
agreement here.''
   The school board had been facing increasing pressure from
parents, including some who threatened to recall the board if a
settlement was not reached. More than 100 angry parents and
students joined picketing teachers Monday to lobby for an end to
the strike.
   The strike was like few others, with teachers eating food
catered by trendy eateries. Parents volunteered more than $500,000
to fulfill teacher salary demands in Beverly Hills, which many
celebrities call home.
   About 300 of the school district's 315 teachers, counselors and
nurses walked off the job Oct. 16, seeking better pay.
   Starting pay for teachers is $21,604 annually, nearly $6,000
less than in neighboring Los Angeles. Top yearly pay for teachers
in Beverly Hills is $46,270, and averages $42,659.
   Ms. Tomarken said the school district may have to consider a
class-size increase, which the community has previously been
unwilling to accept. Beverly Hills averages 25 students per class,
while other districts average 36 students, she said.
   About 4,700 students attend classes at the city's four
elementary schools and one high school.
</TEXT>
