<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Close Adv10-12-1stLd-Writethru   10-31 0989</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Close, Adv 10-12 - 1st Ld-Writethru,b0895,1006</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 10-12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Glenn Close Plays Nice</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 3rd graf to change `their' to `there'; SUBs 19th graf,
``Circumstance,'' she ... limbo situation., to fix typo in quote marks.
Movie opened Oct. 27.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After two Academy Award-nominated portrayals
of vindictive women, versatile Glenn Close returns in another
guise: as a married woman seeking to adopt the baby of an unwed
teen-ager.
   ``Immediate Family'' is the apt title of the Columbia Pictures
release in which Close and James Woods play a childless couple who
seek the child of young Mary Stuart Masterson and her
leather-jacketed boyfriend, Kevin Dillon.
   ``It's a phenomenon in this country called `open adoption,'''
explained Close. ``Instead of there being a big mystery about who
the parents are and where they came from _ they used to seal the
files, especially from the child _ as a reaction to that, it's open
who the parents are. The adoptive parents and the birth parents, as
they're called, get together. It really is the decision of the
birth mother as to who she going to give the child to.''
   What happens if the birth mother changes her mind later?
   ``It's very difficult after all the legal procedures to get a
child back,'' she said. ``There is that horrible period between
when you're given the child and everything is taken care of legally
when the mother can change her mind, and many women do, I think.
That's the terrible emotional minefield.
   ``Once the (legalities) are done, it's hard to reverse it. I
don't know the statistics on how often that happens. I know people
who send Christmas cards to the birth mother, and people who
correspond more than that. I would think that the child would want
to know who the mother is, have pictures of her and maybe even meet
her. He would consider adoptive parents as parents, what they
really are. That's the world that he knows.''
   ``Immediate Family'' follows two stunning portrayals for Close:
as the murderous career woman in ``Fatal Attraction'' and the
scheming Marquise de Merteuil in ``Dangerous Liaisons.'' In both
films she wreaked dire revenge on men who had spurned her, but she
doesn't consider the women evil.
   ``A tragic victim ... out of control,'' is her assessment of the
``Fatal Attraction'' protagonist.
   ``And I think ultimately the Marquise de Merteuil is a victim of
her society,'' she added. ``That's my subjective viewpoint. Yeah,
they were dangerous people. But they were also trying to survive.''
   Is it possible to play a role without feeling any sympathy for
the character?
   ``I don't think it is. Whenever I approach a role, there always
has to be a place where I can identify with her humanity, and
basically love them.''
   Close gives dimension to her role as the barren Linda Spector in
``Immediate Family.'' What helped with Barbara Benedek's script,
she said, ``was its wonderful sense of humor. For all the pain that
Linda and Michael are going through, they also have a sense of
humor about themselves, and about life. It helps to get through the
hard times.''
   She found close parallels between Glenn and Linda, though their
histories are different. After two childless marriages and two
divorces, she gave birth to Annie Maude seven weeks before starting
``Dangerous Liaisons.'' She lives with the father, producer John
Starke.
   Glenn (named after her godmother) Close was born May 19, 1947,
in Greenwich, Conn., the middle of three children of a well-to-do
family.
   ``When I was really little, the golden age of Walt Disney made a
huge impression on me,'' she recalled. ```The Littlest Outlaw,'
`Old Yeller,' `The Vanishing Prairie,' `The Living Desert' ...
vivid movies for a child, wonderful, wonderful movies.
   ``That had a lot to do with my fantasy life of wanting to be an
actor, to be in movies like that. I grew up in the country, and my
parents were quite _ actually antisocial. We had a great
upbringing; we could have been in Iowa. We were very near to New
York, but we only went in to see `The Nutcracker Suite' and the
Barnum and Bailey circus and to have our eyes examined.''
   She admitted that her parents were concerned when she left home
to pursue an acting career in New York: ``I come from a very Yankee
family with Yankee values. I was quite an elusive child. I had a
very active imagination. I was a bookworm and a tomboy and very
shy. My parents didn't know what acting would elicit from me. But
I've proven to them that it's fine for my character.''
   Close was a latecomer to films, starting with ``The World
According to Garp,'' playing Robin Williams' mother when she was
34. Why didn't she begin earlier?
   ``Circumstance,'' she replied. ``I was working in theater, and
I've never been good at auditioning. I feel almost characterless
when I'm put in that kind of position. I don't know how to promote
myself. Because I'm an actor, I would not be playing myself. It's a
strange, horrible, limbo situation.
   ``And I don't think people really knew what to do with me. I'd
been doing theater, but a lot of people don't see theater. So it
just had to have that time and place, which was `Barnum' (on
Broadway) and George Roy Hill, who put me in `Garp' after seeing me
in `Barnum'.''
   Filmmakers found out what to do with her. The results have
produced five Academy nominations. They are: ``Garp,'' ``The Big
Chill,'' ``The Natural,'' ``Fatal Attraction'' and ``Dangerous
Liaisons.''
   She kids about the fact that she has been a five-time bridesmaid
without becoming a bride at the Oscars: ``Well, I'm not married in
life. So we'll see.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 10-12</NOTE>
</DOC>
