<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     10-31 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Up on Treasury Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction, which included a couple of
unusual twists to enable continued operation of the government
despite a decline in its borrowing authority.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.8 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.78 percent, up from 7.52 percent
last week.
   Another $7.8 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average
discount rate of 7.62 percent, up from 7.5 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since Oct. 2, when three-month bills
sold for 7.83 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.92 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.05 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,799.00 and 8.04 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,610.50.
   Monday's auction differed from the usual weekly sale in two ways
because of the expected drop in the government's debt ceiling at
midnight Tuesday from $2.87 trillion to $2.8 trillion.
   To ensure that the lower ceiling does not stop Social Security
checks from going out this week, the Treasury Department required
buyers of the three-and six-month bills to pay for those securities
Tuesday rather than on Thursday as usually would be the case.
   And the Treasury auctioned an additional $2 billion on Monday to
take full advantage of the $2.87 trillion borrowing authority
before it expires on Tuesday.
   The average discount rate for the new 51-day bills was 7.87
percent. But it too understates the actual return to investors _
8.07 percent for a $10,000 bill selling for $9,888.50.
   The House has voted to raise the debt ceiling to $3.1 trillion
for the current fiscal year, but Senate legislation has been
blocked by a squabble over whether to cut the capital gains tax.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for 1-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for
making changes in adjustable-rate mortgages, fell to 7.81 percent
last week, down from 7.85 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
