<FIRST>r f PM-ManufacturersHanover     10-31 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manufacturers Hanover,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manufacturers Employee Held in Connection with $2.2 Million Embezzlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss police said they arrested a former
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. investment banker in connection
with the alleged embezzlement of $2.2 million from the New York
bank's Geneva office.
   A Manufacturers Hanover spokesman, John Stefans, confirmed in
New York that ``irregularities concerning customer accounts were
discovered in our Geneva office'' and that Swiss authorities were
investigating.
   Swiss court officials said Konstantin Phacos, 39, was arrested
last week and was being held during the investigation of the
alleged embezzlement, which the officials said took place over the
past three years.
   Stefans declined to confirm the amount of money allegedly
embezzled, but he said Phacos had been dismissed from the bank.
Stefans refused further comment while the police investigation was
under way.
   The spokesman said losses like those that occurred in the Geneva
office are normally covered by insurance and do not affect the
company's earnings.
</TEXT>
