<DOCNO> AP891031-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Moody's-Shearson     10-31 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Moody's-Shearson,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moody's Is Reviewing Shearson's Long-Term Debt Rating</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moody's Investors Service Inc. said it is
reviewing its senior credit ratings on about $4.8 billion in
long-term debt of Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc. with the
possibility of lowering the ratings.
   Shearson is a leading financial services company whose holdings
include the principal broker-dealer subsidiary Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   Moody's, a leading debt-rating agency, cited ``sharpening
competition in the securities business'' as well as profit problems
at Shearson's Boston Safe Deposit &amp; Trust Co. subsidiary for the
review.
   It said Monday that Boston Safe has been a major contributor to
Shearson's earnings, but recent profit problems there could
adversely affect Shearson's future returns.
   The agency said it also was concerned about Shearson's
``substantial commercial real estate exposure via its Balcor
subsidiary.''
   Moody's said it planned to review ``the prospects for and the
quality of these assets.''
   The rating agency also said it would examine Shearson's tangible
capital levels, which it said were low and were weakened by
accounting for goodwill expanded in Shearson's January 1988
acquisition of E.F. Hutton Group.
   ``In addition, Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings has a significant
level of double leverage, which is the use of debt to fund equity
investments in subsidiaries. This significant double leverage
weakens debtholder protection measures,'' the statement said.
   A spokesman for Shearson said the company had no comment on the
Moody's announcement, but would cooperate in the review.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
