<HEAD>Bush Endorses U.S.-Japan Fishing Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has asked Congress to approve a
two-year extension of an agreement with Japan governing fishing off
the coasts of the United States.
   The original agreement was signed in 1982 and has been routinely
extended every two years by a joint resolution from Congress.
   ``Several U.S. fishing industry interests have urged prompt
consideration of this agreement,'' Bush said Monday in letter to
Congress. ``Because of the importance of our fishing relationship
with Japan, I urge that the Congress give favorable consideration
of this agreement at an early date.''
