<DOCNO> AP891031-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-LiquorAds Bjt   10-31 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Liquor Ads, Bjt,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liquor Marketers Plan Unusual Holiday Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For liquor marketers, 'tis the season to be
inventive.
   As the Christmas season approaches, liquor makers and importers
have come up with magazine ads that ``talk'' when the page is
opened, dazzle with a hologram and provide peel-and-stick decals to
liven up a dull party scene.
   The ads, which are each costing $500,000 to several million
dollars to produce and place in magazines ranging from Business
Week to Rolling Stone, are designed to boost sales at a critical
time of year for the liquor industry.
   Liquor industry analysts said the holiday season, which includes
Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's Day, accounts for 30 percent
to 40 percent of annual sales in some categories of the distilled
spirits business, an industry with little to cheer about in recent
years.
   Health concerns, tougher enforcement of drunken-driving laws, an
increase in the legal drinking age to 21 and calls for tougher
restrictions on liquor marketing have taken a toll on consumption
of alcoholic beverages.
   According to the Distilled Spirits Council, per capita
consumption of liquor fell 3.1 percent to 1.54 gallons last year
from 1.59 gallons in 1987. It has fallen every year since peaking
at 2 gallons per person in 1978.
   John Maxwell Jr., who follows the beverage industry for the
investment firm Wheat First Securities Inc. in Richmond, Va., said
consumption of all alcoholic beverages has been declining due to
liftestyle changes.
   But the products promoted in some of this year's unusual holiday
ads are among those categories that claim sales growth.
   The House of Seagram, for instance, is spending an estimated $3
million to $4 million on offbeat ads for Chivas Regal Scotch whisky
and Crown Royal Canadian whisky.
   The four-page Chivas ad, which will appear in holiday issues of
Newsweek and Business Week, among others, asks the question, ``What
if you don't give Chivas Regal for Christmas?''
   Readers _ presumably rich ones _ are invited to tear away tabs
that reveal the humorous consequences of failing to give Chivas to
people like the gardener or the pool man. (Answers: The gardener
may pave the lawn, while the pool man could put sharks in the pool.)
   In an ad for Crown Royal, Seagram has a fold-out photograph of
eight bored partygoers stewing in an elegantly furnished room. The
ad carries 15 peel-and-stick decals with items such as Santa's
elves hats and boxer shorts with kisses that readers can use to
liven up the stuffy drawing-room scene.
   The Crown Royal ad is appearing in Rolling Stone and GQ, among
others.
   Thomas K. McInerney, executive vice president for marketing at
House of Seagram, said he hopes readers will have some fun with the
ads.
   ``If we can get them to stop for 15 seconds or 30 seconds, that
would be a success,'' he said.
   If readers have fun with an ad, the theory is they become more
favorably disposed toward the product and will remember the brand
name when stocking up for a holiday party or buying a gift.
   Absolut Vodka has come up with a ``talking'' ad that uses a
microchip to offer spoken holiday greetings in metallic-sounding
English, Italian and Spanish each time its ad is opened.
   Absolut is spending $1.2 million to include the ad in 200,000
December issues sent to Vanity Fair subscribers in New York State
and California.
   Finlandia Vodka is using a hologram that shows a bottle of the
drink and the outline of two reindeer in combat on the label in an
ad that will appear in the yearend double issue of Rolling Stone
distributed in New York, Chicago and California and the Christmas
Gifts issue of New York magazine.
   The ad cost about $500,000 to produce and place in the
magazines, and is being billed as the first liquor ad to use one of
the 3-D images.
   McDonald's Corp. used a hologram for a 1988 ad that appeared on
the back cover of National Geographic, which also had a hologram on
the front cover.
   Jim Beam Brands Co. decided to make a variation of its new ad
campaign that shows evolving consumer tastes in everything from
sandwiches to underwear.
   In its Christmas ad for Jim Beam bourbon, the company shows the
evolution of the Christmas tree from 1952 to the present from
standard evergreen to flocked to metallic to sculpted and back to
evergreen again.
   ``You always come back to the basics,'' is the message that will
appear in 17 different publications this holiday season, including
Playboy, Working Woman and Self.
</TEXT>
