<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-MonetarySystem 1stLd-Writethru f0009 10-31 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Monetary System, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0009,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Apparently Hardening Against Pound's Link With Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that nine, stead eight, nations in
the monetary system. INSERTS 1 new graf after 2nd graf to ADD other holdout
nations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher appears to be
hardening her position against linking the British pound to other
European currencies despite mounting pressure from her own
Conservative party.
   The growing impression is that Mrs. Thatcher is using an
increasing number of conditions as a pretext not to link the pound
to the 10-year-old exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary
System. The EMS links the currencies of nine of the 12 Common
Market nations to prevent wide currency swings.
   Since Spain joined in June, only Britain, Greece and Portugal
are outside the system.
   Economists now don't expect the pound to be linked before the
next general election, which Mrs. Thatcher must call before
mid-1992.
   Nations linked to the mechanism enjoy currency stability that
helps industry and Common Market planning. But they relinquish
control over an important element of their monetary affairs.
   The European Economic Community is working toward European
monetary union, which would create a single European currency and a
single central bank for the nations.
   But Mrs. Thatcher opposes relinquishing British sovereignty and
champions free-market policies.
   The issue of British participation in the exchange rate
mechanism was seen as central in Thursday's sudden resignation of
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, which created a Cabinet
crisis and shook British financial markets.
   Lawson, who advocated joining the mechanism, said he couldn't
continue to serve in his post as long as Mrs. Thatcher's personal
economic adviser, Sir Alan Walters, stayed. Walters, who called the
system ``half-baked,'' resigned hours later.
   The pound has fallen sharply in recent weeks, fueling inflation
fears and prompting the government to push interest rates to an
eight-year high of 15 percent as well as intervene repeatedly in
the market. Both measures have had limited success.
   The pound was quoted at $1.5785 in Europe late Monday, compared
with $1.6665 on July 31.
   Mrs. Thatcher used to say that the pound would be linked ``when
the time is right.'' Then, in a compromise during June's EEC sumit
in Madrid, she agreed to link the pound once capital flowed freely
in Europe and after Britain's inflation rate, now running at 7.6
percent, fell in line with the lower rates of other European
countries.
   In a Sunday television interview, she went further, saying that
Continental insurance and pension funds must be run as openly and
freely as Britain's and that government subsidies of industries
must end.
   ``You can't have a currency like sterling playing under that
higgledy-piggledy set of rules,'' she said.
   France will eliminate exchange rate controls in July, she said,
but it will take some time for Italy to follow.
   ``I like a strong pound,'' she said, but added that only
intervention and interest rates would keep it that way.
   Charles Bean, who teaches economics at the London School of
Economics, said Monday: ``I certainly interpreted it as a
strengthening of her preconditions of joining the EMS.''
   Robin Aspinall, director of currency economics at the London
investment firm Hoare Govett Ltd., said: ``It was a reaffirmation
certainly. She has been adamant in her position. That was more
fleshing out the details.''
   Labor lawmaker John Smith, the opposition party's chief
financial spokesman, said Sunday, ``Both the tone and content of
Mrs. Thatcher's interview show that she is flatly against joining
the (mechanism) for the foreseeable future.''
   The position of the new chancellor, John Major, is not yet clear.
   Deputy Prime Minister Sir Geoffrey Howe, in a Saturday speech
widely interpreted as a challenge to Mrs. Thatcher, said it was
essential that Britain reaffirm its Madrid commitment in order to
maintain confidence among its European partners.
   Howe was demoted from the more influential position of foreign
secretary in July, apparently for his pro-Europe views.
   Bean said many politicians are now advocating joining the EMS,
including Howe, some rank-and-file Conservative lawmakers and many
Laborites.
   Joining the mechanism would remove uncertainty about monetary
policy, and would allow Britain to lower interest rates without
hurting the pound, Bean said.
   In addition, Bean said: ``It makes some difference from a
political point of view. You can argue that it indicates greater
commitment to Europe.''
   But it's not a panacea, he said, and won't prevent an expected
slowdown in the British economy.
   Aspinall said: ``We would have the same dilemma but more of an
obligation to protect the currency. The protection of the currency
would require us to be intervening or raising interest rates.''
</TEXT>
