<DOCNO> AP891031-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ProgramTrading Bjt   10-31 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Program Trading, Bjt,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Index Futures Increasingly the Target of Market Critics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yet another major Wall Street house says it will
curb program trading, a computer-driven practice that critics claim
is dangerously distorting the stock market and scaring away small
investors.
   On Monday, Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. announced it would halt so-called
index arbitrage for clients until the stock market calms down.
Paine Webber group Inc. took a similar step last week.
   Kidder Peabody &amp; Co. said Monday it would execute index
arbitrage trades only for clients, not for its own account. Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. Inc., Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. and Oppenheimer &amp; Co. made
similar announcements last week.
   Index arbitrage involves stock-index futures, contracts to buy
or sell baskets of stocks based on particular indexes like the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index. These contracts have come to represent
a bigger market than that of common stocks _ and one with higher
stakes.
   Using computer programs, traders seek to capitalize on brief and
minute differences in the prices of stocks and stock-index futures
by buying or selling stocks with opposite trades in the futures.
   It has become entirely typical for stock traders and investors
to look to the futures market as an indicator of where equities are
headed. The fundamentals of individual companies _ their earnings,
their marketing strategies and the overall quality of their
products _ have fallen by the wayside.
   ``It's a disgrace,'' said James J. Cramer, investment manager of
Cramer &amp; Co. ``The market has very little to do with individual
stocks anymore and trades as a whole from the individual programs.''
   Indeed, the stock of telephone and electronic giant Contel Corp.
is down from a month ago even though it announced a 16 percent
increase in its quarterly profits a week after the Friday the 13th
stock market plunge.
   ``Why?'' Chairman Charles Wohlstetter asked rhetorically. ``What
the hell for? The stock is now selling 5{ points below where it was
before that Friday and every bit of information and news that came
out is better than anybody anticipated.''
   But Wohlstetter is determined to turn attention to trading
tactics that hurt his company. In an interview Monday, Wohlstetter
said he has talked to about 50 corporate executives who are
contemplating joining him to complain to authorities in what is
believed to be the first such effort organized at the corporate
level. He did not name his potential allies.
   ``I'll take it to the moon if I have to ... in order to bring to
the attention of the corporate world that the stock exchange has
lost its sense of direction,'' Wohlstetter said.
   The protest already has begun to take shape. In Monday editions
of The New York Times, Neuberger &amp; Berman, an investment management
firm overseeing some $17.5 billion, took out a full-page
advertisement imploring: ``Stop the numbers racket on Wall
Street.'' The ad urged investors to voice their concerns in writing
to Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Richard Breeden and
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   Arguments over unconventional trading strategies came to a head
following the 1987 Black Monday market crash. But the stock
market's recent volatility _ begun Oct. 13 when the Dow Jones
industrial average plunged 190 points in little more than an hour _
has renewed the debate.
   Virtually all observers agree that a ban on stock-index futures
is unrealistic, particularly since the Chicago-based futures
exchanges have the support of many powerful Midwestern politicians.
   But many suggest leveling the playing field by raising the
deposit requirements on futures contracts from 10 percent to 50
percent, making it parallel with margin requirements for stock
purchases.
   With current deposit requirements, someone in the futures market
is able to control $170,000 worth of stocks with a payment of
$9,000, said Larry Zicklin, a managing partner at Neuberger &amp;
Berman.
   ``If you tried to buy $170,000 worth of an underlying stock on
the New York Stock Exchange, you'd have to put up a minimum of
$85,000.''
   While no one knows just how much activity would be dampened by a
tightening of deposit requirements, Zicklin speculated it would be
``substantial.'' Others go so far as to say such a move would in
effect wipe out the strategy.
   Zicklin acknowledges his personal interest in seeing such
strategies curtailed. He neither wants to lose investors who could
become fearful of market swings caused by index arbitrage and
program trading, nor does he want to see stock prices ease as more
money is pulled out of the market.
   ``The market has to be able to attract the private investor with
some degree of comfort that he is not going to be battered around
during the course of a day,'' said Jack Barbanel, president of
First Global Asset Management Inc. in Princeton, N.J. ``He is
drastically psychologically affected when his portfolio moves up
and down in the course of an hour.''
   Barbanel noted, however, that although futures contracts to not
accurately mirror the value of individual stocks, they do correctly
reflect the value of the market as a whole.
   ``If you up the margin requirement, it's like punishing the
instrument instead of punishing the people,'' he said. He said he
favors eliminating index arbitrage rather than trading in index
futures.
</TEXT>
