<DOCNO> AP891031-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Chevron     10-31 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chevron,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chevron Stock Rise Not Surprising, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recent rise in Chevron Corp. stock is not
surprising since it has been undervalued in recent years, analysts
said, as share prices continued to climb amid takeover speculation.
   Chevron's stock closed at $67.25 a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Monday, up 87{ cents from $66.37{
Friday. Chevron's stock has risen about 48 percent this year, from
a low of $45.37{.
   ``It doesn't surprise me. The stock is cheap,'' said Charles
Maxwell, vice chairman and senior energy strategist for C.J.
Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc., dismissing talk that a buyout of
the nation's fourth-largest oil concern is likely.
   Chevron's share price only recently surpassed its previous high
of $64 in 1987 after hardly moving during the previous year,
analysts said.
   ``Chevron stock is undervalued in relation to its asset value;
but not undervalued in terms of price-earnings ratio,'' said Paul
Ting, with the investment firm Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Chevron, rich in oil and gas reserves and a high-performing
chemicals unit, had sales in 1988 of $28.9 billion, down from $29.1
billion in 1987. Earnings last year totaled $1.8 billion, or $5.17
a share, up about 40 percent from $1.3 billion, or $3.65 a share.
   Its $13.3 billion purchase of Gulf Oil in 1984 came just before
a sharp drop in oil prices. The earnings potential of those assets
as well as its 1988 purchase of Tenneco Inc.'s oil and gas
properties in the Gulf of Mexico for $2.5 billion have yet to be
realized, analysts said.
   Chevron's stock has jumped in recent weeks partly on speculation
that the
   San Francisco-based oil concern is ripe for a takeover, possibly
by Pennzoil Co. British Petroleum Co. PLC also has been mentioned
as an interested party.
   A Chevron buyout would be the largest to date. Some analysts say
that in a breakup, Chevron's assets could be worth $100 to $125 a
share _ or approximately $40 billion.
   A published report Monday suggested that a group of investors
could be acting in concert to force Chevron into a restructuring
that would boost the stock further.
   A buyer, possibly a company acting alone or with partners, has
accumulated 12 million to 16 million shares of Chevron stock, or
3.5 percent to 4.7 percent, USA Today reported.
   Chevron spokesman Larry Shushan declined to comment on the
stock's purchaser, in accordance with company policy.
   Pennzoil also declined to comment, but the Houston-based oil
company is rumored to be looking for a place to park some $2.5
billion in cash that it received in a 1988 settlement with Texaco
Inc. following a prolonged battle over Getty Oil Co.
   ``How is Pennzoil going to buy Chevron with $2.5 billion? It
would have to be a junk bond situation,'' said Maxwell, adding that
leveraged deals have lost favor on Wall Street.
   ``No one is going to let Pennzoil have $30 billion to $40
billion in junk bonds,'' Maxwell said.
   ``Pennzoil threatening Chevron is like a kid threatening Mike
Tyson,'' said one securities analyst who did not wish to be named.
   Constantine Fliakos, vice president of Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets, in a recent newsletter also dismissed speculation that the
Houston-based company was a serious contender ``unless Pennzoil is
interested in triggering its own `demise' in the event that Chevron
were to react defensively.''
   Although some analysts said they saw no evidence of a serious
takeover attempt featuring either junk bonds or cash, a ``group
attack'' is not out of the question, they said.
   In addition, some suggested the possibility of a BP-Pennzoil
partnership or a BP-Chevron combination. British Petroleum, which
has said it wants to boost its West Coast properties, recently
denied it would make a major U.S. purchase anytime soon.
   In its latest quarter, Chevron's earnings declined to $417
million, or $1.22 a share, from $420 million, or $1.23 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to $8 billion from $7.2 billion.
</TEXT>
