<FIRST>u f PM-LincolnS&amp;L Bjt   10-31 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L, Bjt,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Defenders Angered by House Chairman's Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Hearing scheduled 10 a.m. EST; lead on merits only. Also moved
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrift regulator M. Danny Wall's defenders are
complaining that a House committee chairman is trying to force Wall
to resign before he has a chance to answer the charges against him.
   The House Banking Committee, chaired by Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez,
D-Texas, is scheduled today to conduct its third hearing into the
collapse of the Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, Irvine,
Calif., which is expected to become the nation's costliest thrift
failure.
   In a letter to President Bush released by the committee Monday,
Gonzalez said Wall's policy of reviewing in advance the testimony
of his subordinates in the Office of Thrift Supervision is
hampering the committee's investigations and suggested the
regulator should step aside.
   Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for the thrift agency, said the
suggestion was ``inappropriate'' and Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, for
whom Wall once worked as chief aide, said it was ``uncalled for.''
   ``Obviously Rep. Gonzalez is looking for a scapegoat on which to
place the blame'' for the S&amp;L bailout, said Garn, the senior
Republican on the Senate Banking Committee.
   The House panel plans to conduct at least one more hearing, and
possibly more, before giving Wall a chance to respond.
   Hoyle said he is concerned Congress will recess for the holidays
before Wall and top aides get a chance to defend his actions. Three
senior thrift agency officials _ counsel Jordan Luke, regulation
director Darrel Dochow and enforcement director Rosemary Stewart _
had been scheduled to appear today, but their testimony has been
postponed.
   ``Dan Wall, like anybody else in this country, is entitled to
due process. ... Quite candidly, I think there's a very fine line
between investigation and prosecution,'' Hoyle said.
   Gonzalez, in a letter to Bush dated last Friday, said his panel
has heard ``startling evidence'' that Wall blocked efforts by field
examiners in the thrift agency's San Francisco office to collect
evidence of misconduct by Lincoln officials.
   The committee is focusing on why Wall in 1987 rejected their
recommendation to seize Lincoln and instead ordered another
examination after the institution's owner, Phoenix, Ariz.,
millionaire Charles H. Keating Jr., complained he was being treated
unfairly by San Francisco regulators.
   ``In view of your commitment to not let those responsible for
these costly failures remain in positions of authority in your
administration, I believe it would be reassuring to the American
taxpayers who have been asked to pay for this regulatory failure if
Mr. Wall steps aside,'' Gonzalez told Bush.
   At today's hearing, the committee was scheduled to hear from 10
thrift examiners from around the country who were assembled by Wall
to review the work of the San Francisco office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
