<FIRST>u f PM-Skinner-Buyouts Bjt   10-31 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skinner-Buyouts, Bjt,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Secretary Shuns Bill to Strengthen His Hand</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: House action possible after noon EST; lead prospects uncertain.
Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner says
he doesn't need the new authority to deal with airline takeovers
that a bill before Congress would give him.
   Skinner said Monday the legislation, which would give the
Transportation Department the power to approve or disapprove
airline mergers before they occur, ``smacks of reregulation'' of
the airline industry.
   ``It probably is reregulation and is inappropriate in a
deregulated environment,'' he said in an interview.
   The Air Carrier Securities Act, which was scheduled for House
action today, would require the department to block purchase of 15
percent or more of an airline if the sale threatened to hinder
safety, reduce competition, break up the carrier or put it under
foreign control.
   Skinner currently has the authority to review airline
transactions for their financial fitness, their safety and the
degree of foreign involvement. The law limits foreign interest in
U.S. carriers to 25 percent of voting stock.
   Skinner said he doesn't think he needs additional powers to
prevent a financially unsound takeover.
   ``I think there are other ways I can do it,'' he said. ``We can
advise individuals who are anticipating a transaction ... as to
some of the problems with a transaction if we see any.''
   The secretary said he had reservations about the planned union
and management takeover of United Airlines, but he denied any
responsibility for failure of the plan. Financial analysts say
collapse of the stock buyout move on United's parent company, UAL
Corp., triggered the Oct. 13 drop in the stock market.
   ``The United Airlines transaction fell for one reason and one
reason only _ it was not sound financially,'' said Skinner.
   Failure of the UAL takeover bid followed agreement of Skinner
with Alfred Checchi to scale down foreign participation in
Checchi's stock buyout of Northwest Airlines' parent company, NWA
Inc. The department concluded the original deal put KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines in a position to control Northwest.
   Responding to reports that other administration officials had
been critical of his NWA action, Skinner said, ``Anybody who says
that I did not keep the White House informed fully as to what was
going on prior to making those decisions just isn't informed.''
   Skinner said every step he took was ``thoroughly coordinated''
with senior White House officials. He declined, however, to
describe any conversations he had with other administration
officials over his NWA action.
   The secretary said his reservations about the United deal, which
was to be financed by banks and British Airways, prompted him to
conduct a department review of the proposal. But he gave no opinion
at the time about its soundness.
   ``I talked to leading scholars and accountants and management
consultants who are experts in the airline industry, and they all
expressed reservations which just fortified my concerns,'' Skinner
said, adding that financial problems with the deal would increase
safety and maintenance concerns.
   The takeover bill has had strong bipartisan support, passing the
Public Works and Transportation Committee 23-5. A similar measure
passed the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee
but has not come up on the Senate floor.
   The takeover legislation was prompted by the United and
Northwest deals and the aborted attempt by developer Donald Trump
to buy AMR Corp., parent company of American Airlines. The decline
in the stock market led Trump to withdraw his $7.5 billion plan
which was opposed by AMR management.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL Bjt   10-31 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL, Bjt,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Pilots Resume Contract Talks With UAL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines' pilots are going back to the
bargaining table and threatening to ground the carrier's newest
jetliners.
   Having failed in their bid to lead an employee buyout of United
parent UAL Corp., the pilots say the contract concessions they
agreed to as a part of that effort _ including flying United's new
747-400 aircraft _ will expire Nov. 22.
   Unless they get a new contract by then, the pilots say they'll
stop flying those planes, forcing United to substitute smaller jets
on daily round-trip flights between Los Angeles and Sydney and
Melbourne, Australia.
   ``We'll be exactly where we were in the pre-buyout
environment,'' said Hank Krakowski, a spokesman for the United
chapter of the Air Line Pilots Association.
   The pilots agreed to fly the planes beginning Sept. 18, ending a
dispute over the size of the cockpit crew that had kept the planes
grounded since June.
   Krakowski said the pilots and UAL resumed negotiations Monday on
a contract to succeed a pact that expired in April 1988.
   Also on Monday, the union representing United's flight
attendants said it had been contacted by California billionaire
Marvin Davis, who first put Chicago-based UAL into play in August.
A published report said Davis has also talked with the airline's
pilots and Machinists with an eye toward re-entering the fight for
ownership of the nation's second-largest carrier.
   United's stock rose $4 a share to $175 Monday on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   United pilots agreed to fly the 747-400s and to increase their
workload to 85 flight-hours a month from 81 with no additional pay,
effective Nov. 1, as a show of good faith in their bid to
participate in an employee-management buyout of UAL for $6.75
billion.
   The deal, which also included minority participation by UAL's
top management and British Airways PLC, collapsed Oct. 13 when the
group failed to secure financing for their $300-a-share bid.
   British Airways has since dropped out and United's flight
attendants have signed on to the group, which hopes to make a
revised offer for UAL.
   Had the buyout gone through, the pilots also had agreed to
accept a 7-year contract requiring a 10 percent pay cut.
   UAL spokeswoman Sara Dornacker declined comment on whether
grounding the 747-400s would disrupt United service between Los
Angeles and Australia. She said the airline had flown the route
using smaller 747-SPs from early 1986 until last month, when United
put two 747-400s into service.
   ``We have the ability to substitute one aircraft for another on
any given route,'' Ms. Dornacker said.
   The technologically superior 400s can carry 392 passengers,
compared with 247 in the SPs, and have a 33 percent larger cargo
capacity, she said.
   Davis contacted the United chapter of the Association of Flight
Attendants on Friday, said AFA spokeswoman Patricia Friend. She
would not comment on the nature of the call.
   The Los Angeles Times reported on Saturday that Davis adviser
David Batchelder had discussed a potential UAL buyout offer with
the pilots, the flight attendants and the International Association
of Machinists and Aerospace Workers, which represents United's
mechanics and ground crews.
   Krakowski said he did not know if the pilots had been contacted
by Davis and the Machinists did not return telephone calls seeking
to confirm the Times report.
   Davis' office in Los Angeles also did not return calls.
   The Machinists' opposition to employee ownership was seen as one
factor in the failure of the pilot-management bid for UAL. Analysts
say the cooperation of and concessions from the unions are critical
for any succesful buyout of the airline.
</TEXT>
