<DOCNO> AP891031-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0845EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Revco-Bidding     10-31 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Revco-Bidding,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revco Considers Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TWINSBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Revco D.S. Inc. said the
troubled drug store chain is considering an unsolicited $925
million buyout bid from Acadia Partners L.P. and the Robert M. Bass
Group.
   The proposal would add an estimated $260 million debt to the
highly leveraged company.
   Revco, with about 1,900 drugstores in 27 states, is undergoing
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code.
   The company's 1986 billion leveraged buy-out, financed with
high-interest junk bonds, ran into trouble in 1988. It was the
first large leveraged-buyout deal of the 1980s to falter.
   With the new debt, along with $150 million in cash, the
purchasers would provide $410 million for payments to creditors and
debt interest.
   Boake A. Sells, Revco's chairman, said Monday the plan by the
Fort Worth, Texas, businesses would add to Revco's existing debt of
$515 million for a total indebtedness of $775 million.
   He said the offer was being studied. He did not say when a
response would be made.
   On Oct. 24, a U.S. bankruptcy judge granted Revco an extension
of its period of exclusivity to file a reorganization plan through
April, 1990. After that, creditors may file their own plans.
</TEXT>
