<FIRST>d f BC-Bausch&amp;Lomb     10-31 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bausch &amp; Lomb,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bausch &amp; Lomb Passes $1 Billion Sales Mark, Gives Employees Day Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bausch &amp; Lomb Inc. will give all its
employees a day off to celebrate passing the $1 billion sales
level, it was announced Tuesday.
   Dec. 22 will be a paid holiday for the Rochester-based eye and
health care company's 12,400 employees worldwide. The company
achieved $1 billion in sales for 1989 last week for the first time
in its history.
   Reaching the $1 billion figure ``is such a matter of pride and
prestige,'' said Daniel E. Gill, chairman and chief executive
officer of the 136-year-old company. ``It just puts you into a new
realm.''
   Gill predicted the company would reach at least $1.2 billion in
sales by the end of the year.
   Company officials have kept track of Bausch &amp; Lomb's progress
toward the $1 billion mark with daily bulletins since last
September. Ordinarily, sales are not reported on a daily basis.
   The company's sales have grown at an annual rate of more than 20
percent for the past five years, Gill said. So far this year, sales
have grown by 28 percent, led by the company's international
business and its sunglass and oral care divisions.
   Earnings for the year so far are about 16 percent higher than in
1988.
</TEXT>
