<FIRST>u f PM-GreatNorthern 2ndLd-Writethru f0039 10-31 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Great Northern, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0039,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Pacific Makes Bid for Great Northern Nekoosa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf to ADD comment from Great Northern; ADDS comments
from analyst in new grafs 8-13; picks up 8th graf pvs, ``Georgia Pacific...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE: NEW YORK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Pacific Corp. said today that it
offered to acquire Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. in a cash deal that
values the company at around $3.13 billion.
   The $58-a-share bid confirms several days of market rumors that
Georgia-Pacific, a forest products company based in Atlanta, would
attempt to take over Great Northern, a Norwalk, Conn., paper
products company.
   Georgia Pacific said its bid represented a 50 percent premium
over the market price of Great Northern before takeover speculation
drove up the stock's price starting last Thursday.
   Nekoosa closed up $2.75 at $42.75 in active New York Stock
Exchange trading Monday. George Pacific fell 12 cents to $53.37 a
share.
   In a letter delivered today to Great Northern Chairman William
R. Laidig, Georgia Pacific Chairman T. Marshall Hahn Jr. emphasized
his desire to achieve a friendly, negotiated merger and requested a
meeting with Laidig as soon as possible.
   ``Unlike many of today's transactions driven by financial
engineering, the merger of our two companies represents an
excellent strategic fit based on industrial logic,'' Hahn said.
``This combination will result in a stronger and more competitive
forest products company.''
   Laidig, in a news release, said the offer was uninvited, but
would be considered, along with the request to negotiate a merger,
``in due course'' by the board of directors.
   Mark Kurland, an analyst with Mabon Nugent &amp; Co. in New York,
said the offer probably could trigger bids from other forest
products companies, including Champion International Co.,
International Paper Corp., Weyerhauser Co., and Canada's
Abitibi-Price Inc.
   ``I'm sure they have calls in to Great Northern right now,''
said Kurland, who expected Great Northern would attempt to secure
the best price for its shareholders if it could not fend off a
takeover attempt by Georgia Pacific.
   Kurland said he would not be surprised if Great Northern pursued
a friendly merger with Champion or Boise Cascade Corp. in order to
avoid an unwanted takeover.
   Great Northern would be an attractive acquisition for Georgia
Pacific because it would allow the company to acquire 7 percent of
both the linerboard and white paper markets in the United States
without having to build its own operations, Kurland said.
   Great Northern has been expanding its facilities. On Monday, it
announced it was acquiring a 50 percent interest in a linerboard
mill in Oklahoma. Two years ago, it bought a paper and box
production unit from Owens-Illinois Inc. for $1.5 billion.
   But Kurland said he was surprised Georgia Pacific's bid came
now, during a downward cycle in the paper products industry he
attributed to a general economic slowdown and expansions in the
paper industry.
   Georgia Pacific said it was offering $58 a share in cash for
each of Great Northern's approximately 54 million shares
outstanding, making the company worth around $3.13 billion.
However, it said it would cost approximately $4.5 billion to
consummate the offer, including ``refinancing certain indebtedness
of Great Northern and Georgia Pacific and pay related fees and
expenses.''
   The company said the deal was conditioned on, among other
things, acquiring at least 75 percent of Great Northern's
outstanding shares by Nov. 29.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
