<FIRST>r f PM-FDA-Cereal 2ndLd-Writethru f0040 10-31 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA-Cereal, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0040,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Chairman Faults OMB for Allowing Cereal Makers to Lie</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 8 grafs new with hearing; picks up 7th graf pvs, `Last month
...' Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House panel investigating
cereal makers' health claims said today that pressure from the
Office of Management and Budget on federal regulators has allowed
food manufacturers to lie about the benefits of eating their
products.
   ``Based on all the evidence the subcommittee has uncovered in
this an other investigations, I am concerned that the agency
empowered by Congress to make the federal government's health
policy is not performing that function,'' said Rep. Ted Weiss,
D-N.Y., chairman of the House Government Operations subcommittee on
human resources and intergovernmental relations.
   ``Instead, an ideologically driven OMB has seized the controls
of the health policy ship,'' he said.
   Weiss said the Food and Drug Administration proposed in 1987
that explicit disease-prevention claims be allowed on food labels.
   He said that under OMB pressure, the FDA bypassed the normal
regulatory rules and allowed companies to begin making the health
claims immediately.
   ``The 1987 proposal has seriously weakened FDA's ability to
challenge even what the agency itself believes are deceptive
claims,'' Weiss said as he opened a hearing on the subject.
   Interviewed earlier on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show, Weiss said
manufacturers are ``playing reckless games'' with the public's
health with their claims.
   The FDA said recently it had serious concerns about cereals that
contain husks of psyllium, which contains soluable fiber.
Manufacturers say the grain is safe and can help lower cholesterol.
   Last month, the FDA told General Mills, maker of Benefit cereal,
and Kellogg Co., maker of Heartwise and Bran Buds, to submit
scientific data to the agency showing that the levels of the grain
in their products is safe.
   Benefit also contains sugar beet fiber and the FDA asked General
Mills to submit data showing it also is safe.
   The cereal makers contend that their products are safe and that
they would submit the requested data.
   Bran Buds has been on the market for a year, Benefit is being
sold in selected test markets but Heartwise is not on the market
yet.
   The issue of whether psyllium is a drug or a food additive was
raised by Procter &amp; Gamble Co., which uses psyllium in its
Metamucil laxative. The company had asked the FDA to pull Benefit
off the market because the cereal had not been subjected to
drug-testing requirements.
   In letters to General Mills and Kellogg, the FDA said there are
``well-known safety concerns'' associated with use of psyllium,
including possible allergic reactions.
   The agency noted that General Mills has warned on its label
about this possibility, provides instructions for its use on the
package label and advises consuming the cereal with adequate
liquids and restricting consumption by children.
   But the FDA also said that unlike a drug product, a food is
subject to unrestricted consumption, and such unrestricted use ``to
reduce serum cholesterol levels or for any other purpose has never
been approved by FDA.''
</TEXT>
