<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Gain Slightly; Corn and Wheat Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices were slightly higher while
the grain markets were narrowly mixed in early trading today on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   The strength in soybeans stemmed from stronger cash markets and
defied predictions for a lower opening based on a
larger-than-expected number of delivery notices posted this morning
against the November contract.
   Today is the first-notice day for the November soybean contract,
the first opportunity for traders to declare their intentions to
actually deliver soybeans when the contract expires next month.
   The corn market's weakness was seen partly as a reaction to an
unexpectedly low export inspection figure in a weekly Agriculture
Department report. The USDA said Monday it inspected about 34.7
million bushels of corn for export last week compared to 33.3
million a week earler and 31 million a year ago.
   The USDA also reported that both the corn and soybean harvests
were 79 percent complete as of Sunday.
   In early trading, wheat futures were { cent lower to 1\ cents
higher with the December contract at $3.96{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to } cent lower with December at $2.40\ a bushel; oats
were { cent higher across the board with December at $1.43\ a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 3 cents higher with November at
$5.62{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher, with pork bellies
up sharply in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange amid
speculation that Yugoslavia may buy a large amount of U.S. bellies.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with December at
74.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .47 cent higher
with November at 82.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower
to .45 cent higher with December at 46.20 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .65 cent to 1.37 cent higher with February at
54.97 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Monday, with pork
bellies posting strong gains.
</TEXT>
