<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     10-31 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0463</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were up sharply today, after a $3
billion takeover bid in the paper industry kicked some life into
the sluggish market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 28.28 points to
2,631.76 at noon EST. The blue-chip indicator was up 18.24 points
an hour earlier.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by about 2 to 1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 937 issues up, 402 down and 464 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 80.48 million shares.
   News that Georgia Pacific Corp. had offered to acquire Great
Northern Nekoosa Corp. in a cash deal valued at more than $3
billion jolted the market out of its recent slumber, analysts said.
The market had declined five straight sessions last week and
recovered only slightly on Monday.
   ``The bid for Great Northern has revitalized the deal syndrome
and the paper group,'' said Larry Wachtel, equities analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Paper stocks have floundered in recent months. In addition, Wall
Street had reacted negatively to the collapse earlier this month of
proposed deals involving UAL Corp. and AMR Corp., parent companies
of United and American airlines. The failure of a UAL pilot-led
group to get necessary financing for the deal helped trigger the
mid-October stock plunge.
   New government data suggesting that the pace of economic growth
is slowing had little immediate impact on the market.
   The Commerce Department reported that the Index of Leading
Indicators, its chief economic forecasting gauge, inched ahead 0.2
percent in September for its second consecutive monthly advance.
However, the August index, designed to foretell economic activity
six to nine months into the future, was revised upward to 0.5
percent from a 0.3 percent gain reported earlier.
   In a second report, the government said sales of new homes fell
14 percent in September, their steepest decline in nearly eight
years, as interest rates crept back to the double-digit level of
the preceding months.
   ``It was O.K. data, but the real juice was the paper
consolidation,'' said Dennis Jarrett, equities analyst with Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. ``It gives players an excuse to come off the
sidelines and bid up paper stocks.''
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.76 to 187.35.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had
gained 1.24 to 370.11.
   Great Northern Nekoosa led the NYSE most active list up 18~ to
61|; Mead Corp. had gained 2\ to 38|; and Chevron was up 2 to 68{.
   Meanwhile, Unisys was off ] to 14~; Chrysler was down ] to 20};
and Warner-Lambert had lost [ to 108].
