<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Kimberly-Clark     10-31 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Kimberly-Clark,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kimberly-Clark Third Quarter Earnings Up 20.2 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kimberly-Clark Corp. Tuesday reported a 20.2
percent jump in third quarter income mainly from increased prices
and sales of disposable diapers and feminine care products.
   Kimberly-Clark said earnings in the three months ended Sept. 30
were $108.8 million, or $1.35 per share, compared with $90.5
million, or $1.12 per share, in the comparable quarter of last year.
   Sales grew 6.2 percent to $1.45 billion this year from $1.37
billion last year.
   The quarterly improvement also was helped by a $11 million
charge last year to cover early retirement and other costs
associated with a modernization program at a pulp and newsprint
plant in Alabama.
   Net income in the nine-month period was $313.2 million, or $3.89
per share, compared with $283.9 million, or $3.53 per share. Sales
in the period rose to $4.27 billion from $4 billion.
   ``The consumer business improvements generally were due to
higher selling prices, particularly for disposable diapers and
tissue products, and from increased sales volumes, especially for
feminine care products,'' the company said.
   While consumer product income was up, the company said its
newsprint business remains depressed because of industry-wide price
discounting.
   Dallas-based Kimberly-Clark markets household, personal care and
health care products under such brands as Kleenex tissues, Kotex
and New Freedom feminine products and Huggies disposable diapers.
</TEXT>
