<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     10-31 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0495</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices steadied at sharply higher levels
in afternoon trading, sustaining a broad-based rally triggered
early in the day by news of a new $3 billion tender offer in the
paper industry.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 34.43 points to
2,637.91 at 2 p.m. EST. The blue-chip indicator was up 28.28 points
at noon EST.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by about 2 to 1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 998 issues up, 464 down and 439 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 117.22 million shares.
   The market opened higher on news that Georgia Pacific Corp. had
offered to acquire Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. in a cash deal
valued at more than $3 billion.
   ``The bid for Great Northern has revitalized the deal syndrome
and the paper group,'' said Larry Wachtel, equities analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Paper stocks have underperformed the market in recent months,
Wall Street brokers said. In addition, the market had reacted
negatively to the collapse earlier this month of proposed deals
involving UAL Corp. and AMR Corp., parent companies of United and
American airlines. The failure of a UAL pilot-led group to get
necessary financing for the deal helped trigger the mid-October
stock plunge.
   However, volume remained relatively low, leading some traders to
question the market's ability to sustain the momentum.
   ``It's a broad-based rally but there is still little volume,''
said Brad Weeks, head of equity trading for Donaldson, Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette. ``It doesn't surprise me because confidence is still very
low.''
   New government data that suggested the pace of economic growth
is slowing boosted the credit markets slightly amid hopes that the
Federal Reserve would now move to ease interest rates. But the
reports had little impact on the stock market.
   The Commerce Department reported that the Index of Leading
Indicators, its chief economic forecasting gauge, inched ahead 0.2
percent in September for its second consecutive monthly advance.
However, the index, designed to foretell economic activity six to
nine months into the future, was revised upward to 0.5 percent for
August from a 0.3 percent gain reported earlier.
   The government also reported that sales of new homes fell 14
percent in September, their steepest decline in nearly eight years,
as interest rates crept back to the double-digit level of the
preceding months.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.94 at 187.55.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had
gained 1.07 at 369.94.
   Great Northern Nekoosa led the NYSE most active list up 19 at
61} _ well above the $58-a-share tender offer by Georgia Pacific;
Chevron was up 2\ at 68}; and Chase Manhattan had gained \ at 36\.
   Unisys, meanwhile, was off { at 14} and Detroit Edison was
unchanged at 23~.
