<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0027 10-31 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0027,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End At Peaks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished at session peaks in London
Tuesday, supported by a reassuring early performance on Wall Street
and news that the British government was prepared to waive its
``golden'' share in Jaguar PLC.
   Trading was very light, however, as investors remained wary from
the market's gyrations of recent weeks.
   Volume was a modest 334.5 million shares, up from the 1989
record low of 257.8 million posted on Monday.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 30.4
points, or 1.4 percent, to close at 2,142.6, its best level for the
session.
   The key index reached a minimum of 2,120.5 points just a
half-hour into the session.
   ``Volume has been appalling,'' said a dealer at a British
brokerage firm. ``The market was dragged up by the scruff of its
neck by Wall Street and by market makers getting caught short. No
one wants stock on their books.''
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 32.18
points at 2,635.66 as London trading finished.
   In London, the Financial Times 30-share index was up 19.7 points
at 1,721.4 points at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index
rose 16.31 points to close at 1,188.47.
   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley said in the House of Commons
that if Jaguar's shareholders voted by a 75 percent majority to
lift a 15 percent restriction on holdings in Jaguar, the government
would drop its golden share allowing it to veto any takeover.
   Jaguar is being pursued by General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor
Co.
   The golden share and the 15 percent limit had been due to expire
at the end of 1990.
   Jaguar's shares finished at 869 pence, or around $13.73, on the
London Stock Exchange, up 122 pence, or $1.93, from Monday's close.
Trading was suspended during most of the afternoon, pending the
government's announcement.
</TEXT>
