<DOCNO> AP891031-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv01   10-31 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 01,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, Nov. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Inflation Abating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Offsetting the news about a weakening economy is
some news of another sort that has surprised some economists. They
are wondering if it is too good to persist. Inflation is declining.
   This may not be news to savvy consumers who have grabbed
bargains at retail outlets of various sorts _ in automobile
showrooms and grocery stores, for example _ in recent weeks. Their
knowledge of prices is immediate.
   For economists who rely on statistics, however, the recognition
is a bit delayed, and some of them are just now expressing their
happiness. In contrast, only a few weeks ago they had thought
inflation was gaining momentum.
   So widespread was that fear during early summer that the Federal
Reserve persisted in a tight-money policy. At one point earlier
this year there wer indications of a 6 percent to 9 percent
inflation rate.
   Over the summer, however, rates decelerated sharply, especially
for food and energy, the very items that had earlier caused alarm.
Transportation, automobile, gasoline and housing costs also fell
significantly.
   The deceleration, and in some instances actual declines in
prices, still leaves some economists a bit puzzled, wondering if
some pieces of the puzzle still need to be fitted into place. They
wait to see if it will continue.
   Allen Sinai, economist for the Boston Co., observes that
disinflation at retail is surprising in an economy that grew 2.5
percent in the second quarter and probably 3 percent-plus in the
third quarter.
   He is among those who tend to suspend judgment about the
permanence of the change, saying ``the puzzle of the rapid
disinflation could well disappear in coming months with another
acceleration.'' That said, he attempts to explain.
   First, he calls attention to a weakening manufacturing sector,
accompanied by efforts to contain costs, especially in labor. With
revenue growth slowing, Sinai says, manufacturers are forced to
stay price-competitive.
   ``This is not the usual reaction of American business,'' he
observes, contending that ``typically, prices are held high to
maintain profit margins, and labor costs are cut much later.''
   He suggests also that the economy may be weaker than the
official data suggest, compelling retailers to offer more discounts
than usual. And adding to the pressure to hold prices, he says, is
intense competition from abroad.
   Other, esoteric explanations are offered in abundance, but
probably come no nearer to explaining the surprisingly good price
performance. More important are the conclusions drawn, and Sinai
sees the possibility of even lower rates.
   Looking into 1990, he talks of an inflation rate as low as 3.5
percent to 4 percent, or about a full percentage point lower than
the surprisingly low rates that now exist.
   There is a price to pay, of course _ there always is _ and that
according to Sinai might be a significant economic downturn.
   Still, if you're going to have a slowdown, let it be accompanied
by stable or lower prices. You may recall that over the past decade
or so it was demonstrated that the economy can fall while prices
rise.
   If the country is going to have an economic slowdown, that is,
let it be accompanied by some good news too, and what better news
can there be than an extended breather from rising prices?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, Nov. 1.</NOTE>
</DOC>
