<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Borden     10-31 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Borden,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Borden Posts Loss _ As Expected _ Due to Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borden Inc., the nation's biggest dairy company,
Tuesday posted a third-quarter loss of $303.4 million due to the
costs of a major restructuring program.
   Advance word of a substantial loss, which came to $2.05 a share,
had been given in September when Borden announced it was
consolidating some operations, reconfiguring others and cutting
worldwide employment by 7,000 people, bringing its payroll down to
39,000.
   In September, Borden said it would sustain a third-quarter loss
of as much as $305 million and a loss of $47 million to $58 million
for the full year.
   The loss for the three months ended Sept. 30 reflected an
after-tax charge of $404.4 million, or $2.73 a share, to cover the
costs of the corporate realignment.
   Last year's third-quarter profit totaled $91.9 million, or 62
cents a share.
   Excluding the one-time charge, this year's third-quarter income
went up by $9 million, or 9.8 percent.
   Third-quarter revenue grew 4.7 percent to $1.96 million from
$1.87 million a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Borden had an loss of $160.5
million, or $1.08 a share, compared with income of $218 million, or
$1.48 a share, through three quarters of 1988.
   Nine-month revenue rose 7.2 percent to $5.64 billion from $5.26
billion in the first nine months of 1988.
   Besides dairy products, Borden makes well-known snack foods such
as Wise potato chips and Cracker Jack popcorn. It also makes pastas
and other foods and manufacturers Elmer's Glue and Krazy Glue.
</TEXT>
