<HEAD>Crop Futures End Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed
mostly lower Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, ending an
uneventful session of listless trading.
   Early strength in the soybean market faded during the morning
and trading in the soybean pit was nearly at a standstill in the
afternoon as players waited in vain for significant news on which
to trade.
   In a report issued late Monday, the Agriculture Department said
the U.S. corn and soybean harvests were each 79 percent complete as
of Sunday.
   In follow-up comments Tuesday, the USDA said corn harvesting was
lagging behind the normal pace in the eastern half of the Corn
Belt, while the soybean harvest had progressed more quickly than
normal except in the eastern Corn Belt and the Southeast.
   The agency said soybean harvesting was finished in South Dakota
and nearly complete in Illiois, Iowa and Nebraska.
   At the close of trading, wheat futures prices were 2 cents lower
to } cent higher with the contract for delivery in December at
$3.94} a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2\ cents lower with December
at $2.38} a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to { cent higher with
December at $1.42{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1 cent
higher with November at $5.59} a bushel.
