<DOCNO> AP891031-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Warner-Azoff     10-31 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner-Azoff,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former MCA Records Chief to Get Own Label in Joint Venture With Warner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Azoff, a music-business wizard who
revived MCA Records after deftly managing the careers of such stars
as the Eagles, Stevie Nicks, and Crosby, Stills, Nash &amp; Young, said
Tuesday that Warner Bros. Records was setting him up as head of his
own label.
   On one level, the creation of a new record concern bucks a trend
of consolidation into a handful of huge conglomerates: Island and
A&amp;M were swallowed by Dutch-owned Polygram, RCA Records by
Germany's Bertelsmann AG and Motown by MCA. CBS Records was
acquired by Sony Corp. and Japan's Fujisankei Communications also
bought a 25 percent stake in Virgin Records.
   ``Everybody has been sold and bought,'' Azoff said in a
telephone interview. ``But rock 'n' roll is a rebellious art form
by nature. And given the choice, I think a real artist would rather
be in business with an individual than a multinational.''
   On the other hand, Azoff will enjoy the advantages of Warner's
huge size _ the company has about 40 percent of the U.S. market _
and international distribution network.
   ``You can't take an artist and say, `I'm going to be so
independent that you're not going to be distributed by a major,'''
Azoff said.
   Azoff, who quit as head of MCA Records in September, said Warner
will handle manufacturing and distribution and will fully fund the
new recording and music publishing company. He will own the company
in a 50-50 partnership with Warner.
   He declined to go into details about the deal, but had estimated
recently that it would take $75 million to $100 million to launch
an independent record label.
   MCA had hoped to negotiate its own, similar deal with Azoff. MCA
president and chief operating officer Sid Sheinberg did not
immediately return a call seeking comment on the Warners deal.
   Warner already has a 50-50 deal with record and movie producer
David Geffen, distributing recordings and movies from his
independent company.
   Geffen is another powerful music-business baron for whose
Geffen-Roberts personal management firm Azoff once worked, handling
the careers of such artists as Crosby, Stills, Nash &amp; Young and
Joni Mitchell.
   ``No two deals are the same,'' Azoff said. ``But my arrangement
is similar in spirit'' to Geffen's.
   A proxy statement shows MCA paid Azoff about $5 million in
salary and stock last year. He wouldn't discuss any guarantees in
his new contract.
   Over the last two decades, Azoff's Front Line Management had
managed many acts who recorded for Warner. The company also had
funded his Full Moon Records in a joint venture and had handled
foreign distribution for MCA.
   Besides MCA and Warner, several other companies had courted him.
   ``I talked to several but all along I hoped it would be
Warner,'' Azoff said, noting that Warner has a long history of
handling distribution in close relationships with independent
labels such as Asylum, Geffen, Sire, Virgin and Island.
   ``Warner has played an instrumental role in launching all the
independents,'' he said. ``No other American company can point to
it and say that.''
   Azoff spent 16 years as a personal manager, then became head of
MCA Records in 1983. He quit in September, leaving behind a music
group where earnings had gone from an $8 million loss in 1983 to a
$60 million profit in 1988. In the same period, units shipped rose
from 35 million to 120 million.
   His as yet-unnamed recorded music and music publishing business,
to be based in Los Angeles, will open Jan. 1. He declined to talk
about what artists he might sign or staff he might hire, except to
say he would not raid MCA employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
