<FIRST>u f AM-SeaContainers     10-31 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sea Containers,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sea Containers to Resist Takeover Bid with Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sea Containers Ltd. on Tuesday announced plans to
sell ferries, ports and hotels and its entire containership fleet
in a restructuring designed to thwart a takeover bid.
   The company, whose president is American millionaire James B.
Sherwood, said it expected to raise more than 750 million British
pounds, or around $1.1 billion, from sales of its assets. Sherwood
also owns the luxury Orient Express train.
   The cash will help increase the price of Sea Containers stock
and counter a rejected 530 million-pound ($832 million) bid from a
rival ferry group, the Temple consortium. The group is comprised of
Stena, a Swedish ferry company, and Tiphook PLC, a British
container rental company.
   Sea Containers said its proposals have to be approved by the 10
million shareholders who are mainly in the United States.
   The projected sales include the profitable six Sealink ferries
between the English south coast and the Isle of Wight, eight other
ferries, the ports of Harwich near London and Heysham in northwest
England, the container fleet of 13 ships, 10 hotels, a 42 percent
stake in Isle of Man Steam Packet Co. and steamboats on Lake
Windermere in England's Lake District.
   The company said there were potential buyers for all the
businesses and that local managers might be interested in buyouts.
 
</TEXT>
