<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 1844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UnixFight     10-31 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unix Fight,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Camp Takes Early Lead in Battle Over Unix Software Standard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that includes AT&amp;T will get a jump on
the competition Wednesday when it introduces a version of Unix
base-layer software that it hopes to make into an international
computing standard.
   The introduction is a blow to plans for a rival standard that
are being formulated by International Business Machines Corp.,
Digital Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.
   Each group is trying to establish itself as the standard-setter
for Unix, an underlying layer of software that makes it easy for
different kinds of computers to run the same programs. Computer
users fear that if the two groups keep fighting there will be two
incompatible versions of Unix.
   Unix International Inc., the group that includes AT&amp;T, said it
would gather 25 senior figures from the computing world on
Wednesday in New York to endorse the introduction of its Unix
System 5 Release 4.0. The version unifies and enhances several
previous Unix releases.
   The group said shipments of the new software would begin early
next year. That gives it a jump on the rival Open Software
Foundation, which is still hammering out standards and does not
expect to begin major shipments until late in 1990.
   The two groups continued to bicker over how much support they
have.
   Unix International said its version of Unix was the successor to
the software on more than 80 percent of all currently installed
Unix systems.
   The Open Software Foundation countered that an independent
survey by International Data Corp. found that its members and
sponsors accounted for more shipments of Unix last year than the
Unix International-affiliated companies.
   AT&amp;T invented Unix but had to surrender control over its
development to Unix International to avoid abandonment of the
standard it created.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
