<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-31 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices advanced on largely
technical factors Tuesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, picked
up 22 cents to close at $19.94 per 42-gallon barrel after slipping
5 cents on Monday.
   Home heating oil futures also rose on technical factors. The
expiring November contract for heating oil rose 1 cent to 58.64
cents a gallon, and subsequent contract months also gained.
   The November contract for unleaded regular gasoline, which also
expired Tuesday, was down 0.94 cent to 52.47 cents a gallon.
Subsequent months were narrowly mixed.
   Analysts said gasoline prices fell on rumors that a large amount
of gas would be dumped onto the spot market, increasing supplies of
the fuel.
   Chris McCormack, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said the oil market was not affected by any fundamental news.
Reports of problems at a refinery in West Germany had no impact on
prices, he said.
   The impending release of weekly oil and gasoline supply figures
also did not affect trading, McCormack said.
   After the session ended, the American Petroleum Institute
announced that U.S. stockpiles of crude and gasoline increased in
the week ended Oct. 27, while heating oil supplies declined.
</TEXT>
