<HEAD>United Machinists Say No to Davis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Machinists union said Tuesday it has no
intention of joining California billionaire Marvin Davis in another
attempt to buy UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines.
   ``We've been contacted by Davis and we told him we weren't
interested,'' said James Conley, a spokesman for the International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers, which represents
United mechanics and ground-crew workers.
   The unions representing United's pilots and flight attendants
said they, too, had been contacted by Davis but declined further
comment. The Los Angeles investor apparently is seeking their
support for a possible takeover bid following the failure of a
pilot-management group to secure financing for a $6.75 billion
buyout attempt.
   Davis put UAL into play with a $5.4 billion offer in August.
Both he and the pilots have said they are exploring the possibility
of making a new bid.
   UAL's stock rose 50 cents a share to $175.50 Tuesday in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Meanwhile, a published report said the pilot-management group
has begun billing UAL for $53.7 million in fees and expenses
related to their failed bid.
   UAL declined comment on the Wall Street Journal report.
   According to the Journal story, a merger agreement reached on
Sept. 14 requires the UAL board of directors to reimburse certain
of the buyout group's expenses even though the transaction wasn't
completed.
