<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing     10-31 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Enter a Second Day In Boeing Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for Boeing Co. and the Machinists
union were back at the bargaining table for a second day Tuesday,
with the federal mediator saying both sides were trying hard to
reach a settlement.
   Meanwhile, the 57,800 striking Machinists faced the expiration
of their health care benefits at midnight Tuesday, although they
could choose to continue the benefits by paying monthly premiums of
$128 to $354 themselves.
   Neither Boeing nor the Machinists union would comment on the
substance of the talks that began Monday, although Tom Baker,
president of Machinists District Lodge 751, said negotiators were
able to talk in great detail about the issues.
   Federal mediator Douglas Hammond, who convened the talks, also
would not discuss what was said but described the negotiations as
``cordial and professional.''
   ``These folks have a problem they're trying to solve and they
recognize it,'' he said.
   Hammond has said he wants to hold negotiations daily until a
settlement is reached.
   Machinists spokesman Jack Daniels said the union has a
counterproposal to the Boeing offer which its membership
overwhelmingly rejected Oct. 3, but he did not know whether it had
been presented.
   Daniels said the mood among pickets at Boeing plants ``is a
little cheerier'' now that talks have resumed.
   The strike began Oct. 4 after the union turned down a 3-year
offer that included pay raises of 4 percent, 3 percent and 3
percent; bonuses of 8 percent of gross pay in the first year and 3
percent in the second; cost-of-living increases to virtually cover
inflation; a reduction in mandatory overtime from 200 hours to 160
hours per quarter; and higher benefits.
   Strikers include 43,300 Machinists in the Seattle area; 12,000
in Wichita, Kan.; 1,700 in Portland, Ore.; and a few hundred others
at scattered sites in California, Hawaii, Montana, Utah and other
states. Boeing has a total 164,000 workers worldwide and 106,000 in
Washington state.
   Machinists received their last paychecks Oct. 19 and the first
of their $100-a-week strike payments last Thursday. However, their
company-paid health plans remained in force through the end of
October.
   Boeing offers a variety of medical plans, but Daniels said the
cost of a medical plan for a single person would be $128.86 a
month, and for a family, $354.46. Striking workers have 60 days
after the health coverage ends to decide whether to continue the
coverage on their own.
   On Wednesday, Boeing begins ``maintable'' bargaining with its
second-largest union, the Seattle Professional Engineering
Employees Association, which represents about 30,000 engineers and
technical workers. Subcommittees of SPEEA and Boeing negotiators
have been meeting for the past week on various aspects of the
contract.
   Like the Machinists, SPEEA wants a substantial pay raise. SPEEA
officials say they believe they can work out an offer to present to
their members by mid-November, well in advance of the Dec. 1
contract expiration date.
</TEXT>
