<FIRST>u f AM-Sneakers     10-31 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sneakers,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reebok Plans $15 Million Ad Campaign for Pump Basketball Shoe Intro</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sneaker maker Reebok unveiled its new
inflatable basketball shoe called The Pump on Tuesday, and said it
planned to spend an unusually large $15 million to advertise it.
   Its main competitor, Nike Inc., said it is already shipping
similar shoes called Nike Air Pressure to retailers although it has
not created special ads for them.
   Nike and Reebok are the leaders in athletic footwear, and their
new shoes are among the highest priced _ Reebok's cost $170 a pair
and Nike's cost $175.
   Frank O'Connell, president of Reebok North America, said
basketball shoes accounted for $300 million of Reebok's $1.3
billion in domestic sales last year. He said orders have already
been placed for 50,000 pairs of the new shoes, which were shown to
retailers earlier.
   Nike is the leader in basketball shoes with about 43 percent of
that market and sold $414 million in basketball shoes last year,
spokeswoman Elizabeth Dolan said.
   Atlanta Hawks basketball star Dominique Wilkins was on hand for
the introduction of the Reebok's Pump shoes at a news conference
held on the basketball court at Hunter College in Manhattan.
   He and NBA players Byron Scott, Danny Ainge, Dennis Johnson and
Doc Rivers, and coaches Pat Riley of the Los Angeles Lakers and
Digger Phelps of Notre Dame, appear in ads debuting later this
month in which they describe in unrehearsed and often humorous
style how the shoes work.
   The high-topped shoes have an orange button on the tongue that
can be pressed to pump air into a specially-designed plastic
bladder, forming a readily-adjusted cushion around the ankle, heel
and instep to support the foot and protect it against the damaging
effects of jarring, sudden moves.
   The air is released by depressing a separate valve on the back
collar of the shoe.
   Wilkins told the news conference the shoes provide a lot of
support, enabling him to skip taping his ankles as he normally does
with other shoes before playing.
   The shoes should start arriving in stores shortly after Nov. 15
and the company plans to spend $5 million on advertising them for
the final two months of 1989 and another $10 million in the first
six months of 1990, O'Connell said.
   The Nike Air Pressure shoes are inflated with a small plastic
hand pump that is separate from the shoe.
   Ms. Dolan said that while having the pump separate from the shoe
may not be convenient, Nike's tests showed an entirely internal
pump system could not withstand the beating shoes take in
tournament-style play.
   But Nike may be turning the separate pump to its advantage. It
sells the shoes and the pump in a special carrying case.
   Ms. Dolan said that emphasizes that the shoes are made for
people who are serious about basketball. ``They wear their regular
shoes to the court and change to their basketball shoes,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891031-0287 </DOCNO>
