<FIRST>u f AM-GulfPower     10-31 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf Power,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf Power Agrees to Plead Guilty in Mysterious Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf Power Co. pleaded guilty Tuesday to federal
conspiracy charges and paid a $500,000 fine in an agreement that
blamed most of the illegal activities on an executive killed last
April in an unexplained plane crash.
   The plea bargain involving the electric utility was announced by
U.S. Attorney Robert L. Barr.
   The guilty pleas to two felonies do not affect a federal grand
jury probe into allegations of tax fraud against the Atlanta-based
parent Southern Co. and another subsidiary, Georgia Power, or an
investigation into the plane crash.
   Gulf Power, based in Pensacola, Fla., pleaded guilty to
violating a law prohibiting utilities from making political
contributions. It also pleaded guilty to conspiring to impede the
Internal Revenue Service through the creation of false or inflated
invoices.
   It was not immediately known which political campaigns were
involved in the charges.
   In a statement, Southern Co. President Edward Addison and Gulf
Power President Douglas L. McCrary said the pleas would allow Gulf
Power to avoid ``prolonged, distracting legal proceedings.''
   The investigation of Gulf Power includes the mysterious April 10
crash of a twin-engine Southern Co. plane that killed two company
pilots and Gulf Senior Vice President Jacob Horton, who was
suspected of accounting irregularities.
   Gulf Power officials have said they told Horton hours before his
death that a company committee was recommending his firing.
   Southern's statement Tuesday said violations were found in the
company's ``thorough review of actions taken or directed by''
Horton.
   A cockpit voice recorder recovered from the wreckage showed a
fire broke out in the back of the plane moments before the crash in
Pensacola.
   After the crash, an anonymous caller told police, ``You can stop
investigating Gulf Power now. We took care of that.''
   Fred Levin, a Pensacola lawyer whose firm represented Gulf
Power, was one of the last people to speak with Horton before the
crash.
   He subsequently found canaries on his doorstep, their necks
broken, an apparent gangland-style warning against ``singing'' to
authorities.
</TEXT>
