<DOCNO> AP891031-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 2103EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Camdessus-Debt     10-31 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Camdessus-Debt,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Chief Says Third World Debt Talks Take Too Long</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks with banks to reduce the $1.3 trillion
debt of Third World countries are taking too long, Managing
Director Michel Camdessus of the International Monetary Fund
complained Tuesday.
   ``Meanwhile, countries are in difficulty,'' he said.
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady outlined his ideas on
debt reduction March 10. Since then, committees representing
creditor banks have made tentative agreements with Mexico, the
Philippines and Costa Rica.
   On the most important deal, with Mexico, more than 400 banks
were due to report their decisions by midnight Tuesday to Citibank,
which heads the committee dealing with Mexican debt.
   The banks had a choice of reducing their share of Mexico's debt,
reducing its interest payments, making new loans to it, or some
combination of the three options. Their decisions will affect about
$53 billion of Mexico's debt, nearly half the total. Mexico's main
objective is to reduce the $12.8 billion it is due to pay this year
in interest on its debt.
   Camndessus defended the IMF's new policy of making new loans of
its own to the debtor countries before they come to an agreement
with private banks. A Frenchman, he is responsible to the 152
governments that own the fund, with the United States as the
biggest contributor.
   ``The banks have not understood,'' he said. ``They thought we
did not care about the arrears owed to them. We made our decision
with our eyes open. The purpose was to disburse a little first, to
show our committment and speed up the negotiations.''
   Negotiations between creditor banks and Venezuela have stalled.
Talks between the banks and Argentina, which is $4 billion behind
on its interest payments alone, were due to start in New York this
week.
   No progress can be made on the situation of Brazil, the biggest
Third World debtor, until after a government is installed after the
election scheduled for Nov. 15.
   Much of the IMF's attention is focused on Poland, in an effort
to help the new non-Communist government deal with the country's
$40 billion foreign debt, skyrocketing inflation and what one
official called its ``messy economy.'' The official, who spoke on
condition has name not be used, said the new government is trying
to move from a Communist economy to one ruled by market forces,
with inadequate structures and institutions, obsolete factories and
a totally distorted price system _ all amid the high expectations
of a country seeking more liberty.
   The IMF is trying to set up a 1-year program to prevent the
Polish economy from getting worse, in preparation for a 3-year
accord to be negotiated later.
   The official said it would take patience from the Poles and a
sustained effort by IMF donor countries.
   He pointed to the need for food aid in Poland, which he said was
extraordinary for such an industrialized country, but necessary so
that there are supplies on hand as prices are freed.
   Camdessus spoke to reporters at a meeting sponsored by the
Bretton Woods Committee, a private group concerned with the affairs
of the IMF and its sister organization, the World Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
