<FIRST>r f BC-Stateswest-Mesa     10-31 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Stateswest-Mesa,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stateswest Pulls Out Offer for Mesa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stateswest Airlines Inc. has withdrawn its offer
to buy Mesa Airlines Inc. because it did not receive a response to
the offer by a self-imposed deadline Tuesday, the company announced.
   Last week, Phoenix-based Stateswest proposed to the board of
directors of Mesa, based in Farmington, N.M., that it acquire 100
percent of Mesa's common stock for $7 a share cash and one share of
a new series of 6 percent convertible preferred stock of Stateswest.
   The chairman of Stateswest, Rudy R. Miller, said in a statement
that last week's offer was essentially a repeat of an earlier
offer, so Mesa had plenty of time to review the proposal. Miller
said that Mesa's refusal to act amounted to a rejection.
   Both airlines are regional carriers that serve the Southwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
